s)\n| votes = 14,995\n| percentage = 22.78\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Shelley Kais\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 5,103\n| percentage = 7.75\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Write-in\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 235\n| percentage = 0.36\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 65,825\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin|title=[[United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2014#District 2|Arizona's 2nd congressional district election, 2014]]}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Republican Party (United States)|candidate='''Martha McSally'''|votes='''109,704|percentage='''50.01%|change=+0.44%}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=Democratic Party (United States)|candidate=[[Ron Barber]] (incumbent)|votes=109,543|percentage=49.94%|change=-0.47%}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|party=N/A|candidate=Write-ins|votes=104|percentage=0.05%|change=+0.03%}}\n{{Election box turnout|votes=219,351|percentage=|change=}}\n{{Election box gain with party link\n  |winner     = Republican Party (United States)\n  |loser      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |swing      =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin|title=[[United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2016#District 2|Arizona's 2nd congressional district election, 2016]]}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = '''Martha McSally''' (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 150,103\n  |percentage = 56.7%\n  |change     = +6.89%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Matt Heinz\n  |votes      = 114,401\n  |percentage = 43.4%\n  |change     = -6.33%\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  |votes      = 264,504\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link\n  |winner     = Republican Party (United States)\n  |loser      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = [[United States Senate elections in Arizona, 2018]] (Republican primary, August 28, 2018)\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Martha McSally\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 357,626\n| percentage = 54.6%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate  = Kelli Ward\n| votes = 180,926\n| percentage = 27.6%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate  = Joe Arpaio\n| votes = 116,555\n| percentage = 17.8%%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate  = Nicholas Glenn (write-in)\n| votes = 121\n| percentage = 0.0%%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate  = William Gonzales (write-in)\n| votes = 70\n| percentage = 0.0%\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 655,298\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin|title=[[United States Senate election in Arizona, 2018]]}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Kyrsten Sinema]]\n  |votes      = 1,191,100\n  |percentage = 49.97%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Martha McSally\n  |votes      = 1,135,200\n  |percentage = 47.62%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  |party      = Green Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Angela Green (withdrawn)\n  |votes      = 57,442\n  |percentage = 2.41%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n  |votes      = 2,383,742\n  |percentage = 100%\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n  |winner    = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |loser     = Republican Party (United States)\n  |swing     = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nMcSally was married to Air Force officer Donald Frederick Henry from 1997 to 1999; the marriage was annulled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agave.cosc.pima.gov/PublicDocs/|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|website=Arizona Superior Court in Pima County|title=Case L5373439|date=March 22, 1997|access-date=October 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118025939/http://www.agave.cosc.pima.gov/PublicDocs/|archive-date=November 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Powers Hannley|first=Pamela|title='Sham' Marriage Allegations Arise Against Arizona Congressional Candidate Col. Martha McSally|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/pamela-powers-hannley/sham-marriage-allegations_b_2036319.html|accessdate=November 4, 2012|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=October 31, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104022053/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/pamela-powers-hannley/sham-marriage-allegations_b_2036319.html|archive-date=November 4, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> She is a triathlete.<ref name=\"people\" /> McSally's rescue [[Golden Retriever]], Boomer, frequently appears alongside her at events and in videos.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2018/11/13/martha-mcsallys-dog-is-leader-america-needs/ Martha McSally's dog is the leader America needs]. [[The Washington Post]]. November 13, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn April 2018 a Tucson man was sentenced to 15 months in prison for threatening to assault and kill McSally.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Prendergast|first1=Curt|title=Tucson man gets 15 months in prison for threatening U.S. Rep. Martha McSally|url=http://tucson.com/news/local/tucson-man-gets-months-in-prison-for-threatening-u-s/article_e51e85b9-fa60-53da-928e-f86f5c1656df.html|accessdate=April 19, 2018|publisher=Arizona Daily Star|date=April 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419074432/http://tucson.com/news/local/tucson-man-gets-months-in-prison-for-threatening-u-s/article_e51e85b9-fa60-53da-928e-f86f5c1656df.html|archive-date=April 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2019, during a hearing on [[Sexual assault in the United States military|Sexual Assault and Misconduct in the Military]] at the [[United States Senate Armed Services Subcommittee on Personnel|Armed Services Subcommittee on Personnel]], McSally informed her colleagues that she had been raped by a superior officer while serving in the Air Force: {{cquote|I also am a military sexual assault survivor, but unlike so many brave survivors, I didn't report being sexually assaulted. Like so many women and men, I didn't trust the system at the time. I blamed myself. I was ashamed and confused. I thought I was strong but felt powerless. The perpetrators abused their position of power in profound ways. In one case I was preyed upon and raped by a superior officer.}} McSally did not name the officer, but said she shares the disgust at the failures of the military system and many commanders to address sexual violence. Her revelation came over a month after fellow Senator [[Joni Ernst]] revealed that she was raped while in college.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Re|first1=Gregg|title=Arizona GOP Sen. Martha McSally says she was 'preyed upon and then raped' in Air Force by superior officer|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/arizona-gop-sen-martha-mcsally-says-she-was-raped-in-air-force-by-a-superior-officer|accessdate=March 6, 2019|publisher=FoxNews.com|date=March 6, 2019|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* ''[[Final Report of the Task Force on Combating Terrorist and Foreign Fighter Travel]]''\n* [[Women in the United States House of Representatives]]\n* [[Women in the United States Senate]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bergquist, Carl, \"1st Air Force female pilot in combat reflects on career\", ''Aerotech News and Review'', December 22, 2006\n* SeniorWomen.com articles by author David Westheimer (USAF Reserve Lt. Col.) \"Women in Blue\" at [http://www.seniorwomen.com/articles/david/articlesDavidAirForce.html Senior Women Web > Articles > David Westheimer],[http://www.seniorwomen.com/articles/david/articlesDavidAirForceII.html Senior Women Web > Articles > David Westheimer] & [http://www.seniorwomen.com/articles/david/articlesDavidMartha.html Senior Women Web > Articles > David Westheimer]\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Martha McSally}}\n* [http://www.mcsally.senate.gov/ U.S. Senator Martha McSally] official U.S. Senate website\n* [https://mcsallyforsenate.com/ Campaign] official website\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Arizona/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Martha_McSally_%5BR-2%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|marthamcsally}}\n* {{CongLinks |congbio=M001197 |votesmart=137299 |fec=S8AZ00221 |congress=martha-mcsally/M001197}}\n* [http://www.c-span.org/video/?40217-1/women-combat Women in Combat, policy change briefing by SecDef Les Aspin, April 28, 1993] (C-SPAN video, forward to 33 minute point)\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y8b837yt0hU Martha McSally speaking on campaign trail in Sierra Vista March 2012]\n* [http://www.ctie.monash.edu.au/hargrave/mcsally.html Profile], ctie.monash.edu.au; accessed November 8, 2014\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state    = Arizona\n|district = 2\n|before   = [[Ron Barber]]\n|after    = [[Ann Kirkpatrick]]\n|years    = 2015\u20132019}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeff Flake]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of United States Senators from Arizona|U.S. Senator]] from [[Arizona]]}}<br />([[Classes of United States Senators|Class 1]])|years=[[United States Senate election in Arizona, 2018|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jon Kyl]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of United States Senators from Arizona|U.S. Senator (Class 3) from Arizona]]|years=2019\u2013present|alongside=[[Kyrsten Sinema]]}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kevin Cramer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States Senate|United States Senators by seniority]]|years=94th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jacky Rosen]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current U.S. Senators}}\n{{Current Arizona statewide political officials}}\n{{ArizonaUSRepresentatives}}\n{{USSenAZ}}\n{{AZ-FedRep}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses=114th\u2013116th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Arizona]]}}\n{{USCongRep/AZ/114}}\n{{USCongRep/AZ/115}}\n{{USCongRep/AZ/116}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Rhode Island Women's Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McSally, Martha Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:American air force personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Appointed United States senators]]\n[[Category:Arizona Republicans]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2012 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Female members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Female United States senators]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Warwick, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force colonels]]\n[[Category:Women in Arizona politics]]\n[[Category:Women in the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Air Force]]\n[[Category:Republican Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n", "name_user": "RedHotPear", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAppointment:grammar, formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martha_McSally"}
{"title_page": "DMC DeLorean", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|1980s automobile}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = DMC DeLorean\n| image = Delorean DMC-12 side.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = 1983 DeLorean\n| manufacturer = [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC)<br />[[Bloomfield_Hills,_Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], Michigan, US\n| production = 9,080<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2015/12/19/delorean-book/77623204/|title=DeLoreans still ply the roads -- and memories|url-status=live}}</ref> (disputed)\n| model_years = 1981\u20131983\n| assembly = DeLorean Motor Cars, Ltd. (DMCL) [[Dunmurry]], [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland\n| designer = [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Italdesign]]<ref>https://www.cnn.com/style/article/giorgetto-giugiaro-interview/index.html</ref>\n| class = Sports car\n| body_style = 2-door coup\u00e9\n| related = \n| layout = Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| engine = {{convert|2.85|L|cuin|0|abbr=on}} [[V6 PRV engine]] ''ZMJ-159''<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| powerout = {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|207|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| transmission = 5-speed manual<br/>3-speed automatic<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2413|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\">{{Cite book|title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946\u20131975|publisher= Krause|isbn=0-87341-027-0|editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first= John A.}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4267|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| width = {{convert|1988|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| height = {{convert|1140|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors closed<br/>{{convert|1962|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors open<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date = 2014| pages = 16}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|1233|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| doors = Gullwing doors\n}}\n\nThe '''DMC DeLorean''' (often referred to simply as the \"'''DeLorean'''\", as it was the only model ever produced by the company) is a sports car manufactured by [[John DeLorean]]'s [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC) for the American market from 1981 to 1983. The car was designed by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] and stood out for its [[gull-wing door]]s and brushed stainless-steel outer body panels, as well as an innovative fiberglass body structure with a steel backbone chassis. It became widely known for its disappointing lack of power and performance, which did not match the expectations created by its looks and price tag, but it became iconic for its appearances as the [[DeLorean time machine|time machine]] in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' media franchise]] after 1985.\n\nThroughout production, the car was generally unchanged, although minor modifications were made to such parts as the hood and wheels. The first production car was completed on January 21, 1981. About 9,000 DeLoreans were made before production halted in late December 1982 shortly after DMC had filed for bankruptcy.\n\n==History==\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 (9979) (cropped).jpg|thumb|A DeLorean with the gull-wing doors closed]]\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 with doors open.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean from the front with the gull-wing doors open]]\nIn October 1976, the first prototype DeLorean was completed by American automotive chief engineer William T. Collins, formerly chief engineer at [[Pontiac]].  Originally, the car was intended to have a centrally-mounted [[Wankel engine|Wankel rotary engine]].  The engine selection was reconsidered when [[Comotor]] production ended, and the favored engine became the [[Ford Cologne V6 engine]].  Eventually the French/Swedish [[fuel injection|fuel-injected]] [[V6 PRV engine]] ([[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]]) was selected.  Also the engine location moved from the mid-engined location in the prototype to a rear-engined installation in the production car.  The [[chassis]] was initially planned to be produced from a new and untested manufacturing technology known as elastic reservoir moulding (ERM), which would lighten the car while presumably lowering its production costs.  This new technology, for which DeLorean had purchased patent rights, was eventually found to be unsuitable.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nThese and other changes to the original concept led to considerable schedule pressures.  The entire car was deemed to require almost complete re-engineering, which was turned over to engineer [[Colin Chapman]], founder of [[Lotus Cars]].  Chapman replaced most of the unproven material and manufacturing techniques with those then employed by Lotus, like the steel backbone chassis.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003| pages = 71\u201375}}</ref>\n\nThe first prototype appeared in October 1976 and was known as the DSV-1, or DeLorean Safety Vehicle.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 23}}</ref> As development continued, the model was referred to as the DSV-12<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 28}}</ref> and later the DMC-12 since DMC was targeting a list price of US$12,000 ({{Inflation|US|12000|1976|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) at release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |title=DeLorean DMC-12 |access-date=February 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204065904/https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |archive-date=February 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html How an immigrant mechanic used $5 million to bring DeLoreans back to the future] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014534/https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html |date=February 4, 2019 }} Zack Guzman. 3:52 PM ET Wed, November 9, 2016</ref>\n\nIn an interview with James Espey of the new incarnation of the DeLorean Motor Company of [[Texas]], a drawing surfaced showing that the car originally had the potential to be named \"Z Tavio\".  John DeLorean's middle name and his son's first name were both Zachary, while Tavio was his father's name and his son's middle name.  Due to only sporadic documentation, there is little more that is currently known about the Z Tavio name and why it was ultimately rejected in favor of the DeLorean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |title=Interview with James Espy of DMCH |publisher=Myride.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908094456/http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |archive-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter several delays and cost overruns, production finally began in late 1980. Around this time DMC officially dropped the name DMC-12 on its now US$25,000 ({{Inflation|US|25000|1981|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) car in favor of the model name DeLorean. The DeLorean sports car, as it was described in advertisements, began production in December 1980 with the first production car rolling off the assembly line on January 21, 1981.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lily Rothman |url=http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |title=DeLorean Auto History: What Happened to the Company |publisher=Time |date=January 21, 2016 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423164413/http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |title=Almanac: The DeLorean car |publisher=CBS News |date=January 21, 2018 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515122627/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |archive-date=May 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean Motor Company was placed into receivership in February 1982 and filed [[bankruptcy]] in October 1982<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/26/business/delorean-motor-files-bankruptcy.html</ref>.  Approximately 100 partially assembled DeLoreans on the production line were completed by [[Big Lots|Consolidated International]].  About 9,000 cars were produced in total.  The remaining parts from the factory stock, the parts from the US Warranty Parts Center, as well as parts from the original suppliers that had not yet been delivered to the factory were all shipped to [[Columbus, Ohio]] in 1983\u201384.  A company called KAPAC sold these parts to retail and [[wholesaling|wholesale]] customers by mail order.  In 1997, DeLorean Motor Company of Texas acquired this inventory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/q&a.asp#whereparts |title=DeLorean Motor Company FAQ |publisher=Delorean.com |date=November 6, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121215155/http://delorean.com/q%26a.asp |archivedate=November 21, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Sales and production==\n===Sales===\nPrior to the release of the DeLorean, there was a waiting list of anxious buyers, many of whom paid over [[List_price#Automobiles/motorcars|MSRP]], however that exuberance subsided very quickly and production output soon far exceeded sales volume.  October 1981 was the highest month of sales for DMC with 720 vehicles sold but by December, the US was falling into recession and interest rates were rising which further negatively impacted sales.  Despite this, instead of reducing production, John DeLorean doubled production output, further adding to the backlog of unsold cars.   By the end of 1981, DMC had produced 7,500 cars but had only sold 3,000.  By this point, DMC was in a financial hardship and in February 1982, DMC was placed into receivership. <ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 130}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1982, unsold 1981 model year cars were \u201cpriced for immediate clearance\u201d in hopes to make room for the more expensive 1982 model year cars.  In March, telegrams were sent to all 343 dealerships requesting each buy six cars to help save the company;  none of the dealers responded with a sales order.  By this point, dealers were sitting on unsold inventory as were the quality assurance centers and hundreds more sitting on the  docks in [[Long Beach]], California.  By the end of May 1982, production at the factory was shut down.  Another attempt in July 1982 was made to revive sales by offering discounts to dealerships and offering a 5-year/{{convert|50000|mi|adj=on}} warranty with the first year or {{convert|12000|mi|adj=on}} portion secured by a major insurance carrier but this was not successful. \n\nBruce McWilliams, VP of Marketing for DMC and later acting President for DMC America, after resigning his position said, \u201cThe car could never be sold in the numbers John DeLorean predicted\u2026\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 133-141}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\nProduction information was lost or scattered upon the [[DeLorean Motor Company#Downturn and bankruptcy|shutdown of DMC]] and production figures for the DeLorean have never been verified based on official factory records.  Despite some unexplained VIN gaps, based upon VIN information, owners have been able to piece together the approximate quantity of DeLoreans produced.\n\nIn February 1982, DMC was placed into [[receivership]] and the factory continued to operate at a reduced production rate until the end of May.  When Consolidated International acquired the unsold and partially assembled cars in November 1982, it brought back workers to complete the cars remaining on the assembly line. It was decided to make the remaining completed 1982 model year cars into 1983 models. The remaining cars VINs were re-VINed into 1983 cars by taking the original VIN number and adding 5000 to it and changing the \"CD\" in the middle of the VIN to \"DD\" thus making a 1983 model.\n\nFor the 1981 model year, there were 6,700 DeLoreans produced (VIN 500-7199).  For the 1982 model year, there were 1,999 DeLoreans produced (VIN 10001-11999).  For the 1983 model year, there were 276 DeLoreans (VIN 17000-17170 and 20001-20105) bringing the total estimated production to 8,975 cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 115-117}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2007, about 6,500 DeLorean cars were thought to still exist.<ref>{{cite news |first= Martin |last= Zimmerman |url= https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |title= For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |accessdate= January 7, 2013 |work= Los Angeles Times |date= July 28, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130228154343/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |archive-date= February 28, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\nThe DeLorean features a number of unusual construction details, including gull-wing doors, unpainted [[stainless-steel]] body panels, and a rear-mounted engine.\n\n===Body===\n[[File:De Lorean DMC-12 at Wollaton Park, Nottingham, England.jpg|thumb|The gull-wing doors on the DeLorean were a distinctive feature.]]\nThe body design of the DeLorean was a product of [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] of [[Italdesign Giugiaro|Ital Design]] and is panelled in brushed [[AISI steel grades#Stainless steel|SS304]] stainless steel. Except for three cars plated in 24-karat gold, all DeLoreans left the factory uncovered by paint or clearcoat.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Body Finish and Composition from Owners Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110228223225/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |archive-date= February 28, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Painted DeLoreans do exist, although these were all painted after the cars were purchased from the factory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |title=DeLorean Prototype & Production |publisher=AACA Museum |date= |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606022652/https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In order to train the workforce, a small number of DeLoreans were produced without the costly stainless steel panels and are referred to as \"black cars\" or [[Development_mule|mules]] in reference to their black fiberglass bodies. These cars were never intended to be sold.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |title=DeLorean - DeLorean DMC-12 Technical (1981-1982) |publisher=Motor-car.net |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425053807/https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSmall scratches in the stainless-steel body panels can be removed with a non-metallic scouring pad (since metal pads can leave iron particles embedded in the stainless steel, which can give the appearance of the stainless \"rusting\"), or even sandpaper.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Care & Feeding: Stainless Steel Body Maintenance |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110515142238/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |archive-date= May 15, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> The stainless-steel panels are fixed to a [[fiberglass]] underbody. The underbody is affixed to a steel double-Y frame chassis, inspired by the [[Lotus Esprit]] platform.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nThe unpainted stainless body creates challenges during [[Automotive restoration|restoration]] of the cars. In traditional automotive body repair, the panel is repaired to be as original (\"straight\") as possible, and imperfections are sculpted back to form with polyester body filler like [[Bondo (putty)|Bondo]] or lead (body [[solder]]). This poses no problem (aside from originality) with most cars, as the filler will be hidden by the car's paint (for example, most new cars have filler hiding the seam where the roof meets the [[quarter panel]]). With an unpainted stainless body, the stainless steel must be reworked to exactly the original shape, contour, and grain, which is a tremendously difficult job on regular steel (a dented or bent panel is stretched, and a shrinking hammer or other techniques must be used to unstretch the metal) and even more difficult with stainless due to its tendency to [[Work hardening|work-harden]]. Furthermore, it is exceedingly difficult to paint stainless steel due to difficulties with paint adhesion. DeLorean envisioned that damaged panels would simply be replaced rather than repaired.\n\nAnother distinctive feature of the DeLorean is its [[gull-wing door]]s. The common problem of supporting the weight of gull-wing doors was solved by other manufacturers with lightweight doors in the [[Mercedes-Benz 300SL]] and a hydraulic pump in the [[Bricklin SV-1]], although these designs had structural or convenience disadvantages. The DeLorean features heavy doors supported by [[Cryogenics|cryogenically]] preset [[Torsion bar suspension|torsion bars]] and gas-charged [[strut]]s.<ref>{{US patent|4,378,658}}</ref> These torsion bars were developed by [[Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation|Grumman Aerospace]] (and built by Unbrako in the UK, a division of SPS Technologies of Jenkintown, Pennsylvania, US) to withstand the stresses of supporting the doors.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Exotic Technology |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511091013/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |archive-date= May 11, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Much like the [[scissor doors|doors]] fitted to the [[Lamborghini Countach]], the DeLorean doors featured small cutout windows, because full-sized windows would not be fully retractable within the short door panels. Additionally, the doors featured red and amber \"safety\" lights around the perimeter. These lights illuminated when the door was open and could be seen from the front, rear or side of the vehicle at night or in low-light situations.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Vehicle Dimensions from Technical Manual, Workshop Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090401070948/http://dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |archive-date= April 1, 2009 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Door Design |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100914111250/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |archive-date= September 14, 2010 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Engine and drivetrain===\nThe [[engine]] is a [[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]] ([[V6 PRV engine|PRV]]) {{cvt|2.85|L|cuin|0}} [[V6 engine|V6]], rated at {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm and [[torque]] of {{convert|153|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 2750 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|website=carfolio.com|title=1981 De Lorean DMC-12 specifications|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614071722/https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1982/587540/de_lorean_dmc-12.html|website=automobile-catalog.com|title=1982 De Lorean DMC-12 specs|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> that was designed and built under special contract with the [[DeLorean Motor Company]]. These PRVs were a development of the 2.7-litre V6 in the [[Renault 30]] and were built in the PRV Factory in [[Douvrin]], Northern France. The 5-speed [[manual transmission]], also designed by PRV, was built at the [[Renault]] facility near [[Caen]] in [[Normandy]]. The engines and [[gearbox]]es were shipped weekly by sea from the PRV factories to the DMC factory.\n\n===Suspension===\nThe [[suspension (vehicle)|suspension]] is a four-wheel [[independent suspension]], [[coil spring]]s, and telescopic [[shock absorbers]]. The front suspension uses [[Double wishbone suspension|double wishbones]], while the rear is a [[Multi-link suspension|multi-link]] setup.\n\nWhen the DeLorean first arrived in the US, the car had a higher than expected wheel gap in the front suspension.  The nose-high appearance is the result of poor quality coil springs.  Despite having significantly less weight in the front, the front and rear springs had the same spring rate and also used lower quality steel which resulted in the nose-high look.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 83}}</ref>  Some people have erroneously cited a last minute change in US bumper height requirements led DMC to raise the vehicle just prior to delivery, however this is not true.  Design drawings clearly show that the design met [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration|NHTSA]] minimum bumper and headlight heights of the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/Bumper/Index.html|title=Bumper Q&A's|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003151011/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/bumper/index.html|archive-date=October 3, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|title=DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 49 CFR Part 571, [Docket No. 01-8885; Notice 01], RIN 2127-AH81, Glare from headlamps and other Front Mounted Lamps, Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard No. 108; Lamps, Reflective Devices, and Associated Equipment|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927155258/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|archive-date=September 27, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Many owners have subsequently replaced or modified the front springs to return the front height to the original design specification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|title=Improving handling and lowering the DeLorean - DeLorean Motor Company|author=|date=|website=support.delorean.com|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621093431/http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSteering is [[rack and pinion]], with an overall [[steering ratio]] of 14.9:1, giving 2.65 turns lock-to-lock and a {{convert|35|ft|m|adj=on}} turning circle. DeLoreans are fitted with [[alloy|cast alloy]] wheels, measuring {{convert|14|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|6|in|mm}} wide on the front and {{convert|15|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|8|in|mm}} wide on the rear. These were fitted with [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]] NCT steel-belted radial tires. The DeLorean is a [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|rear-engine vehicle]] with a 35%\u201365% front\u2013rear weight distribution.<ref>{{cite web|first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_weight.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Weight and Balance from Technical manual |publisher=Dmcnews.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean features power-assisted [[disc brake]]s on all wheels, with {{convert|10|in|mm|adj=on}} rotors front and {{convert|10.5|in|mm|adj=on}} rear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|title=1981 DeLorean-17|author=|date=|website=oldcarbrochures.org|access-date=May 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524222200/http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|archive-date=May 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAt the time of release, the automotive press was generally complimentary towards the DeLorean.  [[Motor Trend]]<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 128\u2013129}}</ref>, [[Car and Driver]] <ref>https://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/comparison-test/a15144078/de-lorean-vs-chevy-corvette-datsun-280-zx-ferrari-308gts-porsche-911-comparison-test/</ref> and [[Road_%26_Track|Road & Track]]<ref>https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/</ref> had mostly positive remarks about the car.  All of them noted disappointing performance, especially those that performed comparative tests against other vehicles but were otherwise impressed with the car noting commendable gas mileage and most of them noting that the DeLorean is more of a [[grand tourer|GT]] car rather than a sports car or racecar.\n\nHowever, more recent reviews of the car have been much more harsh.  In 2017, [[Time Magazine]] included the DeLorean on its list of 50 worst cars of all time.<ref>https://time.com/4723114/50-worst-cars-of-all-time/</ref>  In his book ''Naff Motors: 101 Automotive Lemons'', Tony Davis described the build quality as \"woeful\".  ''Top Gear'' writer Richard Porter included it in his book ''Crap Cars'', calling it \"dismal\",<ref name = \"Porter\">{{cite book|last=Porter |first=Richard |title=Crap Cars |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=2005 |isbn= |page=}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nDMC's comparison literature noted that the DeLorean could achieve {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|}} in 8.8 seconds, when equipped with a manual transmission. When equipped with an automatic transmission, the DeLorean would accelerate from {{convert|0|to|60|mph|}} in 10.5 seconds as tested by ''Road & Track'' magazine. The car's top speed is {{convert|109|mph|0}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|title=1982 DeLorean DMC-12: The Vintage Road & Track Test|date=October 21, 2015|work=Road & Track|publisher=|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803211950/http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|archive-date=August 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Road and Track called the car: \".. not quick for a sports/GT car in this price category ..\".\n\n==Problems and issues==\nDeLoreans, early production models in particular, suffered from poor build quality as well as mechanical issues with the vehicle.  Early production cars needed as much as 140-200 hours of work at DMC Quality Assurance Centers prior to being shipped to dealerships for delivery. DMC eventually sent 30 factory workers to the quality centers in the US to learn about the issues and how to fix them.  Quality issues did improve over time and by 1982 many of the quality issues had been resolved.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 83 - 84}}</ref>\n\nA total of four recalls were issued by the factory to correct issues such as a sticking throttle, front suspension issues and an inertia switch. <ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 108\u2013109}}</ref>\n\nOther quality issues that plagued the car included other issues surrounding the front suspension, clutch pedal adjustment (or lack thereof), brake rotors, instruments; in particular the [[speedometer]], power door locks and weak alternators.  Many early DeLoreans were delivered with an incorrect alignment with the toe-in incorrectly set leading to premature tire wear. \n\nIn addition, many dealers were reluctant to perform warranty work on DeLoreans since DMC owed them money for past warranty claims that were still unpaid.  Some dealerships were not able to perform repair work properly as DMC never issued a proper service manual.  The lack of quality service at dealerships was a point of frustration for many DeLorean owners at the time, particularly those who paid over sticker price to purchase one of the first cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 111\u2013112}}</ref>\n\n==Pricing and options==\n[[File:1982 De Lorean DMC12 coupe (8453073488).jpg|thumb|1982 DeLorean grey interior]]\n[[File:1981 DeLorean DMC 12 -- Virginia Museum of Transportation - 49374820477.jpg|thumb|1981 DeLorean with optional accent stripe]]\nUpon release in 1981, a DeLorean had a suggested retail price of US$25,000 ($650 more when equipped with an [[automatic transmission]]); this is equivalent to approximately US${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|25000|1981}}}} in {{inflation-year|US}}.{{inflation-fn|US}}. MSRP would increase in 1982 to $29,825<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|title=1982 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616231331/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and again in 1983 to $34,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|title=1983 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015225/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> At the outset, there were extensive waiting lists of people willing to pay up to $10,000 above the list price; however, after the collapse of the DeLorean Motor Company, unsold cars could be purchased for less than the retail price.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_sales.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Sales and Dealer Experiences}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean was only available with two factory options; a no-cost [[manual transmission]] or automatic transmission and the choice of a grey or black interior (grey interior became available mid 1981 model year).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |title=one of one! factory burgundy interior delorean |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905044903/https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The standard feature list included stainless-steel body panels; gull-wing doors with cryogenically treated torsion bars; leather seats; [[air conditioning]]; an AM/FM [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] [[stereo system]]; [[power window]]s, [[power door locks|locks]] and [[Power side-view mirror|mirrors]]; a tilt and telescopic [[steering wheel]]; tinted glass; body side moldings; intermittent/constant windshield wipers; and an electric rear-window defogger. Several dealer options were available, including a car cover; [[Sheepskin seat cover|sheepskin]] seat covers; floor mats; car care cleaning kit; black textured accent stripes; grey scotch-cal accent stripes; a luggage rack and a ski-rack adapter.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Dealer Installed Accessories |date= June 20, 1981 |access-date= January 27, 2005 |archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/6HxeVWMtL?url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |archive-date= July 8, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |title= DeLorean Owners Association: DeLorean specifications table |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980214030500/http://delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |archivedate=February 14, 1998}}</ref>\n{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=390 | image1=DMC Sticker.jpg |width1=199 |height1=260 |alt1=1982 DMC-12 window sticker |image2=DMC12 clearance.jpg |width2=200 |height2=260 |alt2=DeLorean clearance advertisement |footer_align=center |footer=1982 window sticker & 1983 DeLorean clearance advertisement}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Production changes==\nAlthough there were no typical yearly updates to the DeLorean, several changes were made to the DeLorean during production.<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\"/>  Instead of making changes at the end of the model year, DMC implemented changes mid-production. This resulted in no clear distinction between the 1981, 1982, and 1983 model years, but with subtle changes taking place almost continuously throughout the life cycle of the DeLorean.\n\n===Hood styles===\nThe original [[hood (vehicle)|hood]] of the DeLorean had [[Groove (machining)|grooves]] running down both sides. It included a tank flap to simplify [[Filling station|fuel filling]]. These cars typically had a locking cap to prevent fuel theft by [[siphon]]ing. In August 1981, the hood flap was removed from the hood of the cars (although the hood creases remained). This style was retained well into 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |title=The DeLorean |publisher=Babb Technology |date=April 8, 2008 |accessdate=November 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Based on production numbers for all three years, this hood style is probably the most common. After the supply of locking caps was exhausted, the company switched to a non-locking version (resulting in at least 500 cars with no flap, but with locking caps). The final styling for the hood included the addition of a DeLorean name badge and the removal of the grooves, resulting in a completely flat hood. According to senior personnel who worked at the Dunmurry factory, initial elimination of flapped hoods has a simple if unglamorous explanation; Chuck Benington, managing director, did not like the design.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nick Sutton, Purchasing Manager, Dunmurry factory|url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132250/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|archive-date=April 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=600 |image1=Early 1981 De Lorean hood.jpg |width1=387 |height1=142 |alt1=Early 1981 hood |image2=1983 De Lorean hood.jpg |width2=414 |height2=162 |alt2=1983 hood |footer_align=center |footer=Side-by-side comparison of an early 1981 hood (left) vs. a later model 1983 hood (right)}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Other changes===\nJohn DeLorean was {{height|ft=6|in=4}} tall, and he designed the car to comfortably fit someone of his stature.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|title= The DeLorean's Time Leap|author= Claire Suddath|publisher= [[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date= April 19, 2012|access-date= July 14, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140706011419/http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|archive-date= July 6, 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> For shorter people, the addition of a pull strap made closing the doors much easier from the inside. These attach to the existing door handle. Late-model 1981 cars, and all cars from 1982 and 1983, have doors with integrated pull straps.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\">{{cite web|url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|title=DeLorean \u2013 The Car: Production Changes|work=babbtechnology.com|access-date=August 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe side [[bolster]]ing in the DeLorean was originally separate from the main interior pieces. In cars with this construction, is a tendency to place pressure on this piece when entering and exiting the vehicle, which eventually causes the bolstering to separate from the trim panel. To solve this problem, cars built in and after late 1981 have one solid trim piece with the bolster permanently attached.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nAs an addition to later cars, a foot rest, or [[dead pedal]], was added to help prevent [[fatigue (physical)|fatigue]] while driving. This is one of the few changes that is directly tied to a model year. These were built into only a few of the late-1981 vehicles and were added to all cars starting with 1982 production.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\"/>\n\nAlthough the styling of the DeLorean's wheels remained unchanged, the wheels of early-model 1981 vehicles were painted grey. These wheels sported matching grey centre caps with an embossed DMC logo. Early into the 1981 production run, these were changed to a polished silver look, with a contrasting black center cap. The embossed logo on the center caps was painted silver to add contrast.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the DeLorean came with an AM/FM stereo radio with cassette made by Craig. Since the Craig radio did not have a built-in clock, one was installed in front of the [[gear shift]] on the console. DeLorean switched to an ASI stereo in the middle of the 1982 production run. Since the ASI radio featured an on-board clock, the clock on the console was removed at the same time.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 44\u201345}}</ref>\n\nThe first 2,200 cars produced used a windshield-embedded [[antenna (radio)|antenna]]. This type of antenna proved to be unsuitable with poor radio reception. Oftentimes the radio would continually \"seek\", attempting to find a signal. A standard whip antenna, which was later changed to a manually retractable antenna, was added to the outside of the front right fender. While improving radio reception, this resulted in a hole in the stainless steel, and an unsightly antenna. As a result, the antenna was again moved. The final antenna was an automatic retractable version installed under the rear induction grill behind the rear driver's-side window.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 28\u201329}}</ref>\n\nThe small [[visor|sun visors]] on the DeLorean have [[Polyvinyl chloride|vinyl]] on one side and headliner [[Textile|fabric]] on the other side. Originally these were installed such that the headliner side would be on the bottom when not in use. Later on in 1981, they were reversed so that the vinyl side would be on the bottom.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 40}}</ref>\n\nThe original 80 amp Ducellier [[Alternator (auto)|alternator]] supplied with the early-production DeLoreans could not provide enough [[electric current|current]] to supply the car when all lights and electrical options were on; as a result, the [[battery (electricity)|battery]] would gradually discharge, leaving the driver stranded on the road. Beginning with cars built in late 1981, DeLoreans were fitted from the factory with a 90 amp [[Motorola]] alternator, which solved this problem. Additional battery drainage problems were caused by faulty or improperly adjusted door jamb switches. This switch activated the \"safety\" lights located around the door perimeter when it was open. When the door was closed, the door seals prevented the light from being seen. Due to the faulty switches the lights remained on, draining the battery. This happened to DeLorean owner [[Johnny Carson]] shortly after he was presented with the vehicle.\n\n<gallery>\n|align=\n\nFile:De Lorean add-on Pull strap.jpg|Early pull strap\nFile:Delorean dmc-12 later style side bolster.jpg|Later-style one-piece bolster\nFile:mid 1981 De Lorean silver wheel.JPG|Mid-1981 silver wheel\n</gallery>\n\n==Notable and unique DeLoreans==\n===Wooden Mock-up===\n[[File:Ulster Transport Museum, Cultra, DMC-12 Coupe clay model of Italdesign, Moncalieri, Turin for the De Lorean Company, 1975 04.jpg|thumb|DMC-12 Coupe model]]\nIn March 1975, DMC entered into a contract with Ital Design to have Giorgetto Giugiaro design the DeLorean Sports Car.  John DeLorean and Bill Collins approved one of the many designs and subsequently the styling mock-up that was made from \u201cepo-wood\u201d was scheduled to be shipped to the DMC office in Michigan on July 31, 1975.  This mockup would serve as the platform in which the prototype was developed.\n\nThe original full-size epowood DeLorean styling model which was modified in the first quarter of 1979 to reflect the refreshed design used in production, was donated to the [[Ulster Folk and Transport Museum]], in [[Cultra]], [[Northern Ireland]] where it is now on display.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nmni.com/uftm/Collections/Transport-(1)/|title=Ulster Folk and Transport Museum - Online Collections|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n\n===Prototypes and pilot cars===\nOnly one of two DeLorean prototypes still exists.<ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |publisher=DeLorean PJ Grady Europe |title=Delorean Repairs |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421053458/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Prototype 1 sold at the bankruptcy auction in 1984 for $37,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |title=DeLorean prototype cars sell at auction for total $58,000 |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602233213/https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The car remained in a private collection until 2005 when it was sold to the owner of DeLorean Motor Company of Florida (DMCFL) where it received a complete restoration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |title=1587: 1976 DeLorean DMC-12 Original Prototype |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602234250/https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Proto 1 is now on display at DMCFL. Proto 2 was sent to [[Lotus Cars]] for development and evaluation in 1978. It was reported to have been destroyed in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Car |url=http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |website=The Delorean Museum |publisher=The Delorean Museum |accessdate=October 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006112343/http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |archivedate=October 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAn estimated 28 pilot cars were built by DMC. The pilot cars are best identified by the subtly different interiors and sliding side windows. These cars, used for evaluation and regulatory testing of the DeLorean, were previously thought to have been destroyed. Subsequently, several of the pilot cars were found to have survived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |title=Earliest known Pilot car found/photographed |publisher=Dmctalk.org |date=November 5, 1955 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132601/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |archive-date=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |title=Pilot Chronology |publisher=Pjgrady.co.uk |date=November 24, 1980 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051421/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Pilot car 25 which was featured on the front cover of [[Autocar (magazine)|Autocar]] in 1981 was found in 2003 in a barn in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |title=pilot-25 |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905040305/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Visioneering car===\nWith the 1980 [[National Automobile Dealers Association|NADA]] meeting approaching, DMC planned to show a final \u201cproduction\u201d version of the DeLorean, however there were no production cars ready at the time or even any production stainless steel panels.\n\nEarlier, in the summer of 1979, the revised Giugiaro styling mock-up was shipped to Visioneering, a [[Detroit]] based company, to create data needed to make the stamping dies for the stainless panels. This project would expand to create dies used to create a \u201cproduction\u201d car for the NADA show.\n\nUsing a prototype chassis supplied by Lotus in late 1979, Visioneering completed the assembly of this car at a cost of $750,000. The car was presented at the 1980 NADA show and was later used for engineering development and technical training as well as press photos. The Visioneering car would eventually be sold at the bankruptcy auction in late 1984 for $21,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\"/> Today, the car is in a private collection.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage| ISBN = 978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2012 | page = 108}}</ref>\n\n===Legend turbo cars===\nIt was determined that the DeLorean needed additional power when automotive magazine road tests showed {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|abbr=on}} times for the DeLorean between 9.5 and 10.5 seconds, while its rivals were in the 7.5\u20138.5 second range. There had been interest in [[turbocharger|turbocharging]] the DeLorean early on, but the DMC engineering staff was busy with other projects, so DeLorean decided to go outside to develop a turbocharged version of the DeLorean.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\">{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion | isbn=0-9744141-0-7 | author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |date= 2003 | pages = 110\u2013111}}</ref>\n\nHaving had previous success with turbocharging [[Fiat 124 Sport Spider|Fiat Spiders]], DeLorean entered into a contract with Legend Industries, based in [[Hauppauge, New York|Hauppauge]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. DMC wanted to increase power without sacrificing fuel efficiency. DMC wanted a wide power band and did not want a surge of power similar to the [[Porsche 930]] Turbo. Legend used twin [[IHI Corporation|IHI]] RHB52 turbos along with twin [[intercooler]]s. The results were an engine capable of accelerating smoothly in fifth gear from 1,500&nbsp;rpm to full turbo boost at 2,500&nbsp;rpm, reaching {{convert|150|mph|abbr=on}} at 6,500&nbsp;rpm.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\" />\n[[File:Legend engine.jpg|thumb|Legend Twin Turbo setup from VIN 530]]\n\nIn addition, Legend Industries developed a single turbocharged setup that was never finished.\nThe company converted a total of four DeLoreans and two Renault Alpines, which were the first development cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|title=Delorean Car Sales Europe UK. Canvey Island Essex SS8 OPQ|publisher=|access-date=February 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513040331/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|archive-date=May 13, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[VIN]] 530 was written in numerous press articles as the fastest production car of its era.\n\nIn a test run of VIN 530 at [[Bridgehampton Race Circuit|Bridgehampton Raceway]] in 1981, the twin-turbo DeLorean was quicker than a [[Ferrari 308 GTB/GTS|Ferrari 308]] and a [[Porsche 928]]. It has been a misconception for many years that VIN 502 was at Bridgehampton and used in testing; however, evidence from pictures, along with information from a Legend employee published by PJ Grady, indicates that 530 was used along with VIN 558.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |title=identifying-the-legend-cars |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905041236/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By the time of Bridgehampton, Legend had perfected modular boosting, which the earlier prototypes did not have installed apart from one of the Alpine mules and VIN 530.<ref>{{cite web | title=DeLorean DMC-12 | website=Silodrome | date=March 3, 2018 | url=https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | access-date=September 5, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905042552/https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | archive-date=September 5, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVIN 530 tested 0\u201360&nbsp;mph in 5.8 seconds and the [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] in 14.7 seconds. John DeLorean was so impressed with the engine, he committed to ordering 5,000 engines from Legend Industries. DMC planned to offer a turbocharged engine as a $7,500 option in 1984 (presumably to compete with the newly redesigned [[Chevrolet Corvette (C4)|1984 Corvette]]). Before any of the 5,000 cars could be put into production, DMC had declared bankruptcy, which drove Legend Industries, as well as other suppliers, into bankruptcy.<ref name=\"DeLorean Gold Portfolio\">{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Gold Portfolio | author=R. M. Clarke| publisher = Brookland Books LTD. |ISBN=1-85520-331-6 |date= 1996 | pages = 137\u2013143}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" Style=\"text-align:center\"\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n!\tVIN\t!!\tConfiguration\t!!\tLast known location\t!!\tComments\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t502\t||\tTwin\t||\tNew Zealand\t||\tOriginal prototype\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t528\t||\tSingle\t||\tNew York\t||\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t530\t||\tTwin\t||\tUnited Kingdom\t||\tSister twin-turbo\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t558\t||\tSingle\t||\tUnknown\t||\t\n|}\n\n===Gold-plated===\n[[File:gold-D.jpg|thumb|A gold-plated DeLorean in Reno, Nevada]]\nFor Christmas 1980, a DeLorean/[[American Express]] promotion planned to sell 100 [[Karat|24K]]-[[Gilding|gold-plated]] DeLoreans for US$85,000 each to its gold-card members, but only two were sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|title=In 1980, You Could Buy an $85,000, 24K-Gold-Plated DeLorean|publisher=|access-date=September 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920152935/http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|archive-date=September 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> One of these was purchased by Roger Mize, president of Snyder National Bank in [[Snyder, Texas]]. VIN #4301 sat in the bank lobby for over 20 years before being loaned to the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]] in [[Los Angeles]]. It has a black interior and an automatic transmission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |title=The 24-Karat Gold Plated DeLorean Car |publisher=Bigtexas.com |accessdate=January 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224111825/http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe second gold-plated American Express DeLorean was purchased by Sherwood Marshall, an entrepreneur and former [[Royal Canadian Navy|Royal Canadian Naval]] Officer. Marshall donated his DeLorean to the [[William F. Harrah]] Foundation/[[National Automobile Museum]] in [[Reno, Nevada]]. This car, VIN #4300, is equipped with a manual transmission and a saddle-brown interior.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.automuseum.org |title=National Automobile Museum |publisher=National Automobile Museum |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207005657/http://www.automuseum.org/ |archive-date=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA third gold-plated car exists that was assembled with spare parts that were required by American Express in case one of the other two that were built were damaged. All necessary gold-plated parts were on hand, with the exception of one door that was sourced later.<ref name=bigtexas>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Gold DeLorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Bigtexas.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110812111029/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/|archivedate=August 12, 2011 }}</ref> The car was first acquired by the winner of a [[Big Lots]] store raffle. Consolidated International, which owned the department store, had purchased 1374 DeLoreans during the DeLorean Motor Company's financial troubles, acquiring the remaining stock after the company went into receivership. It was listed for sale online at a price of US$250,000,<ref name=bigtexas/> but it is unclear whether it ever sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Delorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Archive.is |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524094241/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |archivedate=May 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA gold-plated DeLorean was reproduced privately by an enthusiast.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |title=Gold Plated DeLoreans? \u2013 Yes There Were Four |publisher=Mycarquest.com |date=February 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051720/http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |archive-date=April 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Right-hand-drive models===\nDeLoreans were primarily intended for the American market. All production models were therefore [[left-hand-drive]]. DeLorean Motor Company was aware as early as April 1981 of the need to produce a [[right-hand-drive]] (RHD) version to supply to world markets, specifically the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |title=woller-hodec |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905043041/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe company faced the choice of building right-hand-drive models from scratch or performing a post-production conversion exercise. Given the cost of new body molds, tooling, and a host of specific parts that a factory-built right-hand-drive configuration would require, the company opted to investigate the idea of a post-production conversion using a UK company based in [[Hampshire]] called Wooler-Hodec Ltd.<ref>{{cite book | last=Narus | first=D. | title=Independent Sports Cars | publisher=Lulu.com | year=2017 | isbn=978-1-387-15601-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HolUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA48 | access-date=August 30, 2019 | page=48}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[File:De Lorean DMC12 - Flickr - foshie (1).jpg|thumb|RHD DeLorean]]\nOnly 16 right-hand-drive factory-authorized DeLoreans were ever produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |title=DeLorean: Euro Spec DeLoreans |publisher=Deloreans.co.uk |accessdate=May 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617185502/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |archivedate=June 17, 2010 }}</ref> These cars can be divided into two distinct groups:\n# The first batch, known by enthusiasts as the \"Wooler-Hodec cars\", were converted by the UK company of that name. Evidence still exists in the form of a DMC factory memo, which orders 20 cars to be converted to right-hand drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |title=DMC Inter-Office Memo: RHD Conversion Programme |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905045408/https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Due to the factory's closure, this order was never completed, and today a total of 13 cars survive, carrying the VINs 510, 12171\u201312181 and 12199.\n# The second batch were registered and used by the factory in Northern Ireland, with registration numbers (license plates), AXI 1697, AXI 1698, AXI 1699 and are referred to by enthusiasts as the \"AXI cars\". These three cars (VINs 5565, 5592 and 5638) differ from the first Wooler-Hodec cars in several ways. They all had roof-mounted radio antennas, indicator repeater lights, no side marker lights, white forward-facing door lights, fog-light switch, and textured body rubstrips on the stainless panels. No [[catalytic converters]] or [[Oxygen sensor|lambda equipment]] were fitted, as British legislation did not require them. \n\nOwners who bought these cars at auction in the early 1980s encountered difficulty in registering them as new vehicles in the UK. At this point a former DeLorean Motor Cars executive offered to modify and register the cars so that they could be used in the UK. These modifications included:\n* Different seat-belt units fitted.<ref name=\"foglight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified seat belt unit in right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223213/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of Rubbolite tail light clusters with a built-in fog light function.<ref name=\"rubberlight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating so-called \"Euro-spec\" tail light unit |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223141/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of a fog light switch to one of the center-console dummy switches.<ref name=\"foglight\"/>\n* A custom-made tail light surround and number (license) plate bezel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating custom fabricated tail light and number (license) plate bezel fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223225/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the front turn signal lenses for ones of a different, more rounded style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating rounded turn signal lens on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013912/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the rear side marker lenses for amber ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating amber rear side marker lens fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223301/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAll of the 13 Wooler-Hodec cars were modified to the OEM front turn-signal lens fixing method in order to make them fit flush with the front fascia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified front turn signal lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013859/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref> The cars' headlights were also changed for right-hand-drive spec lights that incorporate a UK sidelight feature. \n\n\nBy contrast, the three AXI cars had further modifications to the amber front door lights, which were exchanged for clear lenses of the same style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating clear door light lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223348/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> Perhaps the most significant alteration on the AXI cars is the deletion of the front and rear side markers. These are replaced by a single small round European-style indicator side repeater, situated on the front wing (fender). The body rubstrips are also of a different configuration in order to cover the areas that would otherwise have had federal side marker lenses fitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified rubstrips and single round marker light |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223415/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===''Back to the Future''===\n{{Main|DeLorean time machine}}\n[[File:'81-'82 DeLorean DMC-12.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean \"time machine\" from the ''Back to the Future'' trilogy exhibited at [[Universal Studios Florida]]]]\nSeveral special-edition DeLorean cars have been produced over the years, and the car is most notably featured as the time machine in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' film trilogy]]. Six DeLorean chassis were used during the production, along with one manufactured out of fiberglass for scenes where a full-size DeLorean was needed to \"fly\" on-screen; only three of the cars still exist, with one that was destroyed at the end of ''[[Back to the Future Part III]]'', two additional cars were abandoned, and the fiberglass replica was scrapped. Universal Studios owns two of the remaining cars, occasionally putting them on display or using them for other productions, and the last resides in a private collection after having been extensively restored.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |title=BTTF3 DeLorean: Where Are They? |date= |accessdate=January 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005125859/http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |archive-date=October 5, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The official ''[[Back to the Future]]'' DeLorean can be viewed at the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |title=Petersen Automotive Museum |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320133259/http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |archivedate=March 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA number of production DeLoreans have been modified by the [[Automotive aftermarket|aftermarket]] into ''Back to the Future'' time machine replicas, whose bodies and interiors are modified to mirror the appearance and functions of the film cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|title=Bob's Prop Shop|work=bobspropshop.com|access-date=November 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016005640/http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|archive-date=October 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==DMC Texas==\n[[File:\" 12 - ITALY (Milan) Electro Vehicles Europe ( EVE ) DeLorean DMC-12.JPG|thumb|[[Electric car|All-electric model]] DMCev in Milan (2012)]]\nIn 1995, Stephen Wynne from Liverpool created a separate company based in Texas using the [[DeLorean Motor Company (Texas)|DeLorean Motor Company]] name. Wynne acquired the trademark on the stylized DMC logo, along with the remaining parts inventory of the original DeLorean Motor Company. The company rebuilds cars at its [[Humble, Texas]], location using a combination of [[new old stock]] (NOS) parts, original equipment manufacturer (OEM), and reproduction parts on a made-to-order basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718103728/http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archivedate=July 18, 2011|title=New build cars|publisher=DeLorean Motor Company|accessdate=May 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDMC Texas (based in [[Humble, Texas]]) announced on July 30, 2007, that the car would be returning into very limited production (about 20 cars a year) in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |title=For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |work=LA Times |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310115947/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |archive-date=March 10, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> They were subsequently sued by John DeLorean's widow for illegally licensing the family name. DMC Texas settled this lawsuit in September 2015 by paying his widow an undisclosed sum and in turn received rights to use the name, images, and trademark in the future.<ref>{{cite web|title = Lawyers Settle DeLorean Lawsuit Just in Time for 'Back to the Future' Day|url = https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|website = WSJ Blogs \u2013 Law Blog|date = October 21, 2015|accessdate = December 26, 2015|first = Jacob|last = Gershman|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151222085854/http://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|archive-date = December 22, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThe cars were announced to have a new stainless-steel frame; with optional extras such as GPS, an enhanced \"Stage 2\" engine, and possibly a new modern interior. Given that the cars were made with 80% old parts,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |title=Texas Entrepreneur Set to Start Building DeLorean Cars |publisher=Fox News |date=August 21, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511132411/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |archive-date=May 11, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> the term \"return to production\" is something of a misnomer; the cars are constructed on DeLorean underbodies built by the original company in the 1980s and retaining their VINs. The cars' titles show the year of the underbody's manufacture. Therefore, they are not new DeLoreans, but complete rebuilds of the car from the underbody with enhancements. In 2009, the price of a refurbished DeLorean from DMC Texas started at US$57,500, and the project was featured in an episode of ''[[Modern Marvels]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|title=Anything But Rusty: Reviewing The DeLorean In 2009|first=Ryan|last=McCaffrey|publisher=Motor Authority|date=December 20, 2009|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222115538/http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2011, it was announced that an all-electric model would be available for sale by 2013. It was said to have a {{Convert|200|hp|0|abbr=on|adj=on}} motor, accelerate from {{Convert|0|to|60|mph|abbr=on|km/h}} in 8 seconds, and sell for US$90,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Fox News |date=October 18, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029024300/http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archivedate=October 29, 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |title=The New DeLorean EV Gets Some Test Runs by Enthusiasts |work=Automotive Discovery |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026195129/http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |archive-date=October 26, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Back To The Future: All Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Forbes |date=October 19, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101212905/http://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archive-date=November 1, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Initial test drives revealed that the prototype had a range of {{Convert|70|mi|km}}, approaching the {{Convert|100|mi|km}} that was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|title=Electric DeLorean: First Drive|first=Kevin|last=McCauley|publisher=Jalopnik|date=October 17, 2011|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025045755/http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|archive-date=October 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> However, 2014 saw criticism from fans who tried to buy the electric DeLorean only to learn that it was still unavailable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|title=It Seems DeLorean Has Gone Back To The Past Again|first=Wes|last=Lungwitz|publisher=Car Debater|date=February 14, 2014|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106215825/http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|archive-date=November 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDue to the passage of the [[Low Volume Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Act of 2015|Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act]], DMC Texas announced that it would be producing replica DeLoreans with an expected release date in 2017. DMC anticipated building approximately 50 vehicles per year over six years with an estimated retail price of US$100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |title=The DeLorean Is Coming Back Thanks To This New Law, Will Have 300-400 HP |first=Jason |last=Torchinsky |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830195816/https://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |title=Brand-New DeLorean Replicas Are on the Way |date=January 27, 2016 |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914085258/https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |archive-date=September 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2016, DMC announced that it was expecting to build 12 units in the first production year with as many as 50 in the second year of production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |title=DMC Blog - DeLorean - The New DMC DeLorean |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827145747/http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |archive-date=August 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>   In December 2019, the NHTSA issued guidelines for the Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act<ref>https://www.nhtsa.gov/sites/nhtsa.dot.gov/files/documents/replica_vehicle_program_nprm_12172019.pdf</ref> and DMC Texas is now projecting they will begin production in 2021.<ref>https://www.autoblog.com/2020/01/24/delorean-motor-company-dmc-12-new-cars/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}<!-- Dead note \"production2\": [http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/img/news/n_vinrat.pdf DMC-12 Estimated Production Volumes by Month] (PDF) by Knut Grimsrud -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/index.html DMC - The legend - DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean.hu/ - Delorean Club Hungary- DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |first1= John Z. |last1= DeLorean |first2= Ted |last2= Schwarz |title= DeLorean |location= Grand Rapids, MI |publisher= Zondervan |year= 1985 |isbn= 0-310-37940-7 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/delorean00delo }}\n* {{cite book |first= John |last= Lamm |title= DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion |edition= 2nd |year= 2003 |location= Fort Jones, CA |publisher= Red Lion Press |isbn= 0-9744141-0-7}}\n* {{cite book |first= R. M. |last= Clarke |title= DeLorean: 1977\u20131995 Gold Portfolio |year= 1995 |location= Cobham |publisher= Brooklands |isbn= 1-85520-331-6}}\n* {{cite book |first= James |last= Espey |title= The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | edition= 2nd |year= 2014 |publisher= the DeLorean Garage |isbn= 978-0-9856578-1-9}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris | last= Parnham |first2= Andrew | last2= Withers |title= DeLorean Celebrating the Impossible |year= 2015| location = | publisher= DeLorean Motor Cars (1978) Ltd.| isbn= 978-0-9928594-0-4}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris |last= Williams|title= DeLorean DMC-12 [sic], The Essential Buyers Guide (2018) |year=2018 | location= |publisher= Veloce Publishing| isbn= 978-1-787112-32-2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia |\n | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n | |\n | Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED. |\n | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details. |\n | |\n | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or |\n | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org) |\n | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template. |\n==={{No more links}}=========-->\n\n{{Commons category|DeLorean DMC-12}}\n* [http://www.delorean.com/ DeLorean Motor Company]\n* {{curlie|Recreation/Autos/Makes_and_Models/DeLorean/|DeLorean}}\n* {{imcdb vehicle|make=De Lorean|model=DMC 12|DeLorean}}\n* [http://www.finecars.cc/en/detail/car/10075/ 1976 Concept DeLorean DMC 12]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_n_oBV2osAg ''The Car's the Star''] \u2013 TV biography of the DMC by former [[Top Gear (1977 TV series)|Top Gear]] host [[Quentin Willson]] (1999, UK)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Lotus}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Cars|North America}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeLorean}}\n[[Category:Cars of Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear-engined vehicles]]\n[[Category:Back to the Future]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1981]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with gull-wing doors]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with backbone chassis]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by rear-mounted 6-cylinder engines]]\n\n[[ja:\u30c7\u30ed\u30ea\u30a2\u30f3#DMC-12]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|1980s automobile}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = DMC DeLorean\n| image = Delorean DMC-12 side.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = 1983 DeLorean\n| manufacturer = [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC)<br />[[Bloomfield_Hills,_Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], Michigan, US\n| production = 9,080<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2015/12/19/delorean-book/77623204/|title=DeLoreans still ply the roads -- and memories|url-status=live}}</ref> (disputed)\n| model_years = 1981\u20131983\n| assembly = DeLorean Motor Cars, Ltd. (DMCL) [[Dunmurry]], [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland\n| designer = [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Italdesign]]<ref>https://www.cnn.com/style/article/giorgetto-giugiaro-interview/index.html</ref>\n| class = Sports car\n| body_style = 2-door coup\u00e9\n| related = \n| layout = Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| engine = {{convert|2.85|L|cuin|0|abbr=on}} [[V6 PRV engine]] ''ZMJ-159''<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| powerout = {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|207|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| transmission = 5-speed manual<br/>3-speed automatic<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2413|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\">{{Cite book|title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946\u20131975|publisher= Krause|isbn=0-87341-027-0|editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first= John A.}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4267|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| width = {{convert|1988|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| height = {{convert|1140|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors closed<br/>{{convert|1962|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors open<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date = 2014| pages = 16}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|1233|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| doors = Gullwing doors\n}}\n\nThe '''DMC DeLorean''' (often referred to simply as the \"'''DeLorean'''\", as it was the only model ever produced by the company) is a sports car manufactured by [[John DeLorean]]'s [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC) for the American market from 1981 to 1983. The car was designed by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] and stood out for its [[gull-wing door]]s and brushed stainless-steel outer body panels, as well as an innovative fiberglass body structure with a steel backbone chassis. It became widely known for its disappointing lack of power and performance, which did not match the expectations created by its looks and price tag, but it became iconic for its appearances as the [[DeLorean time machine|time machine]] in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' media franchise]] after 1985.\n\nThroughout production, the car was generally unchanged, although minor modifications were made to such parts as the hood and wheels. The first production car was completed on January 21, 1981. About 9,000 DeLoreans were made before production halted in late December 1982 shortly after DMC had filed for bankruptcy.\n\n==History==\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 (9979) (cropped).jpg|thumb|A DeLorean with the gull-wing doors closed]]\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 with doors open.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean from the front with the gull-wing doors open]]\nIn October 1976, the first prototype DeLorean was completed by American automotive chief engineer William T. Collins, formerly chief engineer at [[Pontiac]].  Originally, the car was intended to have a centrally-mounted [[Wankel engine|Wankel rotary engine]].  The engine selection was reconsidered when [[Comotor]] production ended, and the favored engine became the [[Ford Cologne V6 engine]].  Eventually the French/Swedish [[fuel injection|fuel-injected]] [[V6 PRV engine]] ([[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]]) was selected.  Also the engine location moved from the mid-engined location in the prototype to a rear-engined installation in the production car.  The [[chassis]] was initially planned to be produced from a new and untested manufacturing technology known as elastic reservoir moulding (ERM), which would lighten the car while presumably lowering its production costs.  This new technology, for which DeLorean had purchased patent rights, was eventually found to be unsuitable.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nThese and other changes to the original concept led to considerable schedule pressures.  The entire car was deemed to require almost complete re-engineering, which was turned over to engineer [[Colin Chapman]], founder of [[Lotus Cars]].  Chapman replaced most of the unproven material and manufacturing techniques with those then employed by Lotus, like the steel backbone chassis.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003| pages = 71\u201375}}</ref>\n\nThe first prototype appeared in October 1976 and was known as the DSV-1, or DeLorean Safety Vehicle.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 23}}</ref> As development continued, the model was referred to as the DSV-12<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 28}}</ref> and later the DMC-12 since DMC was targeting a list price of US$12,000 ({{Inflation|US|12000|1976|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) at release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |title=DeLorean DMC-12 |access-date=February 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204065904/https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |archive-date=February 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html How an immigrant mechanic used $5 million to bring DeLoreans back to the future] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014534/https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html |date=February 4, 2019 }} Zack Guzman. 3:52 PM ET Wed, November 9, 2016</ref>\n\nIn an interview with James Espey of the new incarnation of the DeLorean Motor Company of [[Texas]], a drawing surfaced showing that the car originally had the potential to be named \"Z Tavio\".  John DeLorean's middle name and his son's first name were both Zachary, while Tavio was his father's name and his son's middle name.  Due to only sporadic documentation, there is little more that is currently known about the Z Tavio name and why it was ultimately rejected in favor of the DeLorean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |title=Interview with James Espy of DMCH |publisher=Myride.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908094456/http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |archive-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter several delays and cost overruns, production finally began in late 1980. Around this time DMC officially dropped the name DMC-12 on its now US$25,000 ({{Inflation|US|25000|1981|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) car in favor of the model name DeLorean. The DeLorean sports car, as it was described in advertisements, began production in December 1980 with the first production car rolling off the assembly line on January 21, 1981.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lily Rothman |url=http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |title=DeLorean Auto History: What Happened to the Company |publisher=Time |date=January 21, 2016 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423164413/http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |title=Almanac: The DeLorean car |publisher=CBS News |date=January 21, 2018 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515122627/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |archive-date=May 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean Motor Company was placed into receivership in February 1982 and filed [[bankruptcy]] in October 1982<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/26/business/delorean-motor-files-bankruptcy.html</ref>.  Approximately 100 partially assembled DeLoreans on the production line were completed by [[Big Lots|Consolidated International]].  About 9,000 cars were produced in total.  The remaining parts from the factory stock, the parts from the US Warranty Parts Center, as well as parts from the original suppliers that had not yet been delivered to the factory were all shipped to [[Columbus, Ohio]] in 1983\u201384.  A company called KAPAC sold these parts to retail and [[wholesaling|wholesale]] customers by mail order.  In 1997, DeLorean Motor Company of Texas acquired this inventory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/q&a.asp#whereparts |title=DeLorean Motor Company FAQ |publisher=Delorean.com |date=November 6, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121215155/http://delorean.com/q%26a.asp |archivedate=November 21, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Sales and production==\n===Sales===\nPrior to the release of the DeLorean, there was a waiting list of anxious buyers, many of whom paid over [[List_price#Automobiles/motorcars|MSRP]], however that exuberance subsided very quickly and production output soon far exceeded sales volume.  October 1981 was the highest month of sales for DMC with 720 vehicles sold but by December, the US was falling into recession and interest rates were rising which further negatively impacted sales.  Despite this, instead of reducing production, John DeLorean doubled production output, further adding to the backlog of unsold cars.   By the end of 1981, DMC had produced 7,500 cars but had only sold 3,000.  By this point, DMC was in a financial hardship and in February 1982, DMC was placed into receivership. <ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 130}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1982, unsold 1981 model year cars were \u201cpriced for immediate clearance\u201d in hopes to make room for the more expensive 1982 model year cars.  In March, telegrams were sent to all 343 dealerships requesting each buy six cars to help save the company;  none of the dealers responded with a sales order.  By this point, dealers were sitting on unsold inventory as were the quality assurance centers and hundreds more sitting on the  docks in [[Long Beach]], California.  By the end of May 1982, production at the factory was shut down.  Another attempt in July 1982 was made to revive sales by offering discounts to dealerships and offering a 5-year/{{convert|50000|mi|adj=on}} warranty with the first year or {{convert|12000|mi|adj=on}} portion secured by a major insurance carrier but this was not successful. \n\nBruce McWilliams, VP of Marketing for DMC and later acting President for DMC America, after resigning his position said, \u201cThe car could never be sold in the numbers John DeLorean predicted\u2026\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 133-141}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\nProduction information was lost or scattered upon the [[DeLorean Motor Company#Downturn and bankruptcy|shutdown of DMC]] and production figures for the DeLorean have never been verified based on official factory records.  Despite some unexplained VIN gaps, based upon VIN information, owners have been able to piece together the approximate quantity of DeLoreans produced.\n\nIn February 1982, DMC was placed into [[receivership]] and the factory continued to operate at a reduced production rate until the end of May.  When Consolidated International acquired the unsold and partially assembled cars in November 1982, it brought back workers to complete the cars remaining on the assembly line. It was decided to make the remaining completed 1982 model year cars into 1983 models. The remaining cars VINs were re-VINed into 1983 cars by taking the original VIN number and adding 5000 to it and changing the \"CD\" in the middle of the VIN to \"DD\" thus making a 1983 model.\n\nFor the 1981 model year, there were 6,700 DeLoreans produced (VIN 500-7199).  For the 1982 model year, there were 1,999 DeLoreans produced (VIN 10001-11999).  For the 1983 model year, there were 276 DeLoreans (VIN 17000-17170 and 20001-20105) bringing the total estimated production to 8,975 cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 115-117}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2007, about 6,500 DeLorean cars were thought to still exist.<ref>{{cite news |first= Martin |last= Zimmerman |url= https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |title= For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |accessdate= January 7, 2013 |work= Los Angeles Times |date= July 28, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130228154343/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |archive-date= February 28, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\nThe DeLorean features a number of unusual construction details, including gull-wing doors, unpainted [[stainless-steel]] body panels, and a rear-mounted engine.\n\n===Body===\n[[File:De Lorean DMC-12 at Wollaton Park, Nottingham, England.jpg|thumb|The gull-wing doors on the DeLorean were a distinctive feature.]]\nThe body design of the DeLorean was a product of [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] of [[Italdesign Giugiaro|Ital Design]] and is panelled in brushed [[AISI steel grades#Stainless steel|SS304]] stainless steel. Except for three cars plated in 24-karat gold, all DeLoreans left the factory uncovered by paint or clearcoat.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Body Finish and Composition from Owners Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110228223225/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |archive-date= February 28, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Painted DeLoreans do exist, although these were all painted after the cars were purchased from the factory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |title=DeLorean Prototype & Production |publisher=AACA Museum |date= |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606022652/https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In order to train the workforce, a small number of DeLoreans were produced without the costly stainless steel panels and are referred to as \"black cars\" or [[Development_mule|mules]] in reference to their black fiberglass bodies. These cars were never intended to be sold.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |title=DeLorean - DeLorean DMC-12 Technical (1981-1982) |publisher=Motor-car.net |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425053807/https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSmall scratches in the stainless-steel body panels can be removed with a non-metallic scouring pad (since metal pads can leave iron particles embedded in the stainless steel, which can give the appearance of the stainless \"rusting\"), or even sandpaper.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Care & Feeding: Stainless Steel Body Maintenance |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110515142238/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |archive-date= May 15, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> The stainless-steel panels are fixed to a [[fiberglass]] underbody. The underbody is affixed to a steel double-Y frame chassis, inspired by the [[Lotus Esprit]] platform.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nThe unpainted stainless body creates challenges during [[Automotive restoration|restoration]] of the cars. In traditional automotive body repair, the panel is repaired to be as original (\"straight\") as possible, and imperfections are sculpted back to form with polyester body filler like [[Bondo (putty)|Bondo]] or lead (body [[solder]]). This poses no problem (aside from originality) with most cars, as the filler will be hidden by the car's paint (for example, most new cars have filler hiding the seam where the roof meets the [[quarter panel]]). With an unpainted stainless body, the stainless steel must be reworked to exactly the original shape, contour, and grain, which is a tremendously difficult job on regular steel (a dented or bent panel is stretched, and a shrinking hammer or other techniques must be used to unstretch the metal) and even more difficult with stainless due to its tendency to [[Work hardening|work-harden]]. Furthermore, it is exceedingly difficult to paint stainless steel due to difficulties with paint adhesion. DeLorean envisioned that damaged panels would simply be replaced rather than repaired.\n\nAnother distinctive feature of the DeLorean is its [[gull-wing door]]s. The common problem of supporting the weight of gull-wing doors was solved by other manufacturers with lightweight doors in the [[Mercedes-Benz 300SL]] and a hydraulic pump in the [[Bricklin SV-1]], although these designs had structural or convenience disadvantages. The DeLorean features heavy doors supported by [[Cryogenics|cryogenically]] preset [[Torsion bar suspension|torsion bars]] and gas-charged [[strut]]s.<ref>{{US patent|4,378,658}}</ref> These torsion bars were developed by [[Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation|Grumman Aerospace]] (and built by Unbrako in the UK, a division of SPS Technologies of Jenkintown, Pennsylvania, US) to withstand the stresses of supporting the doors.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Exotic Technology |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511091013/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |archive-date= May 11, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Much like the [[scissor doors|doors]] fitted to the [[Lamborghini Countach]], the DeLorean doors featured small cutout windows, because full-sized windows would not be fully retractable within the short door panels. Additionally, the doors featured red and amber \"safety\" lights around the perimeter. These lights illuminated when the door was open and could be seen from the front, rear or side of the vehicle at night or in low-light situations.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Vehicle Dimensions from Technical Manual, Workshop Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090401070948/http://dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |archive-date= April 1, 2009 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Door Design |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100914111250/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |archive-date= September 14, 2010 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Engine and drivetrain===\nThe [[engine]] is a [[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]] ([[V6 PRV engine|PRV]]) {{cvt|2.85|L|cuin|0}} [[V6 engine|V6]], rated at {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm and [[torque]] of {{convert|153|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 2750 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|website=carfolio.com|title=1981 De Lorean DMC-12 specifications|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614071722/https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1982/587540/de_lorean_dmc-12.html|website=automobile-catalog.com|title=1982 De Lorean DMC-12 specs|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> that was designed and built under special contract with the [[DeLorean Motor Company]]. These PRVs were a development of the 2.7-litre V6 in the [[Renault 30]] and were built in the PRV Factory in [[Douvrin]], Northern France. The 5-speed [[manual transmission]], also designed by PRV, was built at the [[Renault]] facility near [[Caen]] in [[Normandy]]. The engines and [[gearbox]]es were shipped weekly by sea from the PRV factories to the DMC factory.\n\n===Suspension===\nThe [[suspension (vehicle)|suspension]] is a four-wheel [[independent suspension]], [[coil spring]]s, and telescopic [[shock absorbers]]. The front suspension uses [[Double wishbone suspension|double wishbones]], while the rear is a [[Multi-link suspension|multi-link]] setup.\n\nWhen the DeLorean first arrived in the US, the car had a higher than expected wheel gap in the front suspension.  The nose-high appearance is the result of poor quality coil springs.  Despite having significantly less weight in the front, the front and rear springs had the same spring rate and also used lower quality steel which resulted in the nose-high look.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 83}}</ref>  Some people have erroneously cited a last minute change in US bumper height requirements led DMC to raise the vehicle just prior to delivery, however this is not true.  Design drawings clearly show that the design met [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration|NHTSA]] minimum bumper and headlight heights of the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/Bumper/Index.html|title=Bumper Q&A's|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003151011/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/bumper/index.html|archive-date=October 3, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|title=DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 49 CFR Part 571, [Docket No. 01-8885; Notice 01], RIN 2127-AH81, Glare from headlamps and other Front Mounted Lamps, Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard No. 108; Lamps, Reflective Devices, and Associated Equipment|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927155258/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|archive-date=September 27, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Many owners have subsequently replaced or modified the front springs to return the front height to the original design specification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|title=Improving handling and lowering the DeLorean - DeLorean Motor Company|author=|date=|website=support.delorean.com|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621093431/http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSteering is [[rack and pinion]], with an overall [[steering ratio]] of 14.9:1, giving 2.65 turns lock-to-lock and a {{convert|35|ft|m|adj=on}} turning circle. DeLoreans are fitted with [[alloy|cast alloy]] wheels, measuring {{convert|14|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|6|in|mm}} wide on the front and {{convert|15|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|8|in|mm}} wide on the rear. These were fitted with [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]] NCT steel-belted radial tires. The DeLorean is a [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|rear-engine vehicle]] with a 35%\u201365% front\u2013rear weight distribution.<ref>{{cite web|first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_weight.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Weight and Balance from Technical manual |publisher=Dmcnews.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean features power-assisted [[disc brake]]s on all wheels, with {{convert|10|in|mm|adj=on}} rotors front and {{convert|10.5|in|mm|adj=on}} rear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|title=1981 DeLorean-17|author=|date=|website=oldcarbrochures.org|access-date=May 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524222200/http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|archive-date=May 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAt the time of release, the automotive press was generally complimentary towards the DeLorean.  [[Motor Trend]]<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 128\u2013129}}</ref>, [[Car and Driver]] <ref>https://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/comparison-test/a15144078/de-lorean-vs-chevy-corvette-datsun-280-zx-ferrari-308gts-porsche-911-comparison-test/</ref> and [[Road_%26_Track|Road & Track]]<ref>https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/</ref> had mostly positive remarks about the car.  All of them noted disappointing performance, especially those that performed comparative tests against other vehicles but were otherwise impressed with the car noting commendable gas mileage and most of them noting that the DeLorean is more of a [[grand tourer|GT]] car rather than a sports car or racecar.\n\nHowever, more recent reviews of the car have been much more harsh.  In 2017, [[Time Magazine]] included the DeLorean on its list of 50 worst cars of all time.<ref>https://time.com/4723114/50-worst-cars-of-all-time/</ref>  In his book ''Naff Motors: 101 Automotive Lemons'', Tony Davis described the build quality as \"woeful\".  ''Top Gear'' writer Richard Porter included it in his book ''Crap Cars'', calling it \"dismal\",<ref name = \"Porter\">{{cite book|last=Porter |first=Richard |title=Crap Cars |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=2005 |isbn= |page=}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nDMC's comparison literature noted that the DeLorean could achieve {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|}} in 8.8 seconds, when equipped with a manual transmission. When equipped with an automatic transmission, the DeLorean would accelerate from {{convert|0|to|60|mph|}} in 10.5 seconds as tested by ''Road & Track'' magazine. The car's top speed is {{convert|109|mph|0}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|title=1982 DeLorean DMC-12: The Vintage Road & Track Test|date=October 21, 2015|work=Road & Track|publisher=|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803211950/http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|archive-date=August 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Road and Track called the car: \".. not quick for a sports/GT car in this price category ..\".\n\n==Problems and issues==\nDeLoreans, early production models in particular, suffered from poor build quality as well as mechanical issues with the vehicle.  Early production cars needed as much as 140-200 hours of work at DMC Quality Assurance Centers prior to being shipped to dealerships for delivery. DMC eventually sent 30 factory workers to the quality centers in the US to learn about the issues and how to fix them.  Quality issues did improve over time and by 1982 many of the quality issues had been resolved.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 83 - 84}}</ref>\n\nA total of four recalls were issued by the factory to correct issues such as a sticking throttle, front suspension issues and an inertia switch. <ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 108\u2013109}}</ref>\n\nOther quality issues that plagued the car included other issues surrounding the front suspension, clutch pedal adjustment (or lack thereof), brake rotors, instruments; in particular the [[speedometer]], power door locks and weak alternators.  Many early DeLoreans were delivered with an incorrect alignment with the toe-in incorrectly set leading to premature tire wear. \n\nIn addition, many dealers were reluctant to perform warranty work on DeLoreans since DMC owed them money for past warranty claims that were still unpaid.  Some dealerships were not able to perform repair work properly as DMC never issued a proper service manual.  The lack of quality service at dealerships was a point of frustration for many DeLorean owners at the time, particularly those who paid over sticker price to purchase one of the first cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 111\u2013112}}</ref>\n\n==Pricing and options==\n[[File:1982 De Lorean DMC12 coupe (8453073488).jpg|thumb|1982 DeLorean grey interior]]\n[[File:1981 DeLorean DMC 12 -- Virginia Museum of Transportation - 49374820477.jpg|thumb|1981 DeLorean with optional accent stripe]]\nUpon release in 1981, a DeLorean had a suggested retail price of US$25,000 ($650 more when equipped with an [[automatic transmission]]); this is equivalent to approximately US${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|25000|1981}}}} in {{inflation-year|US}}.{{inflation-fn|US}}. MSRP would increase in 1982 to $29,825<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|title=1982 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616231331/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and again in 1983 to $34,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|title=1983 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015225/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> At the outset, there were extensive waiting lists of people willing to pay up to $10,000 above the list price; however, after the collapse of the DeLorean Motor Company, unsold cars could be purchased for less than the retail price.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_sales.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Sales and Dealer Experiences}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean was only available with two factory options; a no-cost [[manual transmission]] or automatic transmission and the choice of a grey or black interior (grey interior became available mid 1981 model year).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |title=one of one! factory burgundy interior delorean |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905044903/https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The standard feature list included stainless-steel body panels; gull-wing doors with cryogenically treated torsion bars; leather seats; [[air conditioning]]; an AM/FM [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] [[stereo system]]; [[power window]]s, [[power door locks|locks]] and [[Power side-view mirror|mirrors]]; a tilt and telescopic [[steering wheel]]; tinted glass; body side moldings; intermittent/constant windshield wipers; and an electric rear-window defogger. Several dealer options were available, including a car cover; [[Sheepskin seat cover|sheepskin]] seat covers; floor mats; car care cleaning kit; black textured accent stripes; grey scotch-cal accent stripes; a luggage rack and a ski-rack adapter.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Dealer Installed Accessories |date= June 20, 1981 |access-date= January 27, 2005 |archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/6HxeVWMtL?url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |archive-date= July 8, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |title= DeLorean Owners Association: DeLorean specifications table |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980214030500/http://delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |archivedate=February 14, 1998}}</ref>\n{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=390 | image1=DMC Sticker.jpg |width1=199 |height1=260 |alt1=1982 DMC-12 window sticker |image2=DMC12 clearance.jpg |width2=200 |height2=260 |alt2=DeLorean clearance advertisement |footer_align=center |footer=1982 window sticker & 1983 DeLorean clearance advertisement}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Production changes==\nAlthough there were no typical yearly updates to the DeLorean, several changes were made to the DeLorean during production.<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\"/>  Instead of making changes at the end of the model year, DMC implemented changes mid-production. This resulted in no clear distinction between the 1981, 1982, and 1983 model years, but with subtle changes taking place almost continuously throughout the life cycle of the DeLorean.\n\n===Hood styles===\nThe original [[hood (vehicle)|hood]] of the DeLorean had [[Groove (machining)|grooves]] running down both sides. It included a tank flap to simplify [[Filling station|fuel filling]]. These cars typically had a locking cap to prevent fuel theft by [[siphon]]ing. In August 1981, the hood flap was removed from the hood of the cars (although the hood creases remained). This style was retained well into 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |title=The DeLorean |publisher=Babb Technology |date=April 8, 2008 |accessdate=November 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Based on production numbers for all three years, this hood style is probably the most common. After the supply of locking caps was exhausted, the company switched to a non-locking version (resulting in at least 500 cars with no flap, but with locking caps). The final styling for the hood included the addition of a DeLorean name badge and the removal of the grooves, resulting in a completely flat hood. According to senior personnel who worked at the Dunmurry factory, initial elimination of flapped hoods has a simple if unglamorous explanation; Chuck Benington, managing director, did not like the design.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nick Sutton, Purchasing Manager, Dunmurry factory|url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132250/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|archive-date=April 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=600 |image1=Early 1981 De Lorean hood.jpg |width1=387 |height1=142 |alt1=Early 1981 hood |image2=1983 De Lorean hood.jpg |width2=414 |height2=162 |alt2=1983 hood |footer_align=center |footer=Side-by-side comparison of an early 1981 hood (left) vs. a later model 1983 hood (right)}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Other changes===\n[[File:De Lorean add-on Pull strap.jpg|thumb|Early pull strap]]\n[[File:Delorean dmc-12 later style side bolster.jpg|thumb|Later-style one-piece bolster]]\n[[File:mid 1981 De Lorean silver wheel.JPG|thumb|Mid-1981 silver wheel]]\n\nJohn DeLorean was {{height|ft=6|in=4}} tall, and he designed the car to comfortably fit someone of his stature.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|title= The DeLorean's Time Leap|author= Claire Suddath|publisher= [[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date= April 19, 2012|access-date= July 14, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140706011419/http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|archive-date= July 6, 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> For shorter people, the addition of a pull strap made closing the doors much easier from the inside. These attach to the existing door handle. Late-model 1981 cars, and all cars from 1982 and 1983, have doors with integrated pull straps.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\">{{cite web|url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|title=DeLorean \u2013 The Car: Production Changes|work=babbtechnology.com|access-date=August 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe side [[bolster]]ing in the DeLorean was originally separate from the main interior pieces. In cars with this construction, is a tendency to place pressure on this piece when entering and exiting the vehicle, which eventually causes the bolstering to separate from the trim panel. To solve this problem, cars built in and after late 1981 have one solid trim piece with the bolster permanently attached.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nAs an addition to later cars, a foot rest, or [[dead pedal]], was added to help prevent [[fatigue (physical)|fatigue]] while driving. This is one of the few changes that is directly tied to a model year. These were built into only a few of the late-1981 vehicles and were added to all cars starting with 1982 production.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\"/>\n\nAlthough the styling of the DeLorean's wheels remained unchanged, the wheels of early-model 1981 vehicles were painted grey. These wheels sported matching grey centre caps with an embossed DMC logo. Early into the 1981 production run, these were changed to a polished silver look, with a contrasting black center cap. The embossed logo on the center caps was painted silver to add contrast.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the DeLorean came with an AM/FM stereo radio with cassette made by Craig. Since the Craig radio did not have a built-in clock, one was installed in front of the [[gear shift]] on the console. DeLorean switched to an ASI stereo in the middle of the 1982 production run. Since the ASI radio featured an on-board clock, the clock on the console was removed at the same time.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 44\u201345}}</ref>\n\nThe first 2,200 cars produced used a windshield-embedded [[antenna (radio)|antenna]]. This type of antenna proved to be unsuitable with poor radio reception. Oftentimes the radio would continually \"seek\", attempting to find a signal. A standard whip antenna, which was later changed to a manually retractable antenna, was added to the outside of the front right fender. While improving radio reception, this resulted in a hole in the stainless steel, and an unsightly antenna. As a result, the antenna was again moved. The final antenna was an automatic retractable version installed under the rear induction grill behind the rear driver's-side window.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 28\u201329}}</ref>\n\nThe small [[visor|sun visors]] on the DeLorean have [[Polyvinyl chloride|vinyl]] on one side and headliner [[Textile|fabric]] on the other side. Originally these were installed such that the headliner side would be on the bottom when not in use. Later on in 1981, they were reversed so that the vinyl side would be on the bottom.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 40}}</ref>\n\nThe original 80 amp Ducellier [[Alternator (auto)|alternator]] supplied with the early-production DeLoreans could not provide enough [[electric current|current]] to supply the car when all lights and electrical options were on; as a result, the [[battery (electricity)|battery]] would gradually discharge, leaving the driver stranded on the road. Beginning with cars built in late 1981, DeLoreans were fitted from the factory with a 90 amp [[Motorola]] alternator, which solved this problem. Additional battery drainage problems were caused by faulty or improperly adjusted door jamb switches. This switch activated the \"safety\" lights located around the door perimeter when it was open. When the door was closed, the door seals prevented the light from being seen. Due to the faulty switches the lights remained on, draining the battery. This happened to DeLorean owner [[Johnny Carson]] shortly after he was presented with the vehicle.\n\n==Notable and unique DeLoreans==\n===Wooden Mock-up===\n[[File:Ulster Transport Museum, Cultra, DMC-12 Coupe clay model of Italdesign, Moncalieri, Turin for the De Lorean Company, 1975 04.jpg|thumb|DMC-12 Coupe model]]\nIn March 1975, DMC entered into a contract with Ital Design to have Giorgetto Giugiaro design the DeLorean Sports Car.  John DeLorean and Bill Collins approved one of the many designs and subsequently the styling mock-up that was made from \u201cepo-wood\u201d was scheduled to be shipped to the DMC office in Michigan on July 31, 1975.  This mockup would serve as the platform in which the prototype was developed.\n\nThe original full-size epowood DeLorean styling model which was modified in the first quarter of 1979 to reflect the refreshed design used in production, was donated to the [[Ulster Folk and Transport Museum]], in [[Cultra]], [[Northern Ireland]] where it is now on display.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nmni.com/uftm/Collections/Transport-(1)/|title=Ulster Folk and Transport Museum - Online Collections|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n\n===Prototypes and pilot cars===\nOnly one of two DeLorean prototypes still exists.<ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |publisher=DeLorean PJ Grady Europe |title=Delorean Repairs |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421053458/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Prototype 1 sold at the bankruptcy auction in 1984 for $37,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |title=DeLorean prototype cars sell at auction for total $58,000 |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602233213/https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The car remained in a private collection until 2005 when it was sold to the owner of DeLorean Motor Company of Florida (DMCFL) where it received a complete restoration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |title=1587: 1976 DeLorean DMC-12 Original Prototype |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602234250/https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Proto 1 is now on display at DMCFL. Proto 2 was sent to [[Lotus Cars]] for development and evaluation in 1978. It was reported to have been destroyed in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Car |url=http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |website=The Delorean Museum |publisher=The Delorean Museum |accessdate=October 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006112343/http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |archivedate=October 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAn estimated 28 pilot cars were built by DMC. The pilot cars are best identified by the subtly different interiors and sliding side windows. These cars, used for evaluation and regulatory testing of the DeLorean, were previously thought to have been destroyed. Subsequently, several of the pilot cars were found to have survived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |title=Earliest known Pilot car found/photographed |publisher=Dmctalk.org |date=November 5, 1955 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132601/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |archive-date=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |title=Pilot Chronology |publisher=Pjgrady.co.uk |date=November 24, 1980 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051421/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Pilot car 25 which was featured on the front cover of [[Autocar (magazine)|Autocar]] in 1981 was found in 2003 in a barn in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |title=pilot-25 |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905040305/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Visioneering car===\nWith the 1980 [[National Automobile Dealers Association|NADA]] meeting approaching, DMC planned to show a final \u201cproduction\u201d version of the DeLorean, however there were no production cars ready at the time or even any production stainless steel panels.\n\nEarlier, in the summer of 1979, the revised Giugiaro styling mock-up was shipped to Visioneering, a [[Detroit]] based company, to create data needed to make the stamping dies for the stainless panels. This project would expand to create dies used to create a \u201cproduction\u201d car for the NADA show.\n\nUsing a prototype chassis supplied by Lotus in late 1979, Visioneering completed the assembly of this car at a cost of $750,000. The car was presented at the 1980 NADA show and was later used for engineering development and technical training as well as press photos. The Visioneering car would eventually be sold at the bankruptcy auction in late 1984 for $21,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\"/> Today, the car is in a private collection.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage| ISBN = 978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2012 | page = 108}}</ref>\n\n===Legend turbo cars===\nIt was determined that the DeLorean needed additional power when automotive magazine road tests showed {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|abbr=on}} times for the DeLorean between 9.5 and 10.5 seconds, while its rivals were in the 7.5\u20138.5 second range. There had been interest in [[turbocharger|turbocharging]] the DeLorean early on, but the DMC engineering staff was busy with other projects, so DeLorean decided to go outside to develop a turbocharged version of the DeLorean.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\">{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion | isbn=0-9744141-0-7 | author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |date= 2003 | pages = 110\u2013111}}</ref>\n\nHaving had previous success with turbocharging [[Fiat 124 Sport Spider|Fiat Spiders]], DeLorean entered into a contract with Legend Industries, based in [[Hauppauge, New York|Hauppauge]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. DMC wanted to increase power without sacrificing fuel efficiency. DMC wanted a wide power band and did not want a surge of power similar to the [[Porsche 930]] Turbo. Legend used twin [[IHI Corporation|IHI]] RHB52 turbos along with twin [[intercooler]]s. The results were an engine capable of accelerating smoothly in fifth gear from 1,500&nbsp;rpm to full turbo boost at 2,500&nbsp;rpm, reaching {{convert|150|mph|abbr=on}} at 6,500&nbsp;rpm.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\" />\n[[File:Legend engine.jpg|thumb|Legend Twin Turbo setup from VIN 530]]\n\nIn addition, Legend Industries developed a single turbocharged setup that was never finished.\nThe company converted a total of four DeLoreans and two Renault Alpines, which were the first development cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|title=Delorean Car Sales Europe UK. Canvey Island Essex SS8 OPQ|publisher=|access-date=February 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513040331/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|archive-date=May 13, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[VIN]] 530 was written in numerous press articles as the fastest production car of its era.\n\nIn a test run of VIN 530 at [[Bridgehampton Race Circuit|Bridgehampton Raceway]] in 1981, the twin-turbo DeLorean was quicker than a [[Ferrari 308 GTB/GTS|Ferrari 308]] and a [[Porsche 928]]. It has been a misconception for many years that VIN 502 was at Bridgehampton and used in testing; however, evidence from pictures, along with information from a Legend employee published by PJ Grady, indicates that 530 was used along with VIN 558.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |title=identifying-the-legend-cars |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905041236/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By the time of Bridgehampton, Legend had perfected modular boosting, which the earlier prototypes did not have installed apart from one of the Alpine mules and VIN 530.<ref>{{cite web | title=DeLorean DMC-12 | website=Silodrome | date=March 3, 2018 | url=https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | access-date=September 5, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905042552/https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | archive-date=September 5, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVIN 530 tested 0\u201360&nbsp;mph in 5.8 seconds and the [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] in 14.7 seconds. John DeLorean was so impressed with the engine, he committed to ordering 5,000 engines from Legend Industries. DMC planned to offer a turbocharged engine as a $7,500 option in 1984 (presumably to compete with the newly redesigned [[Chevrolet Corvette (C4)|1984 Corvette]]). Before any of the 5,000 cars could be put into production, DMC had declared bankruptcy, which drove Legend Industries, as well as other suppliers, into bankruptcy.<ref name=\"DeLorean Gold Portfolio\">{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Gold Portfolio | author=R. M. Clarke| publisher = Brookland Books LTD. |ISBN=1-85520-331-6 |date= 1996 | pages = 137\u2013143}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" Style=\"text-align:center\"\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n!\tVIN\t!!\tConfiguration\t!!\tLast known location\t!!\tComments\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t502\t||\tTwin\t||\tNew Zealand\t||\tOriginal prototype\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t528\t||\tSingle\t||\tNew York\t||\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t530\t||\tTwin\t||\tUnited Kingdom\t||\tSister twin-turbo\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t558\t||\tSingle\t||\tUnknown\t||\t\n|}\n\n===Gold-plated===\n[[File:gold-D.jpg|thumb|A gold-plated DeLorean in Reno, Nevada]]\nFor Christmas 1980, a DeLorean/[[American Express]] promotion planned to sell 100 [[Karat|24K]]-[[Gilding|gold-plated]] DeLoreans for US$85,000 each to its gold-card members, but only two were sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|title=In 1980, You Could Buy an $85,000, 24K-Gold-Plated DeLorean|publisher=|access-date=September 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920152935/http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|archive-date=September 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> One of these was purchased by Roger Mize, president of Snyder National Bank in [[Snyder, Texas]]. VIN #4301 sat in the bank lobby for over 20 years before being loaned to the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]] in [[Los Angeles]]. It has a black interior and an automatic transmission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |title=The 24-Karat Gold Plated DeLorean Car |publisher=Bigtexas.com |accessdate=January 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224111825/http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe second gold-plated American Express DeLorean was purchased by Sherwood Marshall, an entrepreneur and former [[Royal Canadian Navy|Royal Canadian Naval]] Officer. Marshall donated his DeLorean to the [[William F. Harrah]] Foundation/[[National Automobile Museum]] in [[Reno, Nevada]]. This car, VIN #4300, is equipped with a manual transmission and a saddle-brown interior.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.automuseum.org |title=National Automobile Museum |publisher=National Automobile Museum |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207005657/http://www.automuseum.org/ |archive-date=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA third gold-plated car exists that was assembled with spare parts that were required by American Express in case one of the other two that were built were damaged. All necessary gold-plated parts were on hand, with the exception of one door that was sourced later.<ref name=bigtexas>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Gold DeLorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Bigtexas.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110812111029/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/|archivedate=August 12, 2011 }}</ref> The car was first acquired by the winner of a [[Big Lots]] store raffle. Consolidated International, which owned the department store, had purchased 1374 DeLoreans during the DeLorean Motor Company's financial troubles, acquiring the remaining stock after the company went into receivership. It was listed for sale online at a price of US$250,000,<ref name=bigtexas/> but it is unclear whether it ever sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Delorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Archive.is |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524094241/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |archivedate=May 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA gold-plated DeLorean was reproduced privately by an enthusiast.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |title=Gold Plated DeLoreans? \u2013 Yes There Were Four |publisher=Mycarquest.com |date=February 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051720/http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |archive-date=April 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Right-hand-drive models===\nDeLoreans were primarily intended for the American market. All production models were therefore [[left-hand-drive]]. DeLorean Motor Company was aware as early as April 1981 of the need to produce a [[right-hand-drive]] (RHD) version to supply to world markets, specifically the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |title=woller-hodec |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905043041/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe company faced the choice of building right-hand-drive models from scratch or performing a post-production conversion exercise. Given the cost of new body molds, tooling, and a host of specific parts that a factory-built right-hand-drive configuration would require, the company opted to investigate the idea of a post-production conversion using a UK company based in [[Hampshire]] called Wooler-Hodec Ltd.<ref>{{cite book | last=Narus | first=D. | title=Independent Sports Cars | publisher=Lulu.com | year=2017 | isbn=978-1-387-15601-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HolUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA48 | access-date=August 30, 2019 | page=48}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[File:De Lorean DMC12 - Flickr - foshie (1).jpg|thumb|RHD DeLorean]]\nOnly 16 right-hand-drive factory-authorized DeLoreans were ever produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |title=DeLorean: Euro Spec DeLoreans |publisher=Deloreans.co.uk |accessdate=May 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617185502/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |archivedate=June 17, 2010 }}</ref> These cars can be divided into two distinct groups:\n# The first batch, known by enthusiasts as the \"Wooler-Hodec cars\", were converted by the UK company of that name. Evidence still exists in the form of a DMC factory memo, which orders 20 cars to be converted to right-hand drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |title=DMC Inter-Office Memo: RHD Conversion Programme |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905045408/https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Due to the factory's closure, this order was never completed, and today a total of 13 cars survive, carrying the VINs 510, 12171\u201312181 and 12199.\n# The second batch were registered and used by the factory in Northern Ireland, with registration numbers (license plates), AXI 1697, AXI 1698, AXI 1699 and are referred to by enthusiasts as the \"AXI cars\". These three cars (VINs 5565, 5592 and 5638) differ from the first Wooler-Hodec cars in several ways. They all had roof-mounted radio antennas, indicator repeater lights, no side marker lights, white forward-facing door lights, fog-light switch, and textured body rubstrips on the stainless panels. No [[catalytic converters]] or [[Oxygen sensor|lambda equipment]] were fitted, as British legislation did not require them. \n\nOwners who bought these cars at auction in the early 1980s encountered difficulty in registering them as new vehicles in the UK. At this point a former DeLorean Motor Cars executive offered to modify and register the cars so that they could be used in the UK. These modifications included:\n* Different seat-belt units fitted.<ref name=\"foglight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified seat belt unit in right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223213/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of Rubbolite tail light clusters with a built-in fog light function.<ref name=\"rubberlight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating so-called \"Euro-spec\" tail light unit |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223141/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of a fog light switch to one of the center-console dummy switches.<ref name=\"foglight\"/>\n* A custom-made tail light surround and number (license) plate bezel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating custom fabricated tail light and number (license) plate bezel fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223225/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the front turn signal lenses for ones of a different, more rounded style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating rounded turn signal lens on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013912/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the rear side marker lenses for amber ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating amber rear side marker lens fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223301/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAll of the 13 Wooler-Hodec cars were modified to the OEM front turn-signal lens fixing method in order to make them fit flush with the front fascia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified front turn signal lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013859/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref> The cars' headlights were also changed for right-hand-drive spec lights that incorporate a UK sidelight feature. \n\n\nBy contrast, the three AXI cars had further modifications to the amber front door lights, which were exchanged for clear lenses of the same style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating clear door light lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223348/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> Perhaps the most significant alteration on the AXI cars is the deletion of the front and rear side markers. These are replaced by a single small round European-style indicator side repeater, situated on the front wing (fender). The body rubstrips are also of a different configuration in order to cover the areas that would otherwise have had federal side marker lenses fitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified rubstrips and single round marker light |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223415/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===''Back to the Future''===\n{{Main|DeLorean time machine}}\n[[File:'81-'82 DeLorean DMC-12.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean \"time machine\" from the ''Back to the Future'' trilogy exhibited at [[Universal Studios Florida]]]]\nSeveral special-edition DeLorean cars have been produced over the years, and the car is most notably featured as the time machine in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' film trilogy]]. Six DeLorean chassis were used during the production, along with one manufactured out of fiberglass for scenes where a full-size DeLorean was needed to \"fly\" on-screen; only three of the cars still exist, with one that was destroyed at the end of ''[[Back to the Future Part III]]'', two additional cars were abandoned, and the fiberglass replica was scrapped. Universal Studios owns two of the remaining cars, occasionally putting them on display or using them for other productions, and the last resides in a private collection after having been extensively restored.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |title=BTTF3 DeLorean: Where Are They? |date= |accessdate=January 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005125859/http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |archive-date=October 5, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The official ''[[Back to the Future]]'' DeLorean can be viewed at the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |title=Petersen Automotive Museum |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320133259/http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |archivedate=March 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA number of production DeLoreans have been modified by the [[Automotive aftermarket|aftermarket]] into ''Back to the Future'' time machine replicas, whose bodies and interiors are modified to mirror the appearance and functions of the film cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|title=Bob's Prop Shop|work=bobspropshop.com|access-date=November 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016005640/http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|archive-date=October 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==DMC Texas==\n[[File:\" 12 - ITALY (Milan) Electro Vehicles Europe ( EVE ) DeLorean DMC-12.JPG|thumb|[[Electric car|All-electric model]] DMCev in Milan (2012)]]\nIn 1995, Stephen Wynne from Liverpool created a separate company based in Texas using the [[DeLorean Motor Company (Texas)|DeLorean Motor Company]] name. Wynne acquired the trademark on the stylized DMC logo, along with the remaining parts inventory of the original DeLorean Motor Company. The company rebuilds cars at its [[Humble, Texas]], location using a combination of [[new old stock]] (NOS) parts, original equipment manufacturer (OEM), and reproduction parts on a made-to-order basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718103728/http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archivedate=July 18, 2011|title=New build cars|publisher=DeLorean Motor Company|accessdate=May 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDMC Texas (based in [[Humble, Texas]]) announced on July 30, 2007, that the car would be returning into very limited production (about 20 cars a year) in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |title=For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |work=LA Times |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310115947/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |archive-date=March 10, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> They were subsequently sued by John DeLorean's widow for illegally licensing the family name. DMC Texas settled this lawsuit in September 2015 by paying his widow an undisclosed sum and in turn received rights to use the name, images, and trademark in the future.<ref>{{cite web|title = Lawyers Settle DeLorean Lawsuit Just in Time for 'Back to the Future' Day|url = https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|website = WSJ Blogs \u2013 Law Blog|date = October 21, 2015|accessdate = December 26, 2015|first = Jacob|last = Gershman|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151222085854/http://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|archive-date = December 22, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThe cars were announced to have a new stainless-steel frame; with optional extras such as GPS, an enhanced \"Stage 2\" engine, and possibly a new modern interior. Given that the cars were made with 80% old parts,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |title=Texas Entrepreneur Set to Start Building DeLorean Cars |publisher=Fox News |date=August 21, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511132411/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |archive-date=May 11, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> the term \"return to production\" is something of a misnomer; the cars are constructed on DeLorean underbodies built by the original company in the 1980s and retaining their VINs. The cars' titles show the year of the underbody's manufacture. Therefore, they are not new DeLoreans, but complete rebuilds of the car from the underbody with enhancements. In 2009, the price of a refurbished DeLorean from DMC Texas started at US$57,500, and the project was featured in an episode of ''[[Modern Marvels]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|title=Anything But Rusty: Reviewing The DeLorean In 2009|first=Ryan|last=McCaffrey|publisher=Motor Authority|date=December 20, 2009|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222115538/http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2011, it was announced that an all-electric model would be available for sale by 2013. It was said to have a {{Convert|200|hp|0|abbr=on|adj=on}} motor, accelerate from {{Convert|0|to|60|mph|abbr=on|km/h}} in 8 seconds, and sell for US$90,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Fox News |date=October 18, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029024300/http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archivedate=October 29, 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |title=The New DeLorean EV Gets Some Test Runs by Enthusiasts |work=Automotive Discovery |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026195129/http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |archive-date=October 26, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Back To The Future: All Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Forbes |date=October 19, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101212905/http://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archive-date=November 1, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Initial test drives revealed that the prototype had a range of {{Convert|70|mi|km}}, approaching the {{Convert|100|mi|km}} that was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|title=Electric DeLorean: First Drive|first=Kevin|last=McCauley|publisher=Jalopnik|date=October 17, 2011|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025045755/http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|archive-date=October 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> However, 2014 saw criticism from fans who tried to buy the electric DeLorean only to learn that it was still unavailable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|title=It Seems DeLorean Has Gone Back To The Past Again|first=Wes|last=Lungwitz|publisher=Car Debater|date=February 14, 2014|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106215825/http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|archive-date=November 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDue to the passage of the [[Low Volume Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Act of 2015|Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act]], DMC Texas announced that it would be producing replica DeLoreans with an expected release date in 2017. DMC anticipated building approximately 50 vehicles per year over six years with an estimated retail price of US$100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |title=The DeLorean Is Coming Back Thanks To This New Law, Will Have 300-400 HP |first=Jason |last=Torchinsky |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830195816/https://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |title=Brand-New DeLorean Replicas Are on the Way |date=January 27, 2016 |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914085258/https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |archive-date=September 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2016, DMC announced that it was expecting to build 12 units in the first production year with as many as 50 in the second year of production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |title=DMC Blog - DeLorean - The New DMC DeLorean |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827145747/http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |archive-date=August 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>   In December 2019, the NHTSA issued guidelines for the Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act<ref>https://www.nhtsa.gov/sites/nhtsa.dot.gov/files/documents/replica_vehicle_program_nprm_12172019.pdf</ref> and DMC Texas is now projecting they will begin production in 2021.<ref>https://www.autoblog.com/2020/01/24/delorean-motor-company-dmc-12-new-cars/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}<!-- Dead note \"production2\": [http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/img/news/n_vinrat.pdf DMC-12 Estimated Production Volumes by Month] (PDF) by Knut Grimsrud -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/index.html DMC - The legend - DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean.hu/ - Delorean Club Hungary- DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |first1= John Z. |last1= DeLorean |first2= Ted |last2= Schwarz |title= DeLorean |location= Grand Rapids, MI |publisher= Zondervan |year= 1985 |isbn= 0-310-37940-7 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/delorean00delo }}\n* {{cite book |first= John |last= Lamm |title= DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion |edition= 2nd |year= 2003 |location= Fort Jones, CA |publisher= Red Lion Press |isbn= 0-9744141-0-7}}\n* {{cite book |first= R. M. |last= Clarke |title= DeLorean: 1977\u20131995 Gold Portfolio |year= 1995 |location= Cobham |publisher= Brooklands |isbn= 1-85520-331-6}}\n* {{cite book |first= James |last= Espey |title= The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | edition= 2nd |year= 2014 |publisher= the DeLorean Garage |isbn= 978-0-9856578-1-9}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris | last= Parnham |first2= Andrew | last2= Withers |title= DeLorean Celebrating the Impossible |year= 2015| location = | publisher= DeLorean Motor Cars (1978) Ltd.| isbn= 978-0-9928594-0-4}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris |last= Williams|title= DeLorean DMC-12 [sic], The Essential Buyers Guide (2018) |year=2018 | location= |publisher= Veloce Publishing| isbn= 978-1-787112-32-2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia |\n | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n | |\n | Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED. |\n | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details. |\n | |\n | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or |\n | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org) |\n | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template. |\n==={{No more links}}=========-->\n\n{{Commons category|DeLorean DMC-12}}\n* [http://www.delorean.com/ DeLorean Motor Company]\n* {{curlie|Recreation/Autos/Makes_and_Models/DeLorean/|DeLorean}}\n* {{imcdb vehicle|make=De Lorean|model=DMC 12|DeLorean}}\n* [http://www.finecars.cc/en/detail/car/10075/ 1976 Concept DeLorean DMC 12]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_n_oBV2osAg ''The Car's the Star''] \u2013 TV biography of the DMC by former [[Top Gear (1977 TV series)|Top Gear]] host [[Quentin Willson]] (1999, UK)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Lotus}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Cars|North America}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeLorean}}\n[[Category:Cars of Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear-engined vehicles]]\n[[Category:Back to the Future]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1981]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with gull-wing doors]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with backbone chassis]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by rear-mounted 6-cylinder engines]]\n\n[[ja:\u30c7\u30ed\u30ea\u30a2\u30f3#DMC-12]]\n", "name_user": "Expandinglight5", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther changes:moving pics to bottom of section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DMC_DeLorean"}
{"title_page": "Jeannie Seely", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jeannie Seely\n| image              = Jeannie Seely at the Opry.jpg\n| caption            = Jeannie Seely at the [[Grand Ole Opry]], 2010s.\n| birth_name         = Marilyn Jeanne Seely\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1940|07|06}} \n| birth_place        = [[Titusville, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|actress|author|[[record producer|producer]]}}\n| years_active       = 1962\u2013present\n| home_town          = [[Townville, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| spouse             = {{ubl|{{marriage|[[Hank Cochran]]|1969|1981|reason=divorced}}|{{marriage|Gene Ward|2010}}}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed              = yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[Country music|Country]]|[[Nashville Sound]]}}\n| instrument         = Vocals\n| label              = {{hlist|[[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge]]|[[Monument Records|Monument]]|[[Decca Records|Decca]]/[[MCA Records|MCA]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|Power Pak|Shadpoke|OMS|Cheyenne}}\n| associated_acts    = {{hlist|[[Jack Greene]]|[[Dottie West]]|[[Willie Nelson]]}}\n| website            = {{URL|jeannieseely.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Jeannie Seely''' (born '''Marilyn Jeanne Seely'''; July 6, 1940) is an American [[country music]] singer, songwriter, and record producer. She also has several acting credits and published a book. Seely found success with the [[Grammy Award]]-winning hit \"[[Don't Touch Me]]\" (1966). Her [[soul music|soul]]-inspired vocal delivery<ref name=\"Meadville\">{{cite web |title=Big Honor for Jeannie Seely Later This Month |url=https://www.meadvilletribune.com/news/big-honor-for-jeannie-seely-later-this-month/article_33217218-12b4-11ea-9446-8ba8dd6a496c.html |website=[[Meadville Tribune]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> was praised by music professionals, who gave her the nickname of \"Miss Country Soul\".<ref name=\"PBS\">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Ken |title=Country Music: Jeannie Seely Biography |url=https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/country-music/jeannie-seely-biography/ |publisher=[[PBS]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Seely is also known for her membership and presence on the [[Grand Ole Opry]], where she has been active for over 50 years.\n\nSeely was born and raised in northwestern [[Pennsylvania]]. Developing an early interest in country music, she performed regularly on local radio and television stations. Following high school graduation, she worked at a local bank before moving to southern California. It was on the west coast where she rediscovered country music. Originally a secretary at [[Imperial Records]], she soon was writing songs for the company as well. Many of these songs would be recorded by other artists. In 1965, she signed her own recording contract with [[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge Records]]. Seely then moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to pursue a recording career. In Nashville, Seely's \"Don't Touch Me\" was released on [[Monument Records]] and was a major hit single. She followed it with several more hits, including \"[[A Wanderin' Man]]\" (1967) and \"[[I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)]]\" (1968). \n\nSeely started collaborating with [[Jack Greene]] in the late 1960s. The pair toured and had recordings together for several years. Their biggest single would be 1970's \"[[Wish I Didn't Have to Miss You]]\". Seely had solo success during this same time with \"[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms]]\" (1973) and \"[[Lucky Ladies]]\" (1974). In 1977, Seely's career went on hiatus after sustaining severe injuries in an automobile accident. With the support of others, she resumed her career. Seely took a more diverse career approach in the years following her accident. She appeared in the [[Willie Nelson]] film ''[[Honeysuckle Rose (film)|Honeysuckle Rose]]'', acted in several stage plays and performed in concert regularly. During this period, Seely also became the first female artist to host the Grand Ole Opry. In addition, she released her first and only book to date, ''Pieces of a Puzzled Mind''.\n\nIn the 1990s, Seely returned to recording albums. This was launched with a 1990 eponymous release, followed by her first album of [[holiday music]] in 1994 called ''Number One Christmas''. In 1999, she released the studio album ''Been There Sung That'', which included duets with several artists. In 2003, Seely issued ''Life's Highway'', a studio album that fused [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] with traditional country music. Her most recent studio release was 2017's ''[[Written in Song]]'', which was issued on her own record label. Seely has since been a consistent host of the Grand Ole Opry and has been a regular host of a weekly radio program on [[Sirius XM]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Titusville Trust Company.jpg|thumb|right|220px|The original Titusville Trust Company building. After high school, Seely was employed there.]]\nSeely was born Marilyn Jeanne Seely in [[Titusville, Pennsylvania]] on July 6, 1940.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\">{{cite web |last1=Huey |first1=Steve |title=Jeannie Seely: Biography & History |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jeannie-seely-mn0000234004/biography |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Although born in Titusville, she was raised in nearby [[Townville, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Meadville\"/> Seely was the youngest of four children born to Irene and Leo Seely. Leo Seely was a farmer and an employer of the Titusville Steel Mill. On weekends, he worked at local square dances and played the [[fiddle]]. Irene Seely was a homemaker who also enjoyed singing with her children while cooking.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=1}} As a young child, family and friends often gathered together to perform. \"It seemed like everybody back in the country played guitars and fiddles, and when we got together there was always pickin\u2018 and singin\u2018,\" Seely recalled.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=1}} She developed an interest in [[country music]] during her early years. On Saturday nights, the Seely family would spent time listening to the [[Grand Ole Opry]] in her parents' car. Mrs. Seely also brought her children to country music shows at a local venue named Hillbilly Park. At the park, the family often watched performances by country artists such as [[Little Jimmy Dickens]], [[Bill Monroe]] and [[Jean Shepard]].{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|pp=1\u20132}}\n\nAt age 11, she started performing on a local radio station, located in [[Meadville, Pennsylvania]]. Because of her short height and the lack of nonadjustable microphones, Seely had to stand on top of wooden containers to sing.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=1}} At age 16, Seely became a regular performer on [[WICU (AM)|WICU]], a local television station in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"PBS\"/> She recounted being ridiculed by her high school peers in choosing to sing country music. \"They all made fun of me because I sang country. I grew up poor and in those days calling someone 'country' was a put-down,\" she said in 2003.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} In high school, Seely was a [[cheerleading|cheerleader]] and an [[honors student]]. In 1958, she graduated from Townville High School at age eighteen.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} \n\nInstead of attending college, Seely took a job at the Titusville Trust Company as a [[stenographer]]. She was later promoted to a secretarial position.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}}{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Rather than taking collegiate-level courses, she enrolled at the [[American Bankers Association|American Institute of Banking]] and took night classes.<ref name=\"Meadville\"/> She later reflected that having background knowledge in finance and law helped her better understand the music business.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Although Seely was living in Pennsylvania still, she was getting increasingly frustrated by the Pennsylvania winters. One winter day, her car got caught in a snow bank and she was forced to walk home. \"I decided right then and there that I was ready to make a change,\" she recounted on her website.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}}\n\n==Music career==\n===1961-1965: Move to California and early songwriting===\nIn 1961, Seely made the decision to move to southern California. She left in her [[MG MGA|MGA Roadster convertible]], along with three other friends.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harman |first1=Ron |title=Crawford County Native Seely Celebrates 50th Anniversary as Grand Ole Opry Member |url=https://www.meadvilletribune.com/news/crawford-county-native-seely-celebrates-50th-anniversary-as-grand-ole-opry-member/article_9249aeb0-9a5a-11e7-b1e0-3fc30f51ca46.html |website=[[Meadville Tribune]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Upon arriving, she found employment in a bank in [[Beverly Hills, California]]. However, Seely was more interested in the music business. After a year, she left the job to take a lower-paying secretarial position at [[Liberty Records|Liberty]] and [[Imperial Records]] in [[Hollywood, California|Hollywood]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}}{{sfn|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} While working as a record label secretary, Seely wrote one of her first compositions as a songwriter, \"[[Anyone Who Knows What Love Is (Will Understand)]]\". Accompanying herself on piano, she tracked down Imperial Records writer [[Mickey Newbury]] to help finish the song.<ref name=\"Anyone\">{{cite web |last1=Bronson |first1=Fred |title='Anyone Who Knows What Love Is': Why An Obscure '60s Song Is Bigger Than Ever In 2018 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8470437/anyone-who-knows-what-love-is-black-mirror |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> It would be picked up by [[rhythm and blues music|R&B]] singer [[Irma Thomas]]. In 1964, it was released a single and became a major hit on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' pop and R&B charts.<ref>{{cite web |title=Irma Thomas: Billboard chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/irma-thomas/chart-history |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to secretarial work, Seely also worked as a [[disc jockey]] for the [[American Forces Network]] and appeared on a local California television show called ''Hollywood Jamboree''.<ref name=\"PBS\"/> She also continued her work as a songwriter. During the same period she began writing songs for [[Four Star Records|Four Star Music]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} As a songwriter, her songs were recorded by several country artists. One of the first vocalists to recorded a composition was [[Dottie West]] who cut the song \"It Just Take Practice\" for her 1965 album ''[[Dottie West Sings]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dottie West -- ''Dottie West Sings'' (1965, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Dottie-West-Sings/release/2211162 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> The same year, [[Connie Smith]] recorded \"Senses\" which was co-written with [[Glen Campbell]]. It was issued on Smith's studio album ''[[Cute 'n' Country]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Unterberger |first1=Richie |title=''Cute 'n' Country'' -- Connie Smith: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/cute-n-country-mw0000887273 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Her success as a songwriter led to a recording contract with [[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge Records]] in 1964.{{sfn|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Although the label issued three singles between 1964 and 1965, one of the songs received any notable attention.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref> The limited success in California allowed Seely to find other opportunities. Seely had built a friendship with Dottie West. It was West who encouraged her to move to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to further her career. At first, Seely was hesitant about leaving southern California. West then replied with, \"Nashville's where you learn.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Partridge |first1=Tamela Meredith |title=Jeannie Seely and David Frizzell co-headline at Nashville North |url=https://herald-review.com/entertainment/jeannie-seely-and-david-frizzell-co-headline-at-nashville-north/article_212d5efd-6874-571e-85b8-f359989fd882.html |website=[[Herald & Review]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Country songwriter [[Hank Cochran]] was also impressed by her musicianship and also encouraged a Nashville move.<ref name=\"PBS\"/>\n\n===1966\u20131968: \"Don't Touch Me\" and breakthrough===\nIn 1965, Seely officially moved to Nashville. \"When  I  arrived  in  town,  I  only  had  $50  and  a  [[Ford Falcon (North America)|Ford  Falcon]]  to  my  name,\" Seely recalled on her official website biography.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Once arriving, she attended the 1965 DJ Convention and found Hank Cochran at the event. Seely approached him saying, \"Well I'm here! Do you still want to work with me?\" Cochran replied, \"Yes, if you're going to let me make the decisions and do what I know is best for you.\"{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} Seely agreed and shortly afterward, she got a position on [[Porter Wagoner]]'s road and television show,{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}} replacing female artist [[Norma Jean (singer)|Norma Jean]].<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> While on the show, Seely searched for recording labels. However, she found little success in finding any labels interested in signing her.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Finally, [[Monument Records]], offered her a recording contract in 1966 and she remained at the label for several years.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|pp=2-3}} Seely recorded Cochran's newly-composed \"[[Don't Touch Me]]\" shortly after signing.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} Originally, [[Buck Owens]] had interest in recording it but Cochran declined, giving it to Seely instead.<ref name=\"Country Thang\">{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Arden |title=A Rather \u2018Risky\u2019 Song, \u201cDon\u2019t Touch Me\u201d Became A Hit |url=https://www.countrythangdaily.com/risky-dont-touch-seely/ |website=Country Thang Daily |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> Cochran and Seely's relationship would also turn romantic during this period and they would marry before the decade's end.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>\n{{quote box|quote=\"In 1966, Seely's '[[Don't Touch Me]]' took country women's sexuality from the [[honky-tonk]] into the bedroom even though it didn't end up there, and the on-again off-again ache in her voice retained its savor afterwards. But never again did she find a song at once so moral and so febrile.\"|source=\u2014''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]'' (1981)<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: S|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=S&bk=70|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\n\n\"Don't Touch Me\" was released as a single in March 1966 and became a major hit.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/><ref name=\"Joel Whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref> By June 1966, the single reached number 2 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Country Songs |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/country-songs/song/573335 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> In addition, the song crossed over to the [[Billboard Hot 100]] where it reached a peak of number 85.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Hot 100 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/HSI |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> The song's success prompted the release of her debut studio album, ''[[The Seely Style]]''. Released in September 1966, the album peaked at number eight on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums]] list and was her highest-charting album.<ref>{{cite web |title=''The Seely Style'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP/song/832439 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> \"Don't Touch Me\" also brought several awards to Seely. She later won the [[Best Female Country Vocal Performance]] accolade at the [[9th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\"Grammys\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely: Artist |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/jeannie-seely |website=[[Grammy Awards]] |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Seely was also invited to become a member of the [[Grand Ole Opry]] in 1967.{{sfn|Ttott, Walt|2012|p=475}}<ref name=\"Opry\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely -- Grand Ole Opry |url=https://www.opry.com/artists/jeannie-seely/ |website=[[Grand Ole Opry]] |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> \"Don't Touch Me\" would be Seely's biggest hit and [[list of signature songs|signature song]] as a recording artist.{{sfn|Ttott, Walt|2012|p=475}}<ref name=\"Joel Whitburn\"/>\n\nMusic journalists and writers have since commented on \"Don't Touch Me\". Writers Mary Bufwack and [[Robert K. Oermann]] called it \"a throbbing song of unfilled passion\". They also praised Seely's vocal delivery of the tune calling her performance to have \"aching conviction\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} Critic [[Robert Christgau]] gave the song a positive response as well, praising its message for women's sexuality.<ref name=\"CG\"/> Brian Mansfield of [[Allmusic]] called the song a \"great record\" in his review of Seely's 1993 compilation ''Greatest Hits on Monument''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mansfield |first1=Brian |title=''Greatest Hits on Monument'' -- Jeannie Seely: Review |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hits-on-monument-mw0000094907 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Ace Collins would later comment on the song's notoriety in his book, ''The Stories Behind Country Music\u2019s All-Time Greatest 100 Songs''. \"Cochran\u2018s  \u0333Don\u2018t  Touch  Me\u2018has  stood  the  test  of  time  like  few  other  works.  Hauntingly beautiful, poetry set to meter, this composition merits particular praise for the exquisite manner in which it relates its story of love, doubt, and commitment,\" he wrote.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Collins |first1=Ace |title=The Stories Behind Country Music\u2019s All-Time Greatest 100 Songs |date=1996 |publisher=Boulevard Books |isbn=0756755816}}</ref>\n\nSeely had success in further releases for the Monument label.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Her follow-up to \"Don't Touch Me\" also became a major hit. The song, \"[[It's Only Love (Jeannie Seely song)|It's Only Love]]\", reached the top 20 of the ''Billboard'' country singles chart in October 1966.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"It's Only Love\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/835152 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> In March 1967, Monument issued her second studio album entitled, ''[[Thanks, Hank!]]''. The album was a collection of tracks written by Hank Cochran, who had been writing much of her material by this point.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Thanks, Hank!'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Monument Records]] |date=March 1967}}</ref> Greg Adams of [[Allmusic]] considered Seely's voice to be more comparable to that of [[pop music|pop]] rather than country. Nonetheless, he gave the record three out of five stars.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Greg |title=''Thanks, Hank!'' -- Jeannie Seely -- Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/thanks-hank%21-mw0000967234 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"[[A Wanderin' Man]]\", reached number 13 on the ''Billboard'' country list in February 1967, becoming her third major hit.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"A Wanderin' Man\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/838186 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Seely had a second top ten hit with the single \"[[I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)]]\" in early 1968.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/836772 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The song, also written by Cochran, prompted the release of her [[I'll Love You More|third studio album]] in February 1968.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''I'll Love You More'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=February 1968}}</ref> The demand for Seely's public appearances also increased during this time. She toured for extensive periods of time, often traveling from coast to coast.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=3}} The heavy schedule caused for Seely to leave Porter Wagoner's show and he replaced her with [[Dolly Parton]].<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Instead of appearing with Wagoner, she worked regularly with country artist [[Ernest Tubb]] and appeared on his syndicated television show.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=3}}\n\n===1969\u20131977: Move to Decca Records, Jack Greene duets and solo hits===\nIn 1969, Seely left Monument and switched to [[Decca Records]].{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}} She was now working with producer [[Owen Bradley]],{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=4}} who produced her [[Jeannie Seely (1969 album)|eponymous studio album]] the same year. Among its tracks was the song \"Just Enough to Start Me Dreamin'\", which was released as a radio single.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Jeannie Seely'' (Liner Notes & Album Information) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=April 1969}}</ref> Around this period, she made regular appearances on television programs including ''[[Hee Haw]]'' and ''[[The Glen Campbell Goodtime Hour]]''.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=4}} Seely also toured overseas entertaining the [[United States Armed Forces|American military]]. She traveled to various countries including [[China]], [[Thailand]] and [[Vietnam]].{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}} Performing for the military inspired Seely to become more patriotic. Once returning to the United States, she performed at the Grand Ole Opry. In one Opry show, she commented that the [[Flag of the United States|American flag]] was not on display. Following this statement, the Opry started displaying an American flag, which still exists at the venue today.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=4}}\n[[File:Jack Greene.JPG|thumb|left|170px|For several years, Seely recorded and toured with country artist [[Jack Greene]].]]\n\nIn addition to a solo career at Decca, Seely collaborated with country artist [[Jack Greene]]. Their first release together was the single \"[[Wish I Didn't Have to Miss You]]\".<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}} A commercial success, the song reached number two on the ''Billboard'' country singles chart in early 1970.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Wish I Didn't Have to Miss You\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jack-greene/chart-history/CSI/song/837467 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The song prompted their first [[Jack Greene, Jeannie Seely|studio album]] to be issued in January 1970, which reached number 18 on the country albums list.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Jack Greene, Jeannie Seely'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jack-greene/chart-history/CLP/song/831852 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The pair later released another studio album in 1972 entitled ''[[Two for the Show (Jack Greene and Jeannie Seely album)|Two for the Show]]''. It included two singles, starting with 1971's \"[[Much Oblige]]\", which became a top twenty country hit.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Much Oblige\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jack-greene/chart-history/CSI/song/839863 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Greene and Seely's duet success led to the creation of their own traveling road show from 1969 to 1972.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|pp=302-03}} The duo toured and performed at venues ranging from [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York, New York|New York City]] to [[Wembley Stadium]] in [[London, England|London]].{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=4}} Their concerts and recording would receive recognition from several award programs. They were nominated by the [[Grammy Awards]] in 1970<ref name=\"Grammys\"/> and were nominated four times for the [[Country Music Association]]'s \"Vocal Duo of the Year\" between 1972 and 1975.<ref name=\"CMA\">{{cite web |title=Past Winners and Nominees: Jeannie Seely |url=https://cmaawards.com/past-winners-and-nominees/?appSession=9093S4929571M1IR18576495GF10XXQOHK9Q8IE3DCMYFEIWZ17E3C90JMWMD00EM851M17AYT2RLA7WU18V8EWMT89ZUJHXFQ73I8Y0Q756132V0B6HN29R170AV729 |website=[[Country Music Association Awards]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1970s, Seely's solo recordings had declined at radio. Her sixth studio album, ''[[Please Be My New Love]]'' (1970), did not receive a ''Billboard'' placement.<ref name=\"whitburn\"/> Further singles reached lower positions on the ''Billboard'' country songs chart during this time. Singles such as \"Tell Me Again\" (1970) and the self-composed \"Farm in Pennsyltucky\" (1972) did not peak past the top 50.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Farm in Pennsyltucky\" |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/837080 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\"Tell Me Again\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/840009 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> While not achieving any solo achievements, Seely's songwriting was more successful. In 1972, she composed \"Leavin' and Sayin' Goodbye\", which was recorded by [[Faron Young]].<ref name=\"Country Universe\">{{cite web |last1=Coyne |first1=Kevin John |title=100 Greatest Women, #59: Jeannie Seely |url=http://www.countryuniverse.net/2018/06/14/100-greatest-women-59-jeannie-seely/ |website=Country Universe |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Released as a single, it became a major hit when it reached number nine on the country chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Leavin' and Sayin' Goodbye\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/faron-young/chart-history/CSI/song/839166 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Other country artists recorded her compositions during the 1970s. Among these performers was Ernest Tubb who recorded \"Sometimes I Do\". It was released as a single via First Generation Records in 1977.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ernest Tubb -- ''Sometimes I Do'' (1977, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/fr/Ernest-Tubb-Sometimes-I-Do-Half-My-Hearts-In-Texas/release/4371954 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> [[Merle Haggard]] recorded \"Life of a Rodeo Cowboy\" in 1978. Seely later called it a \"great compliment\" to have Haggard cut the track.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Carrie |title=Jeannie Seely Recalls the Conversation That Inspired 'Life of a Rodeo Cowboy' |url=https://theboot.com/jeannie-seely-life-of-a-rodeo-cowboy-inspiration/ |website=The Boot |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeely returned to the popularity charts with solo success in 1973. Hank Cochran had reworked the traditional tune, \"May I Sleep in Your Barn Tonight\" to the country song, \"[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms]]\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} Released as a single, it became Seely's biggest solo hit in several years when it peaked at number six on the ''Billboard'' country songs list.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Can I Sleep in Your Arms\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/839619 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Cochran had also reworked the Appalachian song, \"[[Come All You Fair and Tender Ladies]]\", to the title of \"[[Lucky Ladies (song)|Lucky Ladies]]\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} It also became a major hit, peaking at number 11 on the country songs chart in February 1974.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Lucky Ladies\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/835669 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Her ninth studio album, ''[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms/Lucky Ladies]]'' would be released in late 1973 and reached number 15 on the Top Country Albums chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Can I Sleep in Your Arms/Lucky Ladies'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP/song/831427 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Seely then moved to [[Columbia Records]] where she recorded for several years.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Some music writers noticed a change in her material while at Columbia. Mary Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann called Seely's Columbia recordings to be \"spicy\" and \"franker\" than her previous work, highlighting the hits \"Take Me to Bed\" and \"We're Still in Hangin' in There Ain't We Jessi\". The latter tune documented the marital conflicts of several female country artists including [[Jessi Colter]] and [[Dottie West]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} In addition, \"Take Me to Bed\" would be her last single to date to make a ''Billboard'' chart appearance.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Take Me to Bed\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/363176 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1977\u20131989: Car accident and career slow-down===\nIn June 1977, Seely was involved in a car accident in [[Goodlettsville, Tennessee]], a suburb outside of Nashville.{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}}<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite news |last1=Krebbs |first1=Albin |title=Notes on People |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/06/30/archives/westchester-opinion-notes-on-people.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 30, 1977}}</ref> Seely had been driving her vehicle when it crashed into a tree. She was admitted to Nashville Memorial Hospital where she was reported to be in \"fair condition\". Among her injuries, Seely suffered a fractured jaw, broken ribs,<ref name=\"NY Times\"/> a punctured lung and a collapsed lung. Upon arriving at the hospital she was given same-day surgery to repair her lung.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Indiana Gazette from Indiana Pennsylvania [title unknown] |publisher=[[Indiana Gazette]] |date=June 29, 1977}}</ref> Seely eventually recovered from her injuries<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> and later reflected on her appreciation for her life. \"You know, it sounds like a cliche, but it's true that your perspective changes when you have a close call, what you took for granted you come to appreciate more,\" Seely commented on her official website biography.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=5}} She later would credit friend Dottie West for her support during her recovery. \"Dottie was there as much as she possibly could be, helping me through that time. After I got out of the hospital and was homebound, one time, she drove me out to her place just for a change of scenery,\" she commented in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thanki |first1=Juli |title=Country Trailblazer Dottie West Remembered |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/08/26/country-trailblazer-dottie-west-remembered/88531556/ |website=[[The Tennessean]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her recovery, Seely returned to performing but was no longer signed to a recording label.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> It became more challenging for Seely to tour due to fewer concert engagements. \"The only bright spot in my life right now is a flashing neon sign...and even that comes and goes,\" she stated.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} When opportunities were available, Seely continued to work. Among her first major engagements was a tour with [[Willie Nelson]]. Her appearances with Nelson led to an appearance on the [[Honeysuckle Rose (album)|soundtrack]] of his film ''[[Honeysuckle Rose (film)|Honeysuckle Rose]]'' (1980).<ref name=\"Country Universe\"/> Along with Hank Cochran and Nelson, she performed a collaborative version of the song \"[[Make the World Go Away]]\" for the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Honeysuckle Rose'': Willie Nelson: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/honeysuckle-rose-mw0000190231 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> In 1982, Jack Greene reunited for a [[Greatest Hits (Jack Greene and Jeannie Seely album)|studio album]] containing re-recordings of their previous hits.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Greene |first1=Jack |last2=Seely |first2=Jeannie |title=''Greatest Hits'' (Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=[[Gusto Records]] |date=1982}}</ref> Seely also looked for other music-related opportunities. In 1985, she opened up a nightclub in Nashville named \"Jeannie Seely's Country Club\". Among the venue's major events was a premier music party hosted by Seely on its opening in June 1985.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nashville Then: Best of 1985 Music |url=https://www.tennessean.com/picture-gallery/news/local/2015/12/30/nashville-then-best-of-1985-music/78080448/ |website=[[The Tennessean]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> However, in 1986 the club closed down after only a year of being open to the public.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}}\n[[File:Jeannie Seely (3469185223).jpg|thumb|right|170px|Seely at the Opry, 2007.]]\n\nDuring this time, Seely also became the first female Grand Opry member to host a half hour segment.<ref name=\"Digital Journal\">{{cite web |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Country queen Jeannie Seely receives honorary doctorate from LMU |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/entertainment/country-queen-jeannie-seely-receives-honorary-doctorate-from-lmu/article/563677 |website=Digital Journal |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> In 1985, she was called to replace [[Del Reeves]], who was stuck in a snowstorm.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=5}} From this point forward Seely and other female performers were provided opportunities to host the Opry.<ref name=\"Digital Journal\"/> Seely would also be a recurrent host of [[The Nashville Network]]'s ''Opry Backstage'' show, where she interviewed artists following their Opry performances. Along with the Opry, Seely also appeared on several other network programs during this time. This included appearances on ''[[Nashville Now]]'', ''[[Crook & Chase]]'', ''[[Family Feud]]'' and ''Prime Time Country''.<ref name=\"Country Universe\"/>{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=6}}\n\n===1990\u2013present: Return to recording===\nSeely returned to a more active music career in the 1990s. In 1990, she released her [[Jeannie Seely (1990 album)|eleventh studio album]], which was issued on her own recording label.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Jeannie Seely'' (Cassette Liner Notes & Album Information) |journal=Faux Paw Productions/Shadpoke Records |date=1990}}</ref> In 1993, she appeared alongside [[Stonewall Jackson (musician)|Stonewall Jackson]] in the music video for \"[[Trashy Women]]\", a song by the band [[Confederate Railroad]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Morris |first1=Edward |title=Nashville Scene |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=July 10, 1993 |page=p. 24}}</ref> When released as a single, the song reached number ten on the ''Billboard'' country songs chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Trashy Women\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Confederate-Railroad/chart-history/CSI/song/19146 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> The following year, her first album of [[holiday music]] was released called ''[[Number One Christmas]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Number One Christmas'' -- Jeannie Seely -- Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/number-one-christmas-mw0000895262 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> While not recording or touring, Seely maintained an active presence as a Grand Ole Opry member. She also continued making regular appearances on ''The Nashville Network''.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=6}} Seely's songwriting was also a part of her music career in the 90s. In 1997, [[Lorrie Morgan]] recorded \"I've Enjoyed as Much of This as I Can Stand\", which was composed with [[Bill Anderson (singer)|Bill Anderson]]. Morgan's version was released on her 1997 studio album, ''[[Shakin' Things Up]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Owens |first1=Thom |title=''Shakin' Things Up'' -- Lorrie Morgan -- Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/shakin-things-up-mw0000026152 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Before the end of the decade, Seely released her thirteenth studio effort, ''Been There, Sung That'' (1999). The project was self-produced and featured duets with [[T. Graham Brown]] and [[Willie Nelson]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Been There...Sung That!'' (Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=Faux Paw Productions/Shadpoke Records |date=1999}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jeannie on Opry 040818.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Jeannie Seely in performance at the [[Grand Ole Opry]], 2010s.]]\nIn the early 2000's, Seely turned her attention towards [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] projects. In 2001, she sang alongside [[Ralph Stanley]] on his studio album ''Clinch Mountain Sweethearts''. On the album, they performed the track \"I'm Ready to Go\".<ref>{{cite web |title=''Clinch Mountain Sweethearts'': Ralph Stanley: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/clinch-mountain-sweethearts-mw0000014135 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Seely followed this in 2003 with the studio album ''Life's Highway''.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> The record's bluegrass and acoustic sounds received positive reviews from critics. John Lupton of ''Country Standard Time'' called it an album \"chock-full of top level bluegrass talent.\" Lupton also praised Seely's vocal performance on the album, calling it \"classic country\" and \"timeless\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lupton |first1=John |title=Jeannie Seely travels life's highways |url=https://www.countrystandardtime.com/d/article.asp?xid=734 |website=Country Standard Time |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Bob Mitchell of the ''Louisville Music News'' gave the album mostly a positive response. \"Overall, this recording lacks the earthy intensity and drive that characterizes authentic traditional Bluegrass. But, make no mistake, Life's Highway is enjoyable and features some of country and bluegrass's finest musicians,\" he wrote.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mitchell |first1=Bob |title=Keeping it Real Life's Highway (OMS) Jeannie Seely |url=http://www.louisvillemusicnews.net/webmanager/index.php?WEB_CAT_ID=50&storyid=2900&headline=Jeannie_Seely_-_Life%27s_Highway&issueid=183 |website=Louisville Music News |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 2000s, Seely continued an active touring schedule. During several summers, she held concerts at the ''[[Dollywood]]'' theme park and toured in [[Ireland]].{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=6}} While taking time to tour, Seely also found time to record her fifteenth studio album. In 2011, ''Vintage Country: Old But Treasured'' was released on her latest label, Cheyenne Records.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> \"...like I always joke onstage, I\u2019m speaking about the music when I say old but treasured,\" Seely commented in a 2011 interview.<ref name=\"Nashville Music Guide\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely\u2019s Vintage Country Offers Timeless Country Classics |url=https://www.nashvillemusicguide.com/jeannie-seely%E2%80%99s-vintage-country-offers-timeless-country-classics/ |website=Nashville Music Guide |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> The album was a collection of country music standards previously recorded by others. Among its songs was [[Bobbie Gentry]]'s \"[[Ode to Billie Joe]]\" and [[Billy Walker (musician)|Billy Walker]]'s \"[[Funny How Time Slips Away]]\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Titusville native Jeannie Seely releases album of country favorites |url=https://www.titusvilleherald.com/news/article_05820ff0-a7bd-50f5-a014-bd74754a24ed.html |website=Titusville Herald |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> During the 2010s, Seely's touring schedule remained busy as she performed at events including the [[CMA Music Festival]] and the R.O.P.E.'s \"Summer Spectacular\" show.<ref name=\"Nashville Music Guide\"/> She returned to recording with her sixteenth studio album, ''[[Written in Song]]'' (2017).<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> All fourteen of the album's tracks were composed by Seely and many were first recorded by other artists.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nicholson |first1=Jessica |title=Jeannie Seely Celebrates Release of \u2018Written In Song\u2019 |url=https://musicrow.com/2017/01/jeannie-seely-celebrates-release-of-written-in-song/ |website=Music Row |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Markos Papadatos of the ''Digital Journal'' gave the album an \"A\" rating in his review. \"Overall, Jeannie Seely soars on her new album, ''Written in Song''. \"Miss Country Soul\" is back stronger than ever. There is a variety on her latest musical effort.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Jeannie Seely soars on new country album ''Written in Song'' |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/review-jeannie-seely-soars-on-new-country-album-written-in-song/article/483167#ixzz6JjY2hqQm |website=Digital Journal |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn late 2019, Seely announced the release of her seventeenth studio recording called ''An American Classic''. The project will be produced by [[Don Cusic]] and will be released on [[Curb Records]] in June 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=LMU Honors Jeannie Seely With Honorary Doctorate of Arts Degree |url=https://www.musicconnection.com/lmu-honors-jeannie-seely-honorary-doctorate-arts-degree/ |website=Music Connection |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Jeannie Seely discography}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Year''' || '''Award program''' || '''Award''' || '''Result'''\n|-\n| 1966 || [[Billboard magazine]] || ''Most Promising New Artist'' || Won\n|-\n| 1966 || [[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox magazine]] || ''Most Promising New Artist'' || Won\n|-\n| 1966 || [[Record World|Record World magazine]] || ''Most Promising New Artist'' || Won\n|-\n| 1967 || [[Grammy Awards]] || ''[[Best Female Country Vocal Performance]]'' for \"[[Don't Touch Me]]\" || Won\n|-\n| 1972 || [[CMA Awards]] || ''Vocal Duo of the Year'' (with [[Jack Greene]]) || Nominated\n|-\n| 1973 || [[CMA Awards]] || ''Vocal Duo of the Year'' (with Jack Greene) || Nominated\n|-\n| 1974 || [[CMA Awards]] || ''Vocal Duo of the Year'' (with Jack Greene) || Nominated\n|-\n| 1975 || [[CMA Awards]] || ''Vocal Duo of the Year'' (with Jack Greene) || Nominated\n|-\n| 2017 || R.O.P.E || ''Entertainer of the Year'' (with [[Gene Watson]]) || Won\n|}\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |last2=Bufwack |first2=Mary A. |title=Finding Her Voice: Women in Country Music: 1800\u20132000 |date=2003 |publisher=The Country Music Press & Vanderbilt University Press |location=Nashville, TN |isbn=0-8265-1432-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/findinghervoicew0000bufw|ref={{SfnRef|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003}} }}\n* {{cite web |author1=Seely, Jeannie |author2= Harman, Ron|year=2002|url=http://jeannieseely.com/docs/Jeannie%20Seely%20Full%20Length%20Bio.pdf|title=Biography|work=Jeannie Seely.com|accessdate=April 10, 2020|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Trott |first1=Walt |title=The Encyclopedia of Country Music |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-19-517608-7|ref={{SfnRef|Trott, Walt|2012}} }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.jeannieseely.com/}}\n* [http://www.cmt.com/artists/az/seely_jeannie/artist.jhtml Jeannie Seely at CMT.com]\n\n{{Jeannie Seely}}\n{{Grand Ole Opry}}\n{{Grand Ole Opry members}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seely, Jeannie}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female country singers]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Challenge Records artists]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grand Ole Opry members]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Monument Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Titusville, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jeannie Seely\n| image              = Jeannie Seely at the Opry.jpg\n| caption            = Jeannie Seely at the [[Grand Ole Opry]], 2010s.\n| birth_name         = Marilyn Jeanne Seely\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1940|07|06}} \n| birth_place        = [[Titusville, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|actress|author|[[record producer|producer]]}}\n| years_active       = 1962\u2013present\n| home_town          = [[Townville, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| spouse             = {{ubl|{{marriage|[[Hank Cochran]]|1969|1981|reason=divorced}}|{{marriage|Gene Ward|2010}}}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed              = yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[Country music|Country]]|[[Nashville Sound]]}}\n| instrument         = Vocals\n| label              = {{hlist|[[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge]]|[[Monument Records|Monument]]|[[Decca Records|Decca]]/[[MCA Records|MCA]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|Power Pak|Shadpoke|OMS|Cheyenne}}\n| associated_acts    = {{hlist|[[Jack Greene]]|[[Dottie West]]|[[Willie Nelson]]}}\n| website            = {{URL|jeannieseely.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Jeannie Seely''' (born '''Marilyn Jeanne Seely'''; July 6, 1940) is an American [[country music]] singer, songwriter, and record producer. She also has several acting credits and published a book. Seely found success with the [[Grammy Award]]-winning hit \"[[Don't Touch Me]]\" (1966). Her [[soul music|soul]]-inspired vocal delivery<ref name=\"Meadville\">{{cite web |title=Big Honor for Jeannie Seely Later This Month |url=https://www.meadvilletribune.com/news/big-honor-for-jeannie-seely-later-this-month/article_33217218-12b4-11ea-9446-8ba8dd6a496c.html |website=[[Meadville Tribune]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> was praised by music professionals, who gave her the nickname of \"Miss Country Soul\".<ref name=\"PBS\">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Ken |title=Country Music: Jeannie Seely Biography |url=https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/country-music/jeannie-seely-biography/ |publisher=[[PBS]] |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Seely is also known for her membership and presence on the [[Grand Ole Opry]], where she has been active for over 50 years.\n\nSeely was born and raised in northwestern [[Pennsylvania]]. Developing an early interest in country music, she performed regularly on local radio and television stations. Following high school graduation, she worked at a local bank before moving to southern California. It was on the west coast where she rediscovered country music. Originally a secretary at [[Imperial Records]], she soon was writing songs for the company as well. Many of these songs would be recorded by other artists. In 1965, she signed her own recording contract with [[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge Records]]. Seely then moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to pursue a recording career. In Nashville, Seely's \"Don't Touch Me\" was released on [[Monument Records]] and was a major hit single. She followed it with several more hits, including \"[[A Wanderin' Man]]\" (1967) and \"[[I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)]]\" (1968). \n\nSeely started collaborating with [[Jack Greene]] in the late 1960s. The pair toured and had recordings together for several years. Their biggest single would be 1970's \"[[Wish I Didn't Have to Miss You]]\". Seely had solo success during this same time with \"[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms]]\" (1973) and \"[[Lucky Ladies]]\" (1974). In 1977, Seely's career went on hiatus after sustaining severe injuries in an automobile accident. With the support of others, she resumed her career. Seely took a more diverse career approach in the years following her accident. She appeared in the [[Willie Nelson]] film ''[[Honeysuckle Rose (film)|Honeysuckle Rose]]'', acted in several stage plays and performed in concert regularly. During this period, Seely also became the first female artist to host the Grand Ole Opry. In addition, she released her first and only book to date, ''Pieces of a Puzzled Mind''.\n\nIn the 1990s, Seely returned to recording albums. This was launched with a 1990 eponymous release, followed by her first album of [[holiday music]] in 1994 called ''Number One Christmas''. In 1999, she released the studio album ''Been There Sung That'', which included duets with several artists. In 2003, Seely issued ''Life's Highway'', a studio album that fused [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] with traditional country music. Her most recent studio release was 2017's ''[[Written in Song]]'', which was issued on her own record label. Seely has since been a consistent host of the Grand Ole Opry and has been a regular host of a weekly radio program on [[Sirius XM]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Titusville Trust Company.jpg|thumb|right|220px|The original Titusville Trust Company building. After high school, Seely was employed there.]]\nSeely was born Marilyn Jeanne Seely in [[Titusville, Pennsylvania]] on July 6, 1940.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\">{{cite web |last1=Huey |first1=Steve |title=Jeannie Seely: Biography & History |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jeannie-seely-mn0000234004/biography |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Although born in Titusville, she was raised in nearby [[Townville, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"Meadville\"/> Seely was the youngest of four children born to Irene and Leo Seely. Leo Seely was a farmer and an employer of the Titusville Steel Mill. On weekends, he worked at local square dances and played the [[fiddle]]. Irene Seely was a homemaker who also enjoyed singing with her children while cooking.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=1}} As a young child, family and friends often gathered together to perform. \"It seemed like everybody back in the country played guitars and fiddles, and when we got together there was always pickin\u2018 and singin\u2018,\" Seely recalled.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=1}} She developed an interest in [[country music]] during her early years. On Saturday nights, the Seely family would spent time listening to the [[Grand Ole Opry]] in her parents' car. Mrs. Seely also brought her children to country music shows at a local venue named Hillbilly Park. At the park, the family often watched performances by country artists such as [[Little Jimmy Dickens]], [[Bill Monroe]] and [[Jean Shepard]].{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|pp=1\u20132}}\n\nAt age 11, she started performing on a local radio station, located in [[Meadville, Pennsylvania]]. Because of her short height and the lack of nonadjustable microphones, Seely had to stand on top of wooden containers to sing.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=1}} At age 16, Seely became a regular performer on [[WICU (AM)|WICU]], a local television station in [[Erie, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"PBS\"/> She recounted being ridiculed by her high school peers in choosing to sing country music. \"They all made fun of me because I sang country. I grew up poor and in those days calling someone 'country' was a put-down,\" she said in 2003.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} In high school, Seely was a [[cheerleading|cheerleader]] and an [[honors student]]. In 1958, she graduated from Townville High School at age eighteen.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} \n\nInstead of attending college, Seely took a job at the Titusville Trust Company as a [[stenographer]]. She was later promoted to a secretarial position.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}}{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Rather than taking collegiate-level courses, she enrolled at the [[American Bankers Association|American Institute of Banking]] and took night classes.<ref name=\"Meadville\"/> She later reflected that having background knowledge in finance and law helped her better understand the music business.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Although Seely was living in Pennsylvania still, she was getting increasingly frustrated by the Pennsylvania winters. One winter day, her car got caught in a snow bank and she was forced to walk home. \"I decided right then and there that I was ready to make a change,\" she recounted on her website.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}}\n\n==Music career==\n===1961-1965: Move to California and early songwriting===\nIn 1961, Seely made the decision to move to southern California. She left in her [[MG MGA|MGA Roadster convertible]], along with three other friends.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harman |first1=Ron |title=Crawford County Native Seely Celebrates 50th Anniversary as Grand Ole Opry Member |url=https://www.meadvilletribune.com/news/crawford-county-native-seely-celebrates-50th-anniversary-as-grand-ole-opry-member/article_9249aeb0-9a5a-11e7-b1e0-3fc30f51ca46.html |website=[[Meadville Tribune]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Upon arriving, she found employment in a bank in [[Beverly Hills, California]]. However, Seely was more interested in the music business. After a year, she left the job to take a lower-paying secretarial position at [[Liberty Records|Liberty]] and [[Imperial Records]] in [[Hollywood, California|Hollywood]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}}{{sfn|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} While working as a record label secretary, Seely wrote one of her first compositions as a songwriter, \"[[Anyone Who Knows What Love Is (Will Understand)]]\". Accompanying herself on piano, she tracked down Imperial Records writer [[Mickey Newbury]] to help finish the song.<ref name=\"Anyone\">{{cite web |last1=Bronson |first1=Fred |title='Anyone Who Knows What Love Is': Why An Obscure '60s Song Is Bigger Than Ever In 2018 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8470437/anyone-who-knows-what-love-is-black-mirror |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> It would be picked up by [[rhythm and blues music|R&B]] singer [[Irma Thomas]]. In 1964, it was released a single and became a major hit on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' pop and R&B charts.<ref>{{cite web |title=Irma Thomas: Billboard chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/irma-thomas/chart-history |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to secretarial work, Seely also worked as a [[disc jockey]] for the [[American Forces Network]] and appeared on a local California television show called ''Hollywood Jamboree''.<ref name=\"PBS\"/> She also continued her work as a songwriter. During the same period she began writing songs for [[Four Star Records|Four Star Music]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} As a songwriter, her songs were recorded by several country artists. One of the first vocalists to recorded a composition was [[Dottie West]] who cut the song \"It Just Take Practice\" for her 1965 album ''[[Dottie West Sings]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dottie West -- ''Dottie West Sings'' (1965, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Dottie-West-Sings/release/2211162 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> The same year, [[Connie Smith]] recorded \"Senses\" which was co-written with [[Glen Campbell]]. It was issued on Smith's studio album ''[[Cute 'n' Country]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Unterberger |first1=Richie |title=''Cute 'n' Country'' -- Connie Smith: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/cute-n-country-mw0000887273 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Her success as a songwriter led to a recording contract with [[Challenge Records (1950s-60s label)|Challenge Records]] in 1964.{{sfn|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Although the label issued three singles between 1964 and 1965, one of the songs received any notable attention.<ref name=\"whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref> The limited success in California allowed Seely to find other opportunities. Seely had built a friendship with Dottie West. It was West who encouraged her to move to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to further her career. At first, Seely was hesitant about leaving southern California. West then replied with, \"Nashville's where you learn.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Partridge |first1=Tamela Meredith |title=Jeannie Seely and David Frizzell co-headline at Nashville North |url=https://herald-review.com/entertainment/jeannie-seely-and-david-frizzell-co-headline-at-nashville-north/article_212d5efd-6874-571e-85b8-f359989fd882.html |website=[[Herald & Review]] |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Country songwriter [[Hank Cochran]] was also impressed by her musicianship and also encouraged a Nashville move.<ref name=\"PBS\"/>\n\n===1966\u20131968: \"Don't Touch Me\" and breakthrough===\nIn 1965, Seely officially moved to Nashville. \"When  I  arrived  in  town,  I  only  had  $50  and  a  [[Ford Falcon (North America)|Ford  Falcon]]  to  my  name,\" Seely recalled on her official website biography.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Once arriving, she attended the 1965 DJ Convention and found Hank Cochran at the event. Seely approached him saying, \"Well I'm here! Do you still want to work with me?\" Cochran replied, \"Yes, if you're going to let me make the decisions and do what I know is best for you.\"{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} Seely agreed and shortly afterward, she got a position on [[Porter Wagoner]]'s road and television show,{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}} replacing female artist [[Norma Jean (singer)|Norma Jean]].<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> While on the show, Seely searched for recording labels. However, she found little success in finding any labels interested in signing her.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=2}} Finally, [[Monument Records]], offered her a recording contract in 1966 and she remained at the label for several years.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|pp=2-3}} Seely recorded Cochran's newly-composed \"[[Don't Touch Me]]\" shortly after signing.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} Originally, [[Buck Owens]] had interest in recording it but Cochran declined, giving it to Seely instead.<ref name=\"Country Thang\">{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Arden |title=A Rather \u2018Risky\u2019 Song, \u201cDon\u2019t Touch Me\u201d Became A Hit |url=https://www.countrythangdaily.com/risky-dont-touch-seely/ |website=Country Thang Daily |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> Cochran and Seely's relationship would also turn romantic during this period and they would marry before the decade's end.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>\n{{quote box|quote=\"In 1966, Seely's '[[Don't Touch Me]]' took country women's sexuality from the [[honky-tonk]] into the bedroom even though it didn't end up there, and the on-again off-again ache in her voice retained its savor afterwards. But never again did she find a song at once so moral and so febrile.\"|source=\u2014''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]'' (1981)<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: S|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=S&bk=70|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>|width=25%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}\n\n\"Don't Touch Me\" was released as a single in March 1966 and became a major hit.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/><ref name=\"Joel Whitburn\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=0-89820-177-2}}</ref> By June 1966, the single reached number 2 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Country Songs |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/country-songs/song/573335 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> In addition, the song crossed over to the [[Billboard Hot 100]] where it reached a peak of number 85.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Don't Touch Me\" chart history: Hot 100 |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/HSI |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> The song's success prompted the release of her debut studio album, ''[[The Seely Style]]''. Released in September 1966, the album peaked at number eight on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums]] list and was her highest-charting album.<ref>{{cite web |title=''The Seely Style'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP/song/832439 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> \"Don't Touch Me\" also brought several awards to Seely. She later won the [[Best Female Country Vocal Performance]] accolade at the [[9th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref name=\"Grammys\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely: Artist |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/jeannie-seely |website=[[Grammy Awards]] |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Seely was also invited to become a member of the [[Grand Ole Opry]] in 1967.{{sfn|Ttott, Walt|2012|p=475}}<ref name=\"Opry\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely -- Grand Ole Opry |url=https://www.opry.com/artists/jeannie-seely/ |website=[[Grand Ole Opry]] |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> \"Don't Touch Me\" would be Seely's biggest hit and [[list of signature songs|signature song]] as a recording artist.{{sfn|Ttott, Walt|2012|p=475}}<ref name=\"Joel Whitburn\"/>\n\nMusic journalists and writers have since commented on \"Don't Touch Me\". Writers Mary Bufwack and [[Robert K. Oermann]] called it \"a throbbing song of unfilled passion\". They also praised Seely's vocal delivery of the tune calling her performance to have \"aching conviction\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=301}} Critic [[Robert Christgau]] gave the song a positive response as well, praising its message for women's sexuality.<ref name=\"CG\"/> Brian Mansfield of [[Allmusic]] called the song a \"great record\" in his review of Seely's 1993 compilation ''Greatest Hits on Monument''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mansfield |first1=Brian |title=''Greatest Hits on Monument'' -- Jeannie Seely: Review |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hits-on-monument-mw0000094907 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Ace Collins would later comment on the song's notoriety in his book, ''The Stories Behind Country Music\u2019s All-Time Greatest 100 Songs''. \"Cochran\u2018s  \u0333Don\u2018t  Touch  Me\u2018has  stood  the  test  of  time  like  few  other  works.  Hauntingly beautiful, poetry set to meter, this composition merits particular praise for the exquisite manner in which it relates its story of love, doubt, and commitment,\" he wrote.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Collins |first1=Ace |title=The Stories Behind Country Music\u2019s All-Time Greatest 100 Songs |date=1996 |publisher=Boulevard Books |isbn=0756755816}}</ref>\n\nSeely had success in further releases for the Monument label.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Her follow-up to \"Don't Touch Me\" also became a major hit. The song, \"[[It's Only Love (Jeannie Seely song)|It's Only Love]]\", reached the top 20 of the ''Billboard'' country singles chart in October 1966.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"It's Only Love\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/835152 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> In March 1967, Monument issued her second studio album entitled, ''[[Thanks, Hank!]]''. The album was a collection of tracks written by Hank Cochran, who had been writing much of her material by this point.<ref name=\"Liner Notes\">{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Thanks, Hank!'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Monument Records]] |date=March 1967}}</ref> Greg Adams of [[Allmusic]] considered Seely's voice to be more comparable to that of [[pop music|pop]] rather than country. Nonetheless, he gave the record three out of five stars.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Greg |title=''Thanks, Hank!'' -- Jeannie Seely -- Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/thanks-hank%21-mw0000967234 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"[[A Wanderin' Man]]\", reached number 13 on the ''Billboard'' country list in February 1967, becoming her third major hit.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"A Wanderin' Man\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/838186 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> Seely had a second top ten hit with the single \"[[I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)]]\" in early 1968.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"I'll Love You More (Than You'll Need)\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/836772 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The song, also written by Cochran, prompted the release of her [[I'll Love You More|third studio album]] in February 1968.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''I'll Love You More'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=February 1968}}</ref> The demand for Seely's public appearances also increased during this time. She toured for extensive periods of time, often traveling from coast to coast.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=3}} The heavy schedule caused for Seely to leave Porter Wagoner's show and he replaced her with [[Dolly Parton]].<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Instead of appearing with Wagoner, she worked regularly with country artist [[Ernest Tubb]] and appeared on his syndicated television show.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=3}}\n\n===1969\u20131977: Move to Decca Records, Jack Greene duets and solo hits===\nIn 1969, Seely left Monument and switched to [[Decca Records]].{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}} She was now working with producer [[Owen Bradley]],{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=4}} who produced her [[Jeannie Seely (1969 album)|eponymous studio album]] the same year. Among its tracks was the song \"Just Enough to Start Me Dreamin'\", which was released as a radio single.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Jeannie Seely'' (Liner Notes & Album Information) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=April 1969}}</ref> Around this period, she made regular appearances on television programs including ''[[Hee Haw]]'' and ''[[The Glen Campbell Goodtime Hour]]''.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=4}} Seely also toured overseas entertaining the [[United States Armed Forces|American military]]. She traveled to various countries including [[China]], [[Thailand]] and [[Vietnam]].{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}} Performing for the military inspired Seely to become more patriotic. Once returning to the United States, she performed at the Grand Ole Opry. In one Opry show, she commented that the [[Flag of the United States|American flag]] was not on display. Following this statement, the Opry started displaying an American flag, which still exists at the venue today.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=4}}\n[[File:Jack Greene.JPG|thumb|left|170px|For several years, Seely recorded and toured with country artist [[Jack Greene]].]]\n\nIn addition to a solo career at Decca, Seely collaborated with country artist [[Jack Greene]]. Their first release together was the single \"[[Wish I Didn't Have to Miss You]]\".<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/>{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}} A commercial success, the song reached number two on the ''Billboard'' country singles chart in early 1970.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Wish I Didn't Have to Miss You\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jack-greene/chart-history/CSI/song/837467 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The song prompted their first [[Jack Greene, Jeannie Seely|studio album]] to be issued in January 1970, which reached number 18 on the country albums list.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Jack Greene, Jeannie Seely'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jack-greene/chart-history/CLP/song/831852 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The pair later released another studio album in 1972 entitled ''[[Two for the Show (Jack Greene and Jeannie Seely album)|Two for the Show]]''. It included two singles, starting with 1971's \"[[Much Oblige]]\", which became a top twenty country hit.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Much Oblige\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jack-greene/chart-history/CSI/song/839863 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Greene and Seely's duet success led to the creation of their own traveling road show from 1969 to 1972.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|pp=302-03}} The duo toured and performed at venues ranging from [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York, New York|New York City]] to [[Wembley Stadium]] in [[London, England|London]].{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=4}} Their concerts and recording would receive recognition from several award programs. They were nominated by the [[Grammy Awards]] in 1970<ref name=\"Grammys\"/> and were nominated four times for the [[Country Music Association]]'s \"Vocal Duo of the Year\" between 1972 and 1975.<ref name=\"CMA\">{{cite web |title=Past Winners and Nominees: Jeannie Seely |url=https://cmaawards.com/past-winners-and-nominees/?appSession=9093S4929571M1IR18576495GF10XXQOHK9Q8IE3DCMYFEIWZ17E3C90JMWMD00EM851M17AYT2RLA7WU18V8EWMT89ZUJHXFQ73I8Y0Q756132V0B6HN29R170AV729 |website=[[Country Music Association Awards]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1970s, Seely's solo recordings had declined at radio. Her sixth studio album, ''[[Please Be My New Love]]'' (1970), did not receive a ''Billboard'' placement.<ref name=\"whitburn\"/> Further singles reached lower positions on the ''Billboard'' country songs chart during this time. Singles such as \"Tell Me Again\" (1970) and the self-composed \"Farm in Pennsyltucky\" (1972) did not peak past the top 50.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Farm in Pennsyltucky\" |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/837080 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\"Tell Me Again\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/840009 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> While not achieving any solo achievements, Seely's songwriting was more successful. In 1972, she composed \"Leavin' and Sayin' Goodbye\", which was recorded by [[Faron Young]].<ref name=\"Country Universe\">{{cite web |last1=Coyne |first1=Kevin John |title=100 Greatest Women, #59: Jeannie Seely |url=http://www.countryuniverse.net/2018/06/14/100-greatest-women-59-jeannie-seely/ |website=Country Universe |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Released as a single, it became a major hit when it reached number nine on the country chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Leavin' and Sayin' Goodbye\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/faron-young/chart-history/CSI/song/839166 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> Other country artists recorded her compositions during the 1970s. Among these performers was Ernest Tubb who recorded \"Sometimes I Do\". It was released as a single via First Generation Records in 1977.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ernest Tubb -- ''Sometimes I Do'' (1977, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/fr/Ernest-Tubb-Sometimes-I-Do-Half-My-Hearts-In-Texas/release/4371954 |website=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> [[Merle Haggard]] recorded \"Life of a Rodeo Cowboy\" in 1978. Seely later called it a \"great compliment\" to have Haggard cut the track.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horton |first1=Carrie |title=Jeannie Seely Recalls the Conversation That Inspired 'Life of a Rodeo Cowboy' |url=https://theboot.com/jeannie-seely-life-of-a-rodeo-cowboy-inspiration/ |website=The Boot |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeely returned to the popularity charts with solo success in 1973. Hank Cochran had reworked the traditional tune, \"May I Sleep in Your Barn Tonight\" to the country song, \"[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms]]\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} Released as a single, it became Seely's biggest solo hit in several years when it peaked at number six on the ''Billboard'' country songs list.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Can I Sleep in Your Arms\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/839619 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Cochran had also reworked the Appalachian song, \"[[Come All You Fair and Tender Ladies]]\", to the title of \"[[Lucky Ladies (song)|Lucky Ladies]]\".{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} It also became a major hit, peaking at number 11 on the country songs chart in February 1974.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Lucky Ladies\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/835669 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Her ninth studio album, ''[[Can I Sleep in Your Arms/Lucky Ladies]]'' would be released in late 1973 and reached number 15 on the Top Country Albums chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Can I Sleep in Your Arms/Lucky Ladies'' chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CLP/song/831427 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> Seely then moved to [[Columbia Records]] where she recorded for several years.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> Some music writers noticed a change in her material while at Columbia. Mary Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann called Seely's Columbia recordings to be \"spicy\" and \"franker\" than her previous work, highlighting the hits \"Take Me to Bed\" and \"We're Still in Hangin' in There Ain't We Jessi\". The latter tune documented the marital conflicts of several female country artists including [[Jessi Colter]] and [[Dottie West]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} In addition, \"Take Me to Bed\" would be her last single to date to make a ''Billboard'' chart appearance.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Take Me to Bed\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/jeannie-seely/chart-history/CSI/song/363176 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===1977\u20131989: Car accident and career slow-down===\nIn June 1977, Seely was involved in a car accident in [[Goodlettsville, Tennessee]], a suburb outside of Nashville.{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=475}}<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite news |last1=Krebbs |first1=Albin |title=Notes on People |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/06/30/archives/westchester-opinion-notes-on-people.html |accessdate=15 April 2020 |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 30, 1977}}</ref> Seely had been driving her vehicle when it crashed into a tree. She was admitted to Nashville Memorial Hospital where she was reported to be in \"fair condition\". Among her injuries, Seely suffered a fractured jaw, broken ribs,<ref name=\"NY Times\"/> a punctured lung and a collapsed lung. Upon arriving at the hospital she was given same-day surgery to repair her lung.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Indiana Gazette from Indiana Pennsylvania [title unknown] |publisher=[[Indiana Gazette]] |date=June 29, 1977}}</ref> Seely eventually recovered from her injuries<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> and later reflected on her appreciation for her life. \"You know, it sounds like a cliche, but it's true that your perspective changes when you have a close call, what you took for granted you come to appreciate more,\" Seely commented on her official website biography.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=5}} She later would credit friend Dottie West for her support during her recovery. \"Dottie was there as much as she possibly could be, helping me through that time. After I got out of the hospital and was homebound, one time, she drove me out to her place just for a change of scenery,\" she commented in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thanki |first1=Juli |title=Country Trailblazer Dottie West Remembered |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/08/26/country-trailblazer-dottie-west-remembered/88531556/ |website=[[The Tennessean]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her recovery, Seely returned to performing but was no longer signed to a recording label.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> It became more challenging for Seely to tour due to fewer concert engagements. \"The only bright spot in my life right now is a flashing neon sign...and even that comes and goes,\" she stated.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}} When opportunities were available, Seely continued to work. Among her first major engagements was a tour with [[Willie Nelson]]. Her appearances with Nelson led to an appearance on the [[Honeysuckle Rose (album)|soundtrack]] of his film ''[[Honeysuckle Rose (film)|Honeysuckle Rose]]'' (1980).<ref name=\"Country Universe\"/> Along with Hank Cochran and Nelson, she performed a collaborative version of the song \"[[Make the World Go Away]]\" for the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Honeysuckle Rose'': Willie Nelson: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/honeysuckle-rose-mw0000190231 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> In 1982, Jack Greene reunited for a [[Greatest Hits (Jack Greene and Jeannie Seely album)|studio album]] containing re-recordings of their previous hits.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Greene |first1=Jack |last2=Seely |first2=Jeannie |title=''Greatest Hits'' (Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=[[Gusto Records]] |date=1982}}</ref> Seely also looked for other music-related opportunities. In 1985, she opened up a nightclub in Nashville named \"Jeannie Seely's Country Club\". Among the venue's major events was a premier music party hosted by Seely on its opening in June 1985.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nashville Then: Best of 1985 Music |url=https://www.tennessean.com/picture-gallery/news/local/2015/12/30/nashville-then-best-of-1985-music/78080448/ |website=[[The Tennessean]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> However, in 1986 the club closed down after only a year of being open to the public.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=302}}\n[[File:Jeannie Seely (3469185223).jpg|thumb|right|170px|Seely at the Opry, 2007.]]\n\nDuring this time, Seely also became the first female Grand Opry member to host a half hour segment.<ref name=\"Digital Journal\">{{cite web |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Country queen Jeannie Seely receives honorary doctorate from LMU |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/entertainment/country-queen-jeannie-seely-receives-honorary-doctorate-from-lmu/article/563677 |website=Digital Journal |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> In 1985, she was called to replace [[Del Reeves]], who was stuck in a snowstorm.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=5}} From this point forward Seely and other female performers were provided opportunities to host the Opry.<ref name=\"Digital Journal\"/> Seely would also be a recurrent host of [[The Nashville Network]]'s ''Opry Backstage'' show, where she interviewed artists following their Opry performances. Along with the Opry, Seely also appeared on several other network programs during this time. This included appearances on ''[[Nashville Now]]'', ''[[Crook & Chase]]'', ''[[Family Feud]]'' and ''Prime Time Country''.<ref name=\"Country Universe\"/>{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=6}}\n\n===1990\u2013present: Return to recording===\nSeely returned to a more active music career in the 1990s. In 1990, she released her [[Jeannie Seely (1990 album)|eleventh studio album]], which was issued on her own recording label.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Jeannie Seely'' (Cassette Liner Notes & Album Information) |journal=Faux Paw Productions/Shadpoke Records |date=1990}}</ref> In 1993, she appeared alongside [[Stonewall Jackson (musician)|Stonewall Jackson]] in the music video for \"[[Trashy Women]]\", a song by the band [[Confederate Railroad]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Morris |first1=Edward |title=Nashville Scene |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=July 10, 1993 |page=p. 24}}</ref> When released as a single, the song reached number ten on the ''Billboard'' country songs chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Trashy Women\" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Confederate-Railroad/chart-history/CSI/song/19146 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> The following year, her first album of [[holiday music]] was released called ''[[Number One Christmas]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Number One Christmas'' -- Jeannie Seely -- Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/number-one-christmas-mw0000895262 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> While not recording or touring, Seely maintained an active presence as a Grand Ole Opry member. She also continued making regular appearances on ''The Nashville Network''.{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=6}} Seely's songwriting was also a part of her music career in the 90s. In 1997, [[Lorrie Morgan]] recorded \"I've Enjoyed as Much of This as I Can Stand\", which was composed with [[Bill Anderson (singer)|Bill Anderson]]. Morgan's version was released on her 1997 studio album, ''[[Shakin' Things Up]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Owens |first1=Thom |title=''Shakin' Things Up'' -- Lorrie Morgan -- Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/shakin-things-up-mw0000026152 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Before the end of the decade, Seely released her thirteenth studio effort, ''Been There, Sung That'' (1999). The project was self-produced and featured duets with [[T. Graham Brown]] and [[Willie Nelson]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seely |first1=Jeannie |title=''Been There...Sung That!'' (Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=Faux Paw Productions/Shadpoke Records |date=1999}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jeannie on Opry 040818.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Jeannie Seely in performance at the [[Grand Ole Opry]], 2010s.]]\nIn the early 2000's, Seely turned her attention towards [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]] projects. In 2001, she sang alongside [[Ralph Stanley]] on his studio album ''Clinch Mountain Sweethearts''. On the album, they performed the track \"I'm Ready to Go\".<ref>{{cite web |title=''Clinch Mountain Sweethearts'': Ralph Stanley: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/clinch-mountain-sweethearts-mw0000014135 |website=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Seely followed this in 2003 with the studio album ''Life's Highway''.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> The record's bluegrass and acoustic sounds received positive reviews from critics. John Lupton of ''Country Standard Time'' called it an album \"chock-full of top level bluegrass talent.\" Lupton also praised Seely's vocal performance on the album, calling it \"classic country\" and \"timeless\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lupton |first1=John |title=Jeannie Seely travels life's highways |url=https://www.countrystandardtime.com/d/article.asp?xid=734 |website=Country Standard Time |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Bob Mitchell of the ''Louisville Music News'' gave the album mostly a positive response. \"Overall, this recording lacks the earthy intensity and drive that characterizes authentic traditional Bluegrass. But, make no mistake, Life's Highway is enjoyable and features some of country and bluegrass's finest musicians,\" he wrote.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mitchell |first1=Bob |title=Keeping it Real Life's Highway (OMS) Jeannie Seely |url=http://www.louisvillemusicnews.net/webmanager/index.php?WEB_CAT_ID=50&storyid=2900&headline=Jeannie_Seely_-_Life%27s_Highway&issueid=183 |website=Louisville Music News |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 2000s, Seely continued an active touring schedule. During several summers, she held concerts at the ''[[Dollywood]]'' theme park and toured in [[Ireland]].{{sfn|Harman, Ron|Seely, Jeannie|2002|p=6}} While taking time to tour, Seely also found time to record her fifteenth studio album. In 2011, ''Vintage Country: Old But Treasured'' was released on her latest label, Cheyenne Records.<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> \"...like I always joke onstage, I\u2019m speaking about the music when I say old but treasured,\" Seely commented in a 2011 interview.<ref name=\"Nashville Music Guide\">{{cite web |title=Jeannie Seely\u2019s Vintage Country Offers Timeless Country Classics |url=https://www.nashvillemusicguide.com/jeannie-seely%E2%80%99s-vintage-country-offers-timeless-country-classics/ |website=Nashville Music Guide |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> The album was a collection of country music standards previously recorded by others. Among its songs was [[Bobbie Gentry]]'s \"[[Ode to Billie Joe]]\" and [[Billy Walker (musician)|Billy Walker]]'s \"[[Funny How Time Slips Away]]\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Titusville native Jeannie Seely releases album of country favorites |url=https://www.titusvilleherald.com/news/article_05820ff0-a7bd-50f5-a014-bd74754a24ed.html |website=Titusville Herald |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> During the 2010s, Seely's touring schedule remained busy as she performed at events including the [[CMA Music Festival]] and the R.O.P.E.'s \"Summer Spectacular\" show.<ref name=\"Nashville Music Guide\"/> She returned to recording with her sixteenth studio album, ''[[Written in Song]]'' (2017).<ref name=\"Allmusic Bio\"/> All fourteen of the album's tracks were composed by Seely and many were first recorded by other artists.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nicholson |first1=Jessica |title=Jeannie Seely Celebrates Release of \u2018Written In Song\u2019 |url=https://musicrow.com/2017/01/jeannie-seely-celebrates-release-of-written-in-song/ |website=Music Row |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Markos Papadatos of the ''Digital Journal'' gave the album an \"A\" rating in his review. \"Overall, Jeannie Seely soars on her new album, ''Written in Song''. \"Miss Country Soul\" is back stronger than ever. There is a variety on her latest musical effort.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Jeannie Seely soars on new country album ''Written in Song'' |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/review-jeannie-seely-soars-on-new-country-album-written-in-song/article/483167#ixzz6JjY2hqQm |website=Digital Journal |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn late 2019, Seely announced the release of her seventeenth studio recording called ''An American Classic''. The project will be produced by [[Don Cusic]] and wil be released on [[Curb Records]] in June 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=LMU Honors Jeannie Seely With Honorary Doctorate of Arts Degree |url=https://www.musicconnection.com/lmu-honors-jeannie-seely-honorary-doctorate-arts-degree/ |website=Music Connection |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Jeannie Seely discography}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Year''' || '''Award program''' || '''Award''' || '''Result'''\n|-\n| 1966 || [[Billboard magazine]] || ''Most Promising New Artist'' || Won\n|-\n| 1966 || [[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox magazine]] || ''Most Promising New Artist'' || Won\n|-\n| 1966 || [[Record World|Record World magazine]] || ''Most Promising New Artist'' || Won\n|-\n| 1967 || [[Grammy Awards]] || ''[[Best Female Country Vocal Performance]]'' for \"[[Don't Touch Me]]\" || Won\n|-\n| 1972 || [[CMA Awards]] || ''Vocal Duo of the Year'' (with [[Jack Greene]]) || Nominated\n|-\n| 1973 || [[CMA Awards]] || ''Vocal Duo of the Year'' (with Jack Greene) || Nominated\n|-\n| 1974 || [[CMA Awards]] || ''Vocal Duo of the Year'' (with Jack Greene) || Nominated\n|-\n| 1975 || [[CMA Awards]] || ''Vocal Duo of the Year'' (with Jack Greene) || Nominated\n|-\n| 2017 || R.O.P.E || ''Entertainer of the Year'' (with [[Gene Watson]]) || Won\n|}\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |last2=Bufwack |first2=Mary A. |title=Finding Her Voice: Women in Country Music: 1800\u20132000 |date=2003 |publisher=The Country Music Press & Vanderbilt University Press |location=Nashville, TN |isbn=0-8265-1432-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/findinghervoicew0000bufw|ref={{SfnRef|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003}} }}\n* {{cite web |author1=Seely, Jeannie |author2= Harman, Ron|year=2002|url=http://jeannieseely.com/docs/Jeannie%20Seely%20Full%20Length%20Bio.pdf|title=Biography|work=Jeannie Seely.com|accessdate=April 10, 2020|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Trott |first1=Walt |title=The Encyclopedia of Country Music |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-19-517608-7|ref={{SfnRef|Trott, Walt|2012}} }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.jeannieseely.com/}}\n* [http://www.cmt.com/artists/az/seely_jeannie/artist.jhtml Jeannie Seely at CMT.com]\n\n{{Jeannie Seely}}\n{{Grand Ole Opry}}\n{{Grand Ole Opry members}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seely, Jeannie}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female country singers]]\n[[Category:American record producers]]\n[[Category:Challenge Records artists]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Grand Ole Opry members]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Monument Records artists]]\n[[Category:People from Titusville, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "ChrisTofu11961", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1990\u2013present: Return to recording:fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeannie_Seely"}
{"title_page": "Pottassery-II", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Pottassery (disambiguation){{!}}Pottassery}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Pottassery-II\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = village\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Kerala#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Kerala, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|10|59|42|N|76|30|19|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Kerala]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Palakkad]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 10246\n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 6XXXXX\n| registration_plate      = [[List of RTO districts in India#KL.E2.80.94Kerala|KL]]-\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Pottassery-II''' is a village in the [[Palakkad district]], state of [[Kerala]], India. It is administered by the [[Tachampara (gram panchayat)|Tachampara gram panchayat]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Reports of National Panchayat Directory |publisher=Ministry of Panchayati Raj |url=http://panchayatdirectory.gov.in/adminreps/viewGPmapcvills.asp?gpcode=224721&rlbtype=V |accessdate=31 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101015040/http://panchayatdirectory.gov.in/adminreps/viewGPmapcvills.asp?gpcode=224721&rlbtype=V |archivedate=1 January 2014 }}</ref> and the [[Kanjirampuzha (gram panchayat)|Kanjirampuzha gram panchayat]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Reports of National Panchayat Directory |publisher=Ministry of Panchayati Raj |url=http://panchayatdirectory.gov.in/adminreps/viewGPmapcvills.asp?gpcode=224715&rlbtype=V |accessdate=2 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102200109/http://panchayatdirectory.gov.in/adminreps/viewGPmapcvills.asp?gpcode=224715&rlbtype=V |archivedate=2 January 2014 }}</ref> The village contains the places of Mundakkunnu, Kanjiram, and Pottassery.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]], Pottassery-II had a population of 10,246 with 4,979 males and 5,267 females.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/Village_Directory/Population_data/Population_5000_and_Above.aspx|title=Census of India : Villages with population 5000 & above|publisher=Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|accessdate=2008-12-10}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Palakkad district}}\n[[Category:Villages in Palakkad district|Pottassery-II]]\n\n\n{{Palakkad-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Pottassery (disambiguation){{!}}Pottassery}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Pottassery-II\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = village\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Kerala#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Kerala, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|10|59|42|N|76|30|19|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Kerala]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Palakkad]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 10246\n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[English language|English]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 6XXXXX\n| registration_plate      = [[List of RTO districts in India#KL.E2.80.94Kerala|KL]]-\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Pottassery-II''' is a village in the [[Palakkad district]], state of [[Kerala]], India. It is administered by the [[Tachampara (gram panchayat)|Tachampara gram panchayat]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Reports of National Panchayat Directory |publisher=Ministry of Panchayati Raj |url=http://panchayatdirectory.gov.in/adminreps/viewGPmapcvills.asp?gpcode=224721&rlbtype=V |accessdate=31 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101015040/http://panchayatdirectory.gov.in/adminreps/viewGPmapcvills.asp?gpcode=224721&rlbtype=V |archivedate=1 January 2014 }}</ref> and the [[Kanjirampuzha (gram panchayat)|Kanjirampuzha gram panchayat]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Reports of National Panchayat Directory |publisher=Ministry of Panchayati Raj |url=http://panchayatdirectory.gov.in/adminreps/viewGPmapcvills.asp?gpcode=224715&rlbtype=V |accessdate=2 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102200109/http://panchayatdirectory.gov.in/adminreps/viewGPmapcvills.asp?gpcode=224715&rlbtype=V |archivedate=2 January 2014 }}</ref>\nThe village contains the places of Mundakkunnu, Kanjiram, and Pottassery.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]], Pottassery-II had a population of 10,246 with 4,979 males and 5,267 females.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/Village_Directory/Population_data/Population_5000_and_Above.aspx|title=Census of India : Villages with population 5000 & above|publisher=Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India|accessdate=2008-12-10}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Palakkad district}}\n[[Category:Villages in Palakkad district|Pottassery-II]]\n\n\n{{Palakkad-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CJK09", "label": "safe", "comment": "spacing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pottassery-II"}
{"title_page": "Controversies about the word niggardly", "text_new": "{{pp-move-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Controversies about the word ''niggardly''}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{wiktionarypar|niggardly|niggard}}\nIn the [[United States]], there have been several '''controversies involving the word ''niggardly''''', an adjective meaning 'stingy' or 'miserly', because of its [[phonetics|phonetic]] similarity to the [[racial slur]] ''[[nigger]]''. [[Etymology|Etymologically]], the two words are unrelated. The term ''niggardly,'' arising in the [[Middle Ages]], long predates the term ''[[nigger]]'', which arose in the 16th century.<ref name=\"Pilgrim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ferris.edu/news/jimcrow/caricature/|title=Nigger and Caricatures|last=Pilgrim|first=David|date=September 2001|accessdate=June 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n''Niggardly'' (noun: ''niggard'') is an adjective meaning \"stingy\" or \"miserly\". It is derived from the [[Middle English]] word ''{{lang|enm|nigard}}'', which is probably derived from [[Old Norse]] ''{{lang|non|hn\u01ebggr}}'' (\"stingy\").<ref>Erik Bj\u00f6rkman, ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IZRMl0NXHZ8C&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=middle+english+word+nig&#v=onepage&q=middle%20english%20word%20nig&f=false Scandinavian Loan-words in Middle English]'', page 34.</ref>\n\n''Nigger'', a racial epithet in English, derives from the [[Spanish language|Spanish]]/[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] word ''{{lang|es|negro}}'', meaning \"[[black]]\", and the [[French language|French]] word ''{{lang|fr|n\u00e8gre}}''. Both ''{{lang|es|negro}}'' and ''{{lang|fr|noir}}'' (and therefore also ''{{lang|fr|n\u00e8gre}}'' and ''nigger'') ultimately come from ''{{lang|la|nigrum}}'', the [[accusative case]] singular masculine and neuter <!-- Nouns in Western Romance languages typically come from the accusative case, rather than the nominative case that we quote in English. --> form of the [[Latin]] masculine adjective ''{{lang|la|niger}}'', meaning \"black\" or \"[[dark]]\".<ref>{{cite dictionary |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/nigger |title=''Nigger'' Usage Note |dictionary=[[Dictionary.com]] |accessdate=May 17, 2015 }}</ref> Its first recorded use dates to 1574, and its first recorded derogatory use to 1775.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peterson|first1=Christopher|title=Bestial Traces: Race, Sexuality, Animality|date=2013|publisher=Fordham Univ Press|isbn=978-0-8232-4520-8|page=91|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=_Z54563cYpoC&pg=PA91#v=onepage|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Patricia T. O'Conner, Stewart Kellerman|title=Origins of the Specious: Myths and Misconceptions of the English Language|date=2010|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8129-7810-0|page=134|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=hsu47CBwJPUC&pg=PA134#v=onepage|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== David Howard incident ==\nOn January 15, 1999, David Howard, an aide to [[Anthony A. Williams]], the [[mayor]] of [[Washington, D.C.]], used \"niggardly\" in reference to a [[budget]].<ref name=\"Dowd\">{{cite news|last=Dowd|first=Maureen|title=Liberties; Niggardly City|work=The New York Times|page=17|date=January 31, 1999|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/31/opinion/liberties-niggardly-city.html}}</ref> This apparently upset one of his black colleagues, who misinterpreted it as a racial slur and lodged a complaint. As a result, on January 25, Howard tendered his resignation, and Williams accepted it.<ref name=\"washpost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/williams/williams020499.htm|title=D.C. Mayor Acted 'Hastily,' Will Rehire Aide|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=February 4, 1999}}</ref> However, after public pressure, an internal review into the matter was brought about, and the mayor offered Howard the chance to return to his position as Office of the Public Advocate on February 4. Howard refused but accepted another position with the mayor instead, insisting that he did not feel victimized by the incident. On the contrary, Howard felt that he had learned from the situation. \"I used to think it would be great if we could all be colorblind; that's na\u00efve, especially for a white person, because a white person can't {{sic}}<!-- in context, ''can'' makes more sense \u2013 since emphatic ''can'' is sometimes pronounced identically to ''can't'' in American English \u2013 IPA [k\u02b0e\u0259n] \u2013 or at least ''can't'' can sound pretty close \u2013 IPA [k\u02b0e\u0259nt\u031a] \u2013, see also https://www.reddit.com/r/linguistics/comments/7b5o89/phonology_of_can_and_cant_in_standard_american/, there's a good chance that an emphatic ''can'' was misheard and transcribed as ''can't'' here --> afford to be colorblind. They don't have to think about race every day. An African American does.\"<ref name=\"washpost\" />\n\nIt had been speculated that this incident inspired [[Philip Roth]]'s novel ''[[The Human Stain]]'',<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/969/ |title=Sight & Sound \u2013 The Human Stain (2003) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401003346/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/969 |archivedate=April 1, 2009 |first=Xan |last=Brooks |publisher=British Film Institute |date=March 2004 |accessdate=February 3, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> though Roth has stated that his source was an incident in the career of [[Sociology|sociologist]] and professor [[Melvin Tumin]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/an-open-letter-to-wikipedia |title=An Open Letter to Wikipedia |first=Philip |last=Roth |authorlink=Philip Roth |date=March 22, 2016 |magazine=The New Yorker}}</ref>\n\n=== Public response ===\nThe Howard incident led to a national debate in the U.S., in the context of racial sensitivity and [[political correctness]], on whether use of ''niggardly'' should be avoided. As [[James Poniewozik]] wrote in ''[[Salon.com|Salon]]'', the controversy was \"an issue that opinion-makers right, left and center could universally agree on.\" He wrote that \"the defenders of the [[dictionary]]\" were \"[[wiktionary:legion|legion]], and still queued up six [[wiktionary:abreast|abreast]]\".<ref name=jp>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/1999/02/02/poni_8/|title=The little N-word|work=[[Salon.com]]|accessdate=March 20, 2014|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=February 2, 1999}}</ref> [[Julian Bond]], then chairman of the [[NAACP|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]], deplored the offense that had been taken at Howard's use of the word. \"You hate to think you have to censor your language to meet other people's lack of understanding\", he said. \"David Howard should not have quit. Mayor Williams should bring him back\u2014and order dictionaries issued to all staff who need them.\"<ref>Demarco, Donald, \"Acting Niggardly\", article reprinted at the ''Catholic Education Resource Center'' Web site, which states the article originally appeared in ''Social Justice Review'' 91, no. 3\u20134 (March\u2013April 2000): 45\u201348; the article cites ''The Washington Post'', January 29, 1999, page A24, Web page accessed March 15, 2007</ref> Bond also said, \"Seems to me the mayor has been niggardly in his judgment on the issue\" and that as a nation the US has a \"hair-trigger sensibility\" on race that can be tripped by both real and false grievances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GXcfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Ky8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6910,3749147&dq=hair-trigger-sensibility|title=NAACP official calls word flap overreaction|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|publisher=Associated Press|date=January 29, 1999|accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison incident ==\nShortly after the Washington incident, another controversy erupted over the use of the word at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]. At a February 1999 meeting of the Faculty Senate, Amelia Rideau, a junior English major and vice chairwoman of the Black Student Union told the group how a professor teaching [[Chaucer]] had used the word ''niggardly''. She later said she was unaware of the related Washington, D.C., controversy that had come to light the week before. She said the professor continued to use the word even after she told him that she was offended. \"I was in tears, shaking,\" she told the faculty. \"It's not up to the rest of the class to decide whether my feelings are valid.\"<ref name=kors>{{cite magazine|url=http://reason.com/archives/1999/07/01/cracking-the-speech-code|title=Cracking the speech code|magazine=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|author=[[Alan Charles Kors]]|date=July 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe student's plea, offered as evidence in support of the school's [[speech code]], instead struck an unintended chord helping to destroy it. \"Many 'abolitionists', as they now were called, believe that [the student's] speech, widely reported, was the turning point,\" according to an article in ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine. An editorial in the ''[[Wisconsin State Journal]]'' addressed the student who complained, saying: \"Thank you [...] for clarifying precisely why the UW\u2013Madison does not need an academic speech code. [...] Speech codes have a chilling effect on academic freedom and they reinforce defensiveness among students who ought to be more open to learning.\"<ref name=kors />\n\n== Wilmington, North Carolina incident ==\nIn late January or early February 2002, a white fourth-grade teacher in [[Wilmington, North Carolina]], was formally reprimanded for teaching the word and told to attend sensitivity training.<ref name=adv>{{cite web|url=http://www.starnewsonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?Site=WM&Date=20020904&Category=NEWS&ArtNo=209040302&Ref=AR&Profile=1004&template=printart|title=Teacher reprimanded for word choice|publisher=[[Wilmington Star-News]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=September 4, 2002}}</ref> The teacher, Stephanie Bell, said she used \"niggardly\" during a discussion about literary characters. Parent Akwana Walker, who is black, protested the use of the word, saying it offended her.<ref name=adv />\n\nBell's teacher's association, the [[North Carolina Association of Educators]], told her not to speak about the situation, so her son spoke to the newspaper, saying that his mother received a letter from the school principal stating that the teacher used poor judgment and instructing her to send an apology to the parents of her students, which was done. The principal's letter also criticized the teacher for lacking sensitivity.<ref name=adv /> The daughter of the complaining parent was moved to another classroom.\n\nNorm Shearin, the deputy superintendent of schools for the district, said the teacher made a bad decision by teaching the word because it was inappropriate for that grade level.<ref name=adv />\n\n== Mendocino County, California incident ==\nIn early 2009,<ref name=\"Ukiah Daily Journal\">{{cite news |last1=Stark |first1=Monica|title=Judge finds for school district in niggardly\" lawsuit |url=https://www.ukiahdailyjournal.com/2010/07/07/judge-finds-for-school-district-in-niggardly-lawsuit/ |newspaper=The Ukiah Daily Journal |date=7 July 2010}}</ref> Dennis Boaz, a history teacher, sued the administrators of the [[Mendocino County]] Office of Education for [[defamation]]. Boaz, who was bargaining for [[Ukiah, California|Ukiah]] schoolteachers, wrote a letter saying that the \"tenor of the negotiation tactics of the district office has become increasingly negative and niggardly.\" The response was a memo from one defendant of the lawsuit that implied that Boaz was racist, and a letter cosigned by the other defendant and nine other individuals in the Mendocino County school system stating that Boaz's comments were \"racially charged and show a complete lack of respect and integrity toward Dr. Nash, Ukiah Unified District Superintendent,\" who is a black woman.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stark |first1=Monica|url=https://www.ukiahdailyjournal.com/2009/10/14/uproar-over-word-choice-results-in-lawsuit-by-ukiah-teacher/|title=Uproar over word choice results in lawsuit by Ukiah teacher|newspaper=Ukiah Daily Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=14 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Other complaints ==\n=== Letter to ''The Economist'' magazine, 1995 ===\nIn 1995, London-based magazine ''[[The Economist]]'' used the word \"niggardly\" in an article about the impact of computers and productivity: \"During the 1980s, when service industries consumed about 85% of the $1 trillion invested in I.T. in the United States, productivity growth averaged a niggardly 0.8% a year.\" ''The Economist'' later pointed out with amusement that it received a letter from a reader in Boston who thought the word \"niggardly\" was inappropriate. \"Why do we get such letters only from America?\" the British magazine commented.<ref name=jd>{{cite magazine|url=http://old.nationalreview.com/derbyshire/derbyshire091702.asp|title=Niggling doubts|magazine=[[National Review Online]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|last=Derbyshire|first=John|date=September 17, 2002|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502072428/http://old.nationalreview.com/derbyshire/derbyshire091702.asp|archivedate=May 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Dallas Morning News'' ===\nAt some point before the Washington, D.C., incident (of early 1999), ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' had banned the use of the word after its use in a restaurant review had raised complaints.<ref name=jp /><ref>\"Even before the Washington incident, the ''Dallas Morning News'' had ixnayed the word after its use in a restaurant review raised ire.\"</ref>\n\n=== Acampo, California ===\nOn March 31, 2010, a [[billboard]] appeared along the frontage of [[California State Route 99]] in [[Acampo, California]], that referred to [[Barack Obama]], the first black [[President of the United States]], as \"niggardly\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fox40.com/news/headlines/ktxl-news-obamasign0331,0,1047633.story|title='Niggardly Obama' Billboard Generates Outrage In Acampo|first=Matthew|last=Keys|work=fox40.com|date=March 31, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318151315/http://www.fox40.com/news/headlines/ktxl-news-obamasign0331%2C0%2C1047633.story|archivedate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> The sign was placed among several billboards advertising a local coffee shop that was going out of business that week. The restaurant's owner stated that they were unaware of the Obama sign until contacted by a local news station. The sign was removed shortly after news reports about it appeared on local television stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news10.net/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=78454|title=Acampo anti-Obama sign taken down|first=James|last=Scullary|work=news10.net|date=March 31, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607083702/http://www.news10.net/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=78454|archive-date=June 7, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Broward County, Florida ===\nIn November 2011, a [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] drug counsellor was fired and another suspended for an incident in which the word \"niggardly\" was used. A substance-abuse client filed a complaint saying a counsellor called him \"niggardly dumb\" in a June meeting with two workers at a county rehab center. In an investigative report, the county's professional standards office found the workers, who are both white, engaged in \"unprofessional, unethical and discriminatory\" behavior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/columnists/fl-niggardly-mayocol-b110811-20111107,0,488452.column|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130203210120/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/columnists/fl-niggardly-mayocol-b110811-20111107,0,488452.column|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 3, 2013|title=Is using this N-word (niggardly) a firing offense?|first=Michael|last=Mayo|work=sun-sentinel.com|date=November 11, 2011|accessdate=November 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Publicity and racial use ==\nThe public controversies caused some commentators to speculate that \"niggardly\" would be used more often, both in its correct sense and as fodder for humor, as a racist [[Code word (figure of speech)|code word]], or both.\n\n\"The word's new lease of life is probably among manufacturers and retailers of sophomoric humor,\" wrote [[John Derbyshire]], a conservative commentator, in 2002. \"I bet that even as I write, some adolescent boys, in the stairwell of some high school somewhere in America, are accusing each other of being niggardly, and sniggering at their own outrageous wit. I bet ... Wait a minute. 'Sniggering'? Oh, my God. ...\"<ref name=jd /> Derbyshire wrote that although he loved to use words that are sometimes considered obscure, he would not use the word among black people, especially among less-educated black people, out of politeness and to avoid causing someone to feel uncomfortable, regardless of any non-racial meanings he would intend.<ref name=jd />\n\nShortly after the Washington, D.C., incident, [[James Poniewozik]] wrote in his column at ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' online magazine that some were already using \"niggardly\" in a way that made their motives ambiguous. He quoted a posting by a user from a reader forum at the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' website \"who just happened to use 'niggardly'\u2014linguistically correctly\" in commenting on two witnesses to a Congressional investigation:<ref name=jp />\n\n{{quote|[[Betty Currie|B. Curry]] [sic] got a pc pass because her testimony like that of all Clintonistas was niggardly with the truth. It is predictable that [[Vernon Jordan|V. Jordan]] will have his opportunity to be equally niggardly in this regard. Witnesses? A woman (child), a negro, and a jew\u2014very PC indeed!}}\n\n\"You can't say [the commenter]\u2014white, black or [[Klingon]] for all I know\u2014had racist motives. And you can't exactly not say it,\" Poniewozik wrote. He expected a number of \"[[Pinhead|pinheads]]\" to be asking \"black waitresses not to be 'niggardly' with the coffee\".<ref name=jp /> But there would be a different reaction in polite company, especially in racially diverse company, so the word would probably be thought of only when people think of racial epithets. \"In theory, you, I and the columnist next door will defend to the death our right to say 'niggardly.' But in practice, will we use it?\"<ref name=jp />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Tar-Baby]], a term with a benign usage that has also been perceived as a racial slur\n*[[Water buffalo incident]], a similar controversy involving remarks regarded as racist\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Politics and race in the United States|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:English words and phrases|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:African-American-related controversies|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:Connotation|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:English words|Niggardly]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Controversies about the word ''niggardly''}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{wiktionarypar|niggardly|niggard}}\nIn the United States, there have been several '''controversies involving the word ''niggardly''''', an adjective meaning 'stingy' or 'miserly', because of its [[phonetics|phonetic]] similarity to the [[racial slur]] ''[[nigger]]''. [[Etymology|Etymologically]], the two words are unrelated. The term ''niggardly,'' arising in the [[Middle Ages]], long predates the term ''nigger'', which arose in the 16th century.<ref name=\"Pilgrim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ferris.edu/news/jimcrow/caricature/|title=Nigger and Caricatures|last=Pilgrim|first=David|date=September 2001|accessdate=June 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n''Niggardly'' (noun: ''niggard'') is an adjective meaning \"stingy\" or \"miserly\". It is derived from the [[Middle English]] word ''{{lang|enm|nigard}}'', which is probably derived from [[Old Norse]] ''{{lang|non|hn\u01ebggr}}'' (\"stingy\").<ref>Erik Bj\u00f6rkman, ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IZRMl0NXHZ8C&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=middle+english+word+nig&#v=onepage&q=middle%20english%20word%20nig&f=false Scandinavian Loan-words in Middle English]'', page 34.</ref>\n\n''[[Nigger]]'', a racial epithet in English, derives from the [[Spanish language|Spanish]]/[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] word ''{{lang|es|negro}}'', meaning \"[[black]]\", and the [[French language|French]] word ''{{lang|fr|n\u00e8gre}}''. Both ''{{lang|es|negro}}'' and ''{{lang|fr|noir}}'' (and therefore also ''{{lang|fr|n\u00e8gre}}'' and ''nigger'') ultimately come from ''{{lang|la|nigrum}}'', the [[accusative case]] singular masculine and neuter <!-- Nouns in Western Romance languages typically come from the accusative case, rather than the nominative case that we quote in English. --> form of the [[Latin]] masculine adjective ''{{lang|la|niger}}'', meaning \"black\" or \"[[dark]]\".<ref>{{cite dictionary |url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/nigger |title=''Nigger'' Usage Note |dictionary=[[Dictionary.com]] |accessdate=May 17, 2015 }}</ref> Its first recorded use dates to 1574, and its first recorded derogatory use to 1775.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peterson|first1=Christopher|title=Bestial Traces: Race, Sexuality, Animality|date=2013|publisher=Fordham Univ Press|isbn=978-0-8232-4520-8|page=91|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=_Z54563cYpoC&pg=PA91#v=onepage|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Patricia T. O'Conner, Stewart Kellerman|title=Origins of the Specious: Myths and Misconceptions of the English Language|date=2010|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8129-7810-0|page=134|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=hsu47CBwJPUC&pg=PA134#v=onepage|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== David Howard incident ==\nOn January 15, 1999, David Howard, an aide to [[Anthony A. Williams]], the mayor of [[Washington, D.C.]], used \"niggardly\" in reference to a budget.<ref name=\"Dowd\">{{cite news|last=Dowd|first=Maureen|title=Liberties; Niggardly City|work=The New York Times|page=17|date=January 31, 1999|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/31/opinion/liberties-niggardly-city.html}}</ref> This apparently upset one of his black colleagues, who misinterpreted it as a racial slur and lodged a complaint. As a result, on January 25, Howard tendered his resignation, and Williams accepted it.<ref name=\"washpost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/williams/williams020499.htm|title=D.C. Mayor Acted 'Hastily,' Will Rehire Aide|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=February 4, 1999}}</ref> However, after public pressure, an internal review into the matter was brought about, and the mayor offered Howard the chance to return to his position as Office of the Public Advocate on February 4. Howard refused but accepted another position with the mayor instead, insisting that he did not feel victimized by the incident. On the contrary, Howard felt that he had learned from the situation. \"I used to think it would be great if we could all be colorblind; that's na\u00efve, especially for a white person, because a white person can't {{sic}}<!-- in context, ''can'' makes more sense \u2013 since emphatic ''can'' is sometimes pronounced identically to ''can't'' in American English \u2013 IPA [k\u02b0e\u0259n] \u2013 or at least ''can't'' can sound pretty close \u2013 IPA [k\u02b0e\u0259nt\u031a] \u2013, see also https://www.reddit.com/r/linguistics/comments/7b5o89/phonology_of_can_and_cant_in_standard_american/, there's a good chance that an emphatic ''can'' was misheard and transcribed as ''can't'' here --> afford to be colorblind. They don't have to think about race every day. An African American does.\"<ref name=\"washpost\" />\n\nIt had been speculated that this incident inspired [[Philip Roth]]'s novel ''[[The Human Stain]]'',<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/969/ |title=Sight & Sound \u2013 The Human Stain (2003) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401003346/http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/969 |archivedate=April 1, 2009 |first=Xan |last=Brooks |publisher=British Film Institute |date=March 2004 |accessdate=February 3, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> though Roth has stated that his source was an incident in the career of sociologist and professor [[Melvin Tumin]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/an-open-letter-to-wikipedia |title=An Open Letter to Wikipedia |first=Philip |last=Roth |authorlink=Philip Roth |date=March 22, 2016 |magazine=The New Yorker}}</ref>\n\n=== Public response ===\nThe Howard incident led to a national debate in the U.S., in the context of racial sensitivity and [[political correctness]], on whether use of ''niggardly'' should be avoided. As [[James Poniewozik]] wrote in ''[[Salon.com|Salon]]'', the controversy was \"an issue that opinion-makers right, left and center could universally agree on.\" He wrote that \"the defenders of the dictionary\" were \"legion, and still queued up six abreast\".<ref name=jp>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/1999/02/02/poni_8/|title=The little N-word|work=[[Salon.com]]|accessdate=March 20, 2014|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=February 2, 1999}}</ref> [[Julian Bond]], then chairman of the [[NAACP|National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]], deplored the offense that had been taken at Howard's use of the word. \"You hate to think you have to censor your language to meet other people's lack of understanding\", he said. \"David Howard should not have quit. Mayor Williams should bring him back\u2014and order dictionaries issued to all staff who need them.\"<ref>Demarco, Donald, \"Acting Niggardly\", article reprinted at the ''Catholic Education Resource Center'' Web site, which states the article originally appeared in ''Social Justice Review'' 91, no. 3\u20134 (March\u2013April 2000): 45\u201348; the article cites ''The Washington Post'', January 29, 1999, page A24, Web page accessed March 15, 2007</ref> Bond also said, \"Seems to me the mayor has been niggardly in his judgment on the issue\" and that as a nation the US has a \"hair-trigger sensibility\" on race that can be tripped by both real and false grievances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GXcfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Ky8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6910,3749147&dq=hair-trigger-sensibility|title=NAACP official calls word flap overreaction|work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel|publisher=Associated Press|date=January 29, 1999|accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison incident ==\nShortly after the Washington incident, another controversy erupted over the use of the word at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]. At a February 1999 meeting of the Faculty Senate, Amelia Rideau, a junior English major and vice chairwoman of the Black Student Union told the group how a professor teaching [[Chaucer]] had used the word ''niggardly''. She later said she was unaware of the related Washington, D.C., controversy that had come to light the week before. She said the professor continued to use the word even after she told him that she was offended. \"I was in tears, shaking,\" she told the faculty. \"It's not up to the rest of the class to decide whether my feelings are valid.\"<ref name=kors>{{cite magazine|url=http://reason.com/archives/1999/07/01/cracking-the-speech-code|title=Cracking the speech code|magazine=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|author=[[Alan Charles Kors]]|date=July 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe student's plea, offered as evidence in support of the school's [[speech code]], instead struck an unintended chord helping to destroy it. \"Many 'abolitionists', as they now were called, believe that [the student's] speech, widely reported, was the turning point,\" according to an article in ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine. An editorial in the ''[[Wisconsin State Journal]]'' addressed the student who complained, saying: \"Thank you [...] for clarifying precisely why the UW\u2013Madison does not need an academic speech code. [...] Speech codes have a chilling effect on academic freedom and they reinforce defensiveness among students who ought to be more open to learning.\"<ref name=kors />\n\n== Wilmington, North Carolina incident ==\nIn late January or early February 2002, a white fourth-grade teacher in [[Wilmington, North Carolina]], was formally reprimanded for teaching the word and told to attend sensitivity training.<ref name=adv>{{cite web|url=http://www.starnewsonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?Site=WM&Date=20020904&Category=NEWS&ArtNo=209040302&Ref=AR&Profile=1004&template=printart|title=Teacher reprimanded for word choice|publisher=[[Wilmington Star-News]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=September 4, 2002}}</ref> The teacher, Stephanie Bell, said she used \"niggardly\" during a discussion about literary characters. Parent Akwana Walker, who is black, protested the use of the word, saying it offended her.<ref name=adv />\n\nBell's teacher's association, the [[North Carolina Association of Educators]], told her not to speak about the situation, so her son spoke to the newspaper, saying that his mother received a letter from the school principal stating that the teacher used poor judgment and instructing her to send an apology to the parents of her students, which was done. The principal's letter also criticized the teacher for lacking sensitivity.<ref name=adv /> The daughter of the complaining parent was moved to another classroom.\n\nNorm Shearin, the deputy superintendent of schools for the district, said the teacher made a bad decision by teaching the word because it was inappropriate for that grade level.<ref name=adv />\n\n== Mendocino County, California incident ==\nIn early 2009,<ref name=\"Ukiah Daily Journal\">{{cite news |last1=Stark |first1=Monica|title=Judge finds for school district in niggardly\" lawsuit |url=https://www.ukiahdailyjournal.com/2010/07/07/judge-finds-for-school-district-in-niggardly-lawsuit/ |newspaper=The Ukiah Daily Journal |date=7 July 2010}}</ref> Dennis Boaz, a history teacher, sued the administrators of the [[Mendocino County]] Office of Education for [[defamation]]. Boaz, who was bargaining for [[Ukiah, California|Ukiah]] schoolteachers, wrote a letter saying that the \"tenor of the negotiation tactics of the district office has become increasingly negative and niggardly.\" The response was a memo from one defendant of the lawsuit that implied that Boaz was racist, and a letter cosigned by the other defendant and nine other individuals in the Mendocino County school system stating that Boaz's comments were \"racially charged and show a complete lack of respect and integrity toward Dr. Nash, Ukiah Unified District Superintendent,\" who is a black woman.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stark |first1=Monica|url=https://www.ukiahdailyjournal.com/2009/10/14/uproar-over-word-choice-results-in-lawsuit-by-ukiah-teacher/|title=Uproar over word choice results in lawsuit by Ukiah teacher|newspaper=Ukiah Daily Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2009|date=14 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Other complaints ==\n=== Letter to ''The Economist'' magazine, 1995 ===\nIn 1995, London-based magazine ''[[The Economist]]'' used the word \"niggardly\" in an article about the impact of computers and productivity: \"During the 1980s, when service industries consumed about 85% of the $1 trillion invested in I.T. in the United States, productivity growth averaged a niggardly 0.8% a year.\" ''The Economist'' later pointed out with amusement that it received a letter from a reader in Boston who thought the word \"niggardly\" was inappropriate. \"Why do we get such letters only from America?\" the British magazine commented.<ref name=jd>{{cite magazine|url=http://old.nationalreview.com/derbyshire/derbyshire091702.asp|title=Niggling doubts|magazine=[[National Review Online]]|accessdate=October 25, 2009|last=Derbyshire|first=John|date=September 17, 2002|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502072428/http://old.nationalreview.com/derbyshire/derbyshire091702.asp|archivedate=May 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Dallas Morning News'' ===\nAt some point before the Washington, D.C., incident (of early 1999), ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' had banned the use of the word after its use in a restaurant review had raised complaints.<ref name=jp /><ref>\"Even before the Washington incident, the ''Dallas Morning News'' had ixnayed the word after its use in a restaurant review raised ire.\"</ref>\n\n=== Acampo, California ===\nOn March 31, 2010, a billboard appeared along the frontage of [[California State Route 99]] in [[Acampo, California]], that referred to [[Barack Obama]], the first black [[President of the United States]], as \"niggardly\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fox40.com/news/headlines/ktxl-news-obamasign0331,0,1047633.story|title='Niggardly Obama' Billboard Generates Outrage In Acampo|first=Matthew|last=Keys|work=fox40.com|date=March 31, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318151315/http://www.fox40.com/news/headlines/ktxl-news-obamasign0331%2C0%2C1047633.story|archivedate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> The sign was placed among several billboards advertising a local coffee shop that was going out of business that week. The restaurant's owner stated that they were unaware of the Obama sign until contacted by a local news station. The sign was removed shortly after news reports about it appeared on local television stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news10.net/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=78454|title=Acampo anti-Obama sign taken down|first=James|last=Scullary|work=news10.net|date=March 31, 2010|accessdate=July 15, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607083702/http://www.news10.net/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=78454|archive-date=June 7, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Broward County, Florida ===\nIn November 2011, a [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] drug counsellor was fired and another suspended for an incident in which the word \"niggardly\" was used. A substance-abuse client filed a complaint saying a counsellor called him \"niggardly dumb\" in a June meeting with two workers at a county rehab center. In an investigative report, the county's professional standards office found the workers, who are both white, engaged in \"unprofessional, unethical and discriminatory\" behavior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/columnists/fl-niggardly-mayocol-b110811-20111107,0,488452.column|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130203210120/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/columnists/fl-niggardly-mayocol-b110811-20111107,0,488452.column|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 3, 2013|title=Is using this N-word (niggardly) a firing offense?|first=Michael|last=Mayo|work=sun-sentinel.com|date=November 11, 2011|accessdate=November 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Publicity and racial use ==\nThe public controversies caused some commentators to speculate that \"niggardly\" would be used more often, both in its correct sense and as fodder for humor, as a racist [[Code word (figure of speech)|code word]], or both.\n\n\"The word's new lease of life is probably among manufacturers and retailers of sophomoric humor,\" wrote [[John Derbyshire]], a conservative commentator, in 2002. \"I bet that even as I write, some adolescent boys, in the stairwell of some high school somewhere in America, are accusing each other of being niggardly, and sniggering at their own outrageous wit. I bet ... Wait a minute. 'Sniggering'? Oh, my God. ...\"<ref name=jd /> Derbyshire wrote that although he loved to use words that are sometimes considered obscure, he would not use the word among black people, especially among less-educated black people, out of politeness and to avoid causing someone to feel uncomfortable, regardless of any non-racial meanings he would intend.<ref name=jd />\n\nShortly after the Washington, D.C., incident, [[James Poniewozik]] wrote in his column at ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' online magazine that some were already using \"niggardly\" in a way that made their motives ambiguous. He quoted a posting by a user from a reader forum at the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' website \"who just happened to use 'niggardly'\u2014linguistically correctly\" in commenting on two witnesses to a Congressional investigation:<ref name=jp />\n\n{{quote|[[Betty Currie|B. Curry]] [sic] got a pc pass because her testimony like that of all Clintonistas was niggardly with the truth. It is predictable that [[Vernon Jordan|V. Jordan]] will have his opportunity to be equally niggardly in this regard. Witnesses? A woman (child), a negro, and a jew\u2014very PC indeed!}}\n\n\"You can't say [the commenter]\u2014white, black or [[Klingon]] for all I know\u2014had racist motives. And you can't exactly not say it,\" Poniewozik wrote. He expected a number of \"pinheads\" to be asking \"black waitresses not to be 'niggardly' with the coffee\".<ref name=jp /> But there would be a different reaction in polite company, especially in racially diverse company, so the word would probably be thought of only when people think of racial epithets. \"In theory, you, I and the columnist next door will defend to the death our right to say 'niggardly.' But in practice, will we use it?\"<ref name=jp />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Tar-Baby]], a term with a benign usage that has also been perceived as a racial slur\n*[[Water buffalo incident]], a similar controversy involving remarks regarded as racist\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Politics and race in the United States|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:English words and phrases|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:African-American-related controversies|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:Connotation|Niggardly]]\n[[Category:English words|Niggardly]]\n", "name_user": "Likebeingawesome", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added links so that readers can understand topics mentioned in the article if they do not know the topic)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Controversies_about_the_word_niggardly"}
{"title_page": "Baron Killanin", "text_new": "[[Image:1stLordKillanin.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Michael Morris, 1st Baron Killanin]]\n'''Baron Killanin''', of Galway in the County of Galway, is a title in the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom]]. It was created in 1900 for the Irish lawyer and politician [[Michael Morris, 1st Baron Killanin|Michael Morris, Baron Morris]], [[Lord Chief Justice of Ireland]] from 1887 to 1889 and a [[Lords of Appeal in Ordinary|Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]] from 1889 to 1900. He had already been created a '''Baronet''' in the [[Baronetage of the United Kingdom]] in 1885, and a [[life peer]] under the [[Appellate Jurisdiction Act 1876]] as '''Baron Morris''', of Spiddal in the County of Galway, in 1889. On his death in 1901 the life peerage became extinct while he was succeeded in the baronetcy and hereditary barony by his eldest son, the second Baron. He briefly represented [[Galway Borough (UK Parliament constituency)|Galway Borough]] in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] as a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] and also served as [[Lord Lieutenant of County Galway]] from 1918 to 1922. He was succeeded by his nephew, the third Baron, the son of [[George Henry Morris]]. He was a prominent author, journalist and sports official and served as President of the [[International Olympic Committee]] from between 1972 and 1980. {{As of|2017}} the titles are held by his eldest son, the fourth Baron, who succeeded in 1999. He is a film producer.\n\n== Barons Killanin (1900) ==\n* [[Michael Morris, 1st Baron Killanin]] (1826\u20131901)\n* [[Martin Morris, 2nd Baron Killanin|Martin Henry Fitzpatrick Morris, 2nd Baron Killanin]] (1867\u20131927)\n* [[Michael Morris, 3rd Baron Killanin]] (1914\u20131999)\n* [[Red Morris, 4th Baron Killanin|(George) Redmond (Fitzpatrick) Morris, 4th Baron Killanin]] (b. 1947)\n\nThe [[heir apparent]] is the present holder's son the Hon. Luke Michael Geoffrey Morris (b. 1975)\n\n===Line of Succession===\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''Michael Morris, Baron Morris, 1st Baron Killanin (1826\u20141901)''<ref>http://www.thepeerage.com/p23192.htm#i231911</ref>\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''Martin Henry FitzPatrick Morris, 2nd Baron Killanin (1867\u20141927)''\n** ''Lt.-Col. Hon. George Henry Morris (1872\u20141914)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''Michael Morris, 3rd Baron Killanin (1914\u20141999)''\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] '''George Redmond FitzPatrick Morris, 4th Baron Killanin''' (b. 1947)\n***** '''(1)''' ''Hon.'' Luke Michael Geoffrey Morris (b. 1975)\n**** '''(2)''' ''Hon.'' Michael Francis Leo Morris (b. 1951)\n***** '''(3)''' James Michael Morris (b. 1983)\n***** '''(4)''' Christopher Michael Morris (b. 1985)\n**** '''(5)''' ''Hon.'' John Martin Morris (b. 1951)\n***** '''(6)''' Roderic Michael Morris (b. 1976)\n***** '''(7)''' Michael-John Morris (b. 1979)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}\n* {{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n{{Extant Barons of the United Kingdom}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Killanin}}\n[[Category:Baronies in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:1stLordKillanin.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Michael Morris, 1st Baron Killanin]]\n'''Baron Killanin''', of Galway in the County of Galway, is a title in the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom]]. It was created in 1900 for the Irish lawyer and politician [[Michael Morris, 1st Baron Killanin|Michael Morris, Baron Morris]], [[Lord Chief Justice of Ireland]] from 1887 to 1889 and a [[Lords of Appeal in Ordinary|Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]] from 1889 to 1900. He had already been created a '''Baronet''' in the [[Baronetage of the United Kingdom]] in 1885, and a [[life peer]] under the [[Appellate Jurisdiction Act 1876]] as '''Baron Morris''', of Spiddal in the County of Galway, in 1889. On his death in 1901 the life peerage became extinct while he was succeeded in the baronetcy and hereditary barony by his eldest son, the second Baron. He briefly represented [[Galway Borough (UK Parliament constituency)|Galway Borough]] in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] as a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] and also served as [[Lord Lieutenant of County Galway]] from 1918 to 1922. He was succeeded by his nephew, the third Baron, the son of [[George Henry Morris]]. He was a prominent author, journalist and sports official and served as President of the [[International Olympic Committee]] from between 1972 and 1980. {{As of|2017}} the titles are held by his eldest son, the fourth Baron, who succeeded in 1999. He is a film producer.\n\n== Barons Killanin (1900) ==\n* [[Michael Morris, 1st Baron Killanin]] (1826\u20131901)\n* [[Martin Morris, 2nd Baron Killanin|Martin Henry Fitzpatrick Morris, 2nd Baron Killanin]] (1867\u20131927)\n* [[Michael Morris, 3rd Baron Killanin]] (1914\u20131999)\n* [[Red Morris, 4th Baron Killanin|(George) Redmond (Fitzpatrick) Morris, 4th Baron Killanin]] (b. 1947)\n\nThe [[heir apparent]] is the present holder's son the Hon. Luke Michael Geoffrey Morris (b. 1975)\n\n===Line of Succession===\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''Michael Morris, Baron Morris, 1st Baron Killanin (1826\u20141901)''<ref>http://www.thepeerage.com/p23192.htm#i231911</ref>\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''Martin Henry FitzPatrick Morris, 2nd Baron Killanin (1867\u20141927)''\n** ''Lt.-Col. Hon. George Henry Morris (1872\u20141914)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''Michael Morris, 3rd Baron Killanin (1914\u20141999)''\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] '''George Redmond FitzPatrick Morris, 4th Baron Killanin''' (b. 1947)\n***** '''(1)''' ''Hon.'' Luke Michael Geoffrey Morris (b. 1975)\n**** '''(2)''' ''Hon.'' Michael Francis Leo Morris (b. 1951)\n***** '''(3)''' James Michael Morris (b. 1983)\n***** '''(4)''' Christopher Michael Morris (b. 1985)\n**** '''(5)''' ''Hon.'' John Martin Morris (b. 1951)\n***** '''(6)''' Roderic Michael Morris (b. 1976)\n***** '''(7)''' Michael-John Morris (b. 1979)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{unreferenced|date=February 2013}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* Kidd, Charles, Williamson, David (editors). ''Debrett's Peerage and Baronetage'' (1990 edition). New York: St Martin's Press, 1990, {{Page needed |date=February 2013}}\n* {{Rayment|date=February 2012}}\n{{Extant Barons of the United Kingdom}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Killanin}}\n[[Category:Baronies in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Cerebellum", "label": "safe", "comment": "mistagged article - it has sources.you can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baron_Killanin"}
